WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.540
[Amit Varma]: Ever since I heard The Grateful Dead, I've thought of trucking as something kind of romantic,

00:00:10.540 --> 00:00:13.060
[Amit Varma]: and yet it's also deeply poignant.

00:00:13.060 --> 00:00:18.220
[Amit Varma]: On the one hand, the wide open highways, meeting new people, seeing new places, a kind of freedom

00:00:18.220 --> 00:00:21.100
[Amit Varma]: from the fetters that tie down most of us.

00:00:21.100 --> 00:00:25.660
[Amit Varma]: On the other hand, a life without roots, no sense of family, traveling all over, yes,

00:00:25.660 --> 00:00:28.220
[Amit Varma]: but constrained in a box with wheels.

00:00:28.220 --> 00:00:32.620
[Amit Varma]: You'd think truckers in India would know this vast and beautiful land more than most of

00:00:32.620 --> 00:00:33.620
[Amit Varma]: us.

00:00:33.620 --> 00:00:38.060
[Amit Varma]: But do they spend their time traveling in a moving cocoon, always on the move, yes,

00:00:38.060 --> 00:00:40.140
[Amit Varma]: but perennially trapped?

00:00:40.140 --> 00:00:48.540
[Amit Varma]: For a trucker, the journey is the destination, and that's usually a bug and not a feature.

00:00:48.540 --> 00:00:53.940
[Unknown]: Welcome to The Seen and The Unseen, our weekly podcast on economics, politics, and behavioral

00:00:53.940 --> 00:00:54.940
[Unknown]: science.

00:00:54.940 --> 00:01:01.420
[Amit Varma]: Please welcome your host, Amit Varma.

00:01:01.420 --> 00:01:02.420
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to The Seen and The Unseen.

00:01:02.420 --> 00:01:07.500
[Amit Varma]: My guest today is Rajat Ubekar, who got this strange kida a few years ago of traveling

00:01:07.500 --> 00:01:10.620
[Amit Varma]: around India in a truck, and that's exactly what he did.

00:01:10.620 --> 00:01:15.300
[Amit Varma]: He went from Mumbai to Kashmir, and then to the Northeast, and then to South India, hitchhiking

00:01:15.300 --> 00:01:20.340
[Amit Varma]: on trucks, making friends with truck drivers, getting a sense of their lives and journeys.

00:01:20.340 --> 00:01:25.060
[Amit Varma]: And he wrote about it in a wonderful book called Truck Day India, A Hitchhiker's Guide

00:01:25.060 --> 00:01:26.060
[Amit Varma]: to Hindustan.

00:01:26.060 --> 00:01:30.380
[Amit Varma]: I was delighted to have Rajat on The Seen and The Unseen as we battled through a litany

00:01:30.380 --> 00:01:34.140
[Amit Varma]: of technical issues, as if we were recording from a moving truck.

00:01:34.140 --> 00:01:40.060
[Amit Varma]: When I record remotely, I do so using a software called Zencastr, and I also keep Zoom on mute

00:01:40.060 --> 00:01:44.020
[Amit Varma]: so my guests and I can see each other and pick up visual cues.

00:01:44.020 --> 00:01:48.440
[Amit Varma]: For this recording, first Zencastr didn't work, and then it did, but Zoom did not.

00:01:48.440 --> 00:01:50.860
[Amit Varma]: And we tried Google Hangouts, and that didn't work.

00:01:50.860 --> 00:01:52.960
[Amit Varma]: And we tried Skype, and that didn't work.

00:01:52.960 --> 00:01:56.860
[Amit Varma]: And then we tried WhatsApp video call, and we could only record half a session.

00:01:56.860 --> 00:02:01.940
[Amit Varma]: So we resumed a couple of days later, when Rajat's internet behaved itself, and we finally

00:02:01.940 --> 00:02:03.500
[Amit Varma]: wrapped up the episode.

00:02:03.500 --> 00:02:09.500
[Amit Varma]: Our conversation was a hell of a trip, and I mean that in a good way.

00:02:09.500 --> 00:02:13.060
[Amit Varma]: If you enjoy listening to The Seen and The Unseen, you can play a part in keeping the

00:02:13.060 --> 00:02:14.340
[Amit Varma]: show alive.

00:02:14.340 --> 00:02:17.380
[Amit Varma]: The Seen and The Unseen has been a labor of love for me.

00:02:17.380 --> 00:02:22.980
[Amit Varma]: I've enjoyed putting together many stimulating conversations, expanding my brain and my universe,

00:02:22.980 --> 00:02:23.980
[Amit Varma]: and hopefully yours as well.

00:02:23.980 --> 00:02:29.260
[Amit Varma]: But while the work has been its own reward, I don't actually make much money off the show.

00:02:29.260 --> 00:02:33.300
[Amit Varma]: Although The Seen and The Unseen has great numbers, advertisers haven't really woken

00:02:33.300 --> 00:02:36.280
[Amit Varma]: up to the insane engagement level of podcasts.

00:02:36.280 --> 00:02:40.680
[Amit Varma]: And I do many, many hours of deep research for each episode, besides all the logistics

00:02:40.680 --> 00:02:46.820
[Amit Varma]: of producing the show myself, scheduling guests, booking studios, paying technicians, the travel

00:02:46.820 --> 00:02:47.820
[Amit Varma]: and so on.

00:02:47.820 --> 00:02:52.180
[Amit Varma]: So, well, I'm trying a new way of keeping this thing going, and that involves you.

00:02:52.180 --> 00:02:54.380
[Amit Varma]: My proposition for you is this.

00:02:54.380 --> 00:02:59.240
[Amit Varma]: For every episode of The Seen and The Unseen that you enjoy, buy me a cup of coffee, or

00:02:59.240 --> 00:03:02.060
[Amit Varma]: even a lavish lunch, whatever you feel it's worth.

00:03:02.060 --> 00:03:07.780
[Amit Varma]: You can do this by heading over to seenunseen.in slash support, and contributing an amount

00:03:07.780 --> 00:03:08.780
[Amit Varma]: of your choice.

00:03:08.780 --> 00:03:10.940
[Amit Varma]: This is not a subscription.

00:03:10.940 --> 00:03:17.980
[Amit Varma]: The Seen and The Unseen will continue to be free on all podcast apps and at seenunseen.in.

00:03:17.980 --> 00:03:24.300
[Amit Varma]: This is just a gesture of appreciation, help keep this thing going, seenunseen.in slash

00:03:24.300 --> 00:03:25.300
[Amit Varma]: support.

00:03:25.300 --> 00:03:29.780
[Amit Varma]: Rajat, welcome to The Seen and The Unseen.

00:03:29.780 --> 00:03:30.780
[Amit Varma]: Thanks Amit.

00:03:30.780 --> 00:03:37.140
[Amit Varma]: You know, I have to tell our listeners that I am getting a sense of the rhythm of Rajat's

00:03:37.140 --> 00:03:41.260
[Amit Varma]: book because in his book, there's a lot of waiting and a lot of hanging around as you

00:03:41.260 --> 00:03:46.260
[Amit Varma]: know, waiting for trucks and waiting for traffic jams to resolve themselves because we started

00:03:46.260 --> 00:03:52.660
[Amit Varma]: this recording exactly one hour late, because we had technical issues, first the Zencaster

00:03:52.660 --> 00:03:57.380
[Amit Varma]: wasn't working, then the zoom wasn't working, then we tried a bunch of other things.

00:03:57.380 --> 00:04:03.100
[Amit Varma]: And we finally got on to recording but never mind better late than never.

00:04:03.100 --> 00:04:08.540
[Amit Varma]: But you know, maybe that's the enjoyment of the journey comes from all these little moments

00:04:08.540 --> 00:04:12.820
[Amit Varma]: in between, though I think you know, technical glitches don't add anything to one's life.

00:04:12.820 --> 00:04:15.740
[Amit Varma]: So Rajat, before we start talking about your fascinating book, tell me a little bit about

00:04:15.740 --> 00:04:21.460
[Amit Varma]: your personal journey, because, you know, you are an engineer, who then did journalism

00:04:21.460 --> 00:04:27.260
[Amit Varma]: and won an award for it, who then went traveling around India on trucks, and you have just

00:04:27.260 --> 00:04:29.060
[Amit Varma]: joined the civil services.

00:04:29.060 --> 00:04:33.140
[Amit Varma]: So take me through this sort of very interesting journey of yours and how you came to writing

00:04:33.140 --> 00:04:38.300
[Amit Varma]: per se, because that sort of seems to be the one great passion of your life, writing and

00:04:38.300 --> 00:04:39.300
[Amit Varma]: traveling.

00:04:39.300 --> 00:04:43.300
[Guest]: Yeah, it's definitely been an interesting journey so far.

00:04:43.300 --> 00:04:50.660
[Guest]: So as far as my personal background goes, I basically hail from Karnataka, coastal Karnataka.

00:04:50.660 --> 00:04:56.660
[Guest]: I was born in Patkal and brought up largely in Mumbai.

00:04:56.660 --> 00:05:02.580
[Guest]: Part of my schooling was also in a military school in Satara, Sainik school, Satara.

00:05:02.580 --> 00:05:09.140
[Guest]: And after that, I joined IIT Kanpur, where I studied electrical engineering.

00:05:09.140 --> 00:05:15.540
[Guest]: Writing and reading have been abiding passions in my life, as far as I remember, right from

00:05:15.540 --> 00:05:21.700
[Guest]: my childhood, I remember scouring these secondhand rattiwalas, trying to find some Amar Chitra

00:05:21.700 --> 00:05:24.780
[Guest]: Katal or any novel that would excite me.

00:05:24.780 --> 00:05:27.980
[Guest]: So right since childhood, I've been interested in reading.

00:05:27.980 --> 00:05:34.260
[Guest]: The reason why I went into engineering was, of course, like many other kids who got decent

00:05:34.260 --> 00:05:36.980
[Guest]: marks, it made the most sense.

00:05:36.980 --> 00:05:44.460
[Guest]: And I don't regret it at all, because a background in science, I feel is definitely helpful everywhere,

00:05:44.460 --> 00:05:47.140
[Guest]: especially in any stream.

00:05:47.140 --> 00:05:48.580
[Guest]: So I don't regret it.

00:05:48.580 --> 00:05:55.500
[Guest]: Also, I met some amazing people in IITK who continue to be close to me.

00:05:55.500 --> 00:05:57.940
[Guest]: So no regrets over there.

00:05:57.940 --> 00:06:05.620
[Guest]: In my third year or fourth year, I finally decided that I wanted to get into journalism.

00:06:05.620 --> 00:06:11.060
[Guest]: Essentially, it was, I did not want to do a desk job in my early 20s.

00:06:11.060 --> 00:06:16.420
[Guest]: I had this deep hunger to see as much of India as possible.

00:06:16.420 --> 00:06:21.580
[Guest]: And part of that hunger also led me to Kanpur in the first place, because I'm from Bombay

00:06:21.580 --> 00:06:22.580
[Guest]: essentially.

00:06:22.580 --> 00:06:27.540
[Guest]: But I did not want to be stuck in Bombay, close to my parents forever.

00:06:27.540 --> 00:06:30.140
[Guest]: So I decided to join IITK.

00:06:30.140 --> 00:06:36.940
[Guest]: So there's this connect throughout my life I see about wanting to see as much of India

00:06:36.940 --> 00:06:37.940
[Guest]: as possible.

00:06:37.940 --> 00:06:44.060
[Guest]: And I worked for a year after graduation in a management consultancy, got a decent job.

00:06:44.060 --> 00:06:49.540
[Guest]: So I thought I'd give the corporate world a try before stitching it all together, just

00:06:49.540 --> 00:06:54.220
[Guest]: to make sure I won't regret it, just for my own satisfaction.

00:06:54.220 --> 00:06:58.700
[Guest]: And after a year or so, I joined the Asian College of Journalism.

00:06:58.700 --> 00:07:05.140
[Guest]: And from there on, I worked as a business journalist for a couple of years in Bombay.

00:07:05.140 --> 00:07:11.500
[Guest]: And while working as a business journalist, I really decided that I had to go on this

00:07:11.500 --> 00:07:14.140
[Guest]: trip across India.

00:07:14.140 --> 00:07:18.900
[Guest]: The seed of that idea, I think, had been with me right since my college days.

00:07:18.900 --> 00:07:25.100
[Guest]: So as I write in the book, in my first year, one truck driver had very kindly rescued us

00:07:25.100 --> 00:07:29.340
[Guest]: from a light while he was stranded on a highway near Shimla.

00:07:29.340 --> 00:07:35.060
[Guest]: And that sort of stayed with me and the idea of their lives, it appealed to me.

00:07:35.060 --> 00:07:39.860
[Guest]: And I thought that in my early 20s, I should do something like that.

00:07:39.860 --> 00:07:45.380
[Guest]: But it crystallized only by the time I was around 23-24.

00:07:45.380 --> 00:07:50.900
[Guest]: And one fine day, I walk into my editor's office, I tell her, ma'am, see, I did I have

00:07:50.900 --> 00:07:54.220
[Guest]: this crazy idea in my mind, I want to travel across India.

00:07:54.220 --> 00:07:57.100
[Guest]: So please, I want to quit right now.

00:07:57.100 --> 00:08:02.020
[Guest]: So because obviously, you won't keep me you won't give me a holiday for like three, four

00:08:02.020 --> 00:08:03.020
[Guest]: months.

00:08:03.020 --> 00:08:06.020
[Guest]: So but she turned out to be much more sensible than I was.

00:08:06.020 --> 00:08:11.460
[Guest]: She suggested that I write a six-part series for the magazine.

00:08:11.460 --> 00:08:12.820
[Guest]: And I jumped at it.

00:08:12.820 --> 00:08:15.780
[Guest]: I mean, I thought I wouldn't get a better chance.

00:08:15.780 --> 00:08:21.300
[Guest]: I mean, you're getting paid your salary while you are sort of exploring India by truck.

00:08:21.300 --> 00:08:23.460
[Guest]: So I thought couldn't get better.

00:08:23.460 --> 00:08:27.900
[Guest]: And later at one point, even Indian Oil Corporation sort of sponsored the trip.

00:08:27.900 --> 00:08:31.540
[Guest]: So it all worked out somehow, I was lucky.

00:08:31.540 --> 00:08:34.780
[Guest]: And that's been my broad journey.

00:08:34.780 --> 00:08:39.140
[Guest]: And apart from that, recently, I have cleared the UTC exam.

00:08:39.140 --> 00:08:41.220
[Amit Varma]: So let's see where that takes me.

00:08:41.220 --> 00:08:47.100
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, yeah, you might just after all the things you wrote about, sort of the predatory state

00:08:47.100 --> 00:08:50.340
[Amit Varma]: in your book, not in so many words, those are my words, but that's how a lot of the

00:08:50.340 --> 00:08:51.340
[Amit Varma]: book came across.

00:08:51.340 --> 00:08:56.180
[Amit Varma]: It'll kind of be sweetly ironic, you're sort of joining that service and hopefully making

00:08:56.180 --> 00:08:57.180
[Amit Varma]: things better.

00:08:57.180 --> 00:09:01.980
[Amit Varma]: Now, I know it's kind of futile often to ask a reader, what kind of writing do they like?

00:09:01.980 --> 00:09:06.740
[Amit Varma]: Because I think a lot of readers who are drawn to this voracious hunger for just reading

00:09:06.740 --> 00:09:09.060
[Amit Varma]: anything that they can get their hands on.

00:09:09.060 --> 00:09:13.100
[Amit Varma]: It's not a fair question that your reading will naturally tend to be eclectic.

00:09:13.100 --> 00:09:17.020
[Amit Varma]: But given that you also love to travel and love seeing new places and all of that, which

00:09:17.020 --> 00:09:19.740
[Amit Varma]: of course, bookstores, books are a window to other places.

00:09:19.740 --> 00:09:25.940
[Amit Varma]: But was there also an attraction, therefore, to people who write about travel and write

00:09:25.940 --> 00:09:28.940
[Amit Varma]: about going to places like were there models for you?

00:09:28.940 --> 00:09:32.580
[Amit Varma]: Did you ever read a writer and think, huh, that's the kind of thing I want to write and

00:09:32.580 --> 00:09:33.580
[Guest]: so on?

00:09:33.580 --> 00:09:39.380
[Guest]: So one book which I distinctly remember leaving an impression on me was something I read when

00:09:39.380 --> 00:09:40.780
[Guest]: I was in ACJ.

00:09:40.780 --> 00:09:44.660
[Guest]: It's this book called A Free Man by Aman Sethi.

00:09:44.660 --> 00:09:51.900
[Guest]: So what that book showed me was that it is possible to write about India's working class,

00:09:51.900 --> 00:09:57.860
[Guest]: its informal economy, so to say, in a sensitive manner, in an entertaining manner, in an informative

00:09:57.860 --> 00:10:03.860
[Guest]: manner, because the lives of us middle class people is so cocooned in many ways, we are

00:10:03.860 --> 00:10:10.020
[Guest]: unaware of the varied struggles, the various jugars, which people employ in India to live

00:10:10.020 --> 00:10:11.740
[Guest]: out their life day to day.

00:10:11.740 --> 00:10:18.740
[Guest]: So that book, which is about a bunch of daily wage laborers in Delhi, when I read that book,

00:10:18.740 --> 00:10:26.420
[Guest]: I thought, I have to absolutely write something about truck drivers, I mean, their life is

00:10:26.420 --> 00:10:30.860
[Guest]: in some ways more fascinating than that of a daily wage laborer also, because the kind

00:10:30.860 --> 00:10:34.740
[Guest]: of landscapes they're exposed to, the kind of characters they're exposed to on a daily

00:10:34.740 --> 00:10:39.620
[Guest]: basis seem to me to be material fit for a book.

00:10:39.620 --> 00:10:44.460
[Guest]: And I could say that book definitely was a huge influence on me.

00:10:44.460 --> 00:10:50.980
[Guest]: And apart from that, as far as the writing style is concerned, I veer towards the more

00:10:50.980 --> 00:10:55.140
[Guest]: simple writing rather than the more flowery writing, which is difficult to pull off.

00:10:55.140 --> 00:11:01.380
[Guest]: I mean, except for a few exceptions, like Wodehouse, who can pull off that sort of writing

00:11:01.380 --> 00:11:02.380
[Guest]: so beautifully.

00:11:02.380 --> 00:11:05.420
[Guest]: I have always been attracted towards simplicity in writing.

00:11:05.420 --> 00:11:11.300
[Guest]: So as far as models around that, those are concerned, Hemingway, definitely, whom I read

00:11:11.300 --> 00:11:15.260
[Guest]: during the final years of my college was quite an influence.

00:11:15.260 --> 00:11:18.180
[Guest]: Yeah, that would be it.

00:11:18.180 --> 00:11:23.740
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I mean, come to my arms, because I teach this course on clear writing.

00:11:23.740 --> 00:11:28.980
[Amit Varma]: And I often when I talk about writing in that, you know, I cite George Orwell's famous quote,

00:11:28.980 --> 00:11:32.820
[Amit Varma]: good prose is like a windowpane, the whole point being that the windowpane is a means

00:11:32.820 --> 00:11:33.820
[Amit Varma]: to an end.

00:11:33.820 --> 00:11:37.660
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, you know, prose like a windowpane should just be clear, a windowpane is supposed

00:11:37.660 --> 00:11:40.820
[Amit Varma]: to show you what's on the other side and not draw attention to itself.

00:11:40.820 --> 00:11:45.460
[Amit Varma]: And the example I gave of an exception to that is the same one you gave, which is Woodhouse,

00:11:45.460 --> 00:11:50.780
[Amit Varma]: where, you know, in his case, the beautiful things that he does with the prose is an end

00:11:50.780 --> 00:11:51.780
[Amit Varma]: in itself.

00:11:51.780 --> 00:11:52.780
[Amit Varma]: And that's fine.

00:11:52.780 --> 00:11:58.500
[Amit Varma]: But one should not get carried away by that, because everybody cannot be Woodhouse.

00:11:58.500 --> 00:12:03.140
[Amit Varma]: And I like the clarity in your style, and also the sort of the conversational feel of

00:12:03.140 --> 00:12:04.140
[Amit Varma]: it.

00:12:04.140 --> 00:12:09.460
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, you throw in a lot of sort of light touches of humor, just perfect places,

00:12:09.460 --> 00:12:12.100
[Amit Varma]: which kind of really worked for me.

00:12:12.100 --> 00:12:16.740
[Amit Varma]: Was there a process that you went through in sort of finding your voice as it was the

00:12:16.740 --> 00:12:21.540
[Amit Varma]: voice of the book, so to say, or is it something that, you know, was very clear from the start?

00:12:21.540 --> 00:12:26.220
[Amit Varma]: Or did you sort of have to experiment a bit and, you know, write a bit till you discovered

00:12:26.220 --> 00:12:28.460
[Amit Varma]: what the right voice would be?

00:12:28.460 --> 00:12:34.420
[Guest]: Initially, I found myself getting bogged down in these long winded sentences.

00:12:34.420 --> 00:12:38.540
[Guest]: I mean, the initial process was quite a bit of a struggle.

00:12:38.540 --> 00:12:43.580
[Guest]: My basic aim with this book was to appeal to the non-reader.

00:12:43.580 --> 00:12:50.100
[Guest]: I mean, I did not want the reader, whoever he or she may be, to get bored at any point

00:12:50.100 --> 00:12:56.820
[Guest]: in the sense, even though I had some interesting facts to share, or anything which I find to

00:12:56.820 --> 00:13:02.780
[Guest]: be interesting, but essentially the reader may not because it's been, it's too long

00:13:02.780 --> 00:13:05.420
[Guest]: winded or it's been going on for a while.

00:13:05.420 --> 00:13:09.780
[Guest]: So in that sense, it went through a constant process of refinement.

00:13:09.780 --> 00:13:14.340
[Guest]: The end goal being, it should hold the reader's attention.

00:13:14.340 --> 00:13:18.660
[Guest]: And we are so easily distracted these days, right?

00:13:18.660 --> 00:13:23.700
[Guest]: And I think the job of writing is to make it as easy as possible for the reader.

00:13:23.700 --> 00:13:25.900
[Guest]: And that is the most challenging part.

00:13:25.900 --> 00:13:29.500
[Guest]: The process largely consisted of defining the text.

00:13:29.500 --> 00:13:31.500
[Guest]: I do not believe in the draft system.

00:13:31.500 --> 00:13:33.980
[Guest]: I mean, I don't usually maintain too many drafts.

00:13:33.980 --> 00:13:38.340
[Guest]: I get too confused at the end if there are seven or eight of them.

00:13:38.340 --> 00:13:45.580
[Guest]: So I typically just tweak, tweak, tweak until, I mean, it's never really finished, but until

00:13:45.580 --> 00:13:50.740
[Guest]: it meets a certain level of satisfaction, until then I keep tweaking.

00:13:50.740 --> 00:13:52.740
[Amit Varma]: That's my broad process when I'm writing.

00:13:52.740 --> 00:13:57.060
[Amit Varma]: I was struck by this quote at the start of your book by John Steinbeck, where he says,

00:13:57.060 --> 00:14:01.740
[Amit Varma]: quote, we find after years of struggle that we do not take a trip, a trip takes us, stop

00:14:01.740 --> 00:14:05.780
[Amit Varma]: quote, which, you know, would appear to the reader is written in the context of the book

00:14:05.780 --> 00:14:07.060
[Amit Varma]: that is to follow.

00:14:07.060 --> 00:14:10.900
[Amit Varma]: But it also struck me that it has a broader resonance.

00:14:10.900 --> 00:14:14.580
[Amit Varma]: And that's sort of what I want to ask you about in the sense that, you know, you said

00:14:14.580 --> 00:14:19.300
[Amit Varma]: you did engineering and engineering has its own sort of subcultures and lingos and ways

00:14:19.300 --> 00:14:22.220
[Amit Varma]: of speaking and ways of thinking about the world.

00:14:22.220 --> 00:14:27.380
[Amit Varma]: Similarly, after that, you, you know, go to the ACJ and you get into journalism and journalism

00:14:27.380 --> 00:14:30.820
[Amit Varma]: also has its own little subcultures depending on where you are.

00:14:30.820 --> 00:14:34.580
[Amit Varma]: And then you go around the country with these struckers and there, as you've described so

00:14:34.580 --> 00:14:39.860
[Amit Varma]: beautifully, there are all these little subcultures and rituals and these worlds that you inhabit,

00:14:39.860 --> 00:14:43.700
[Amit Varma]: which are in fact, as you've shown in the book, different from place to place.

00:14:43.700 --> 00:14:48.980
[Amit Varma]: It's one thing in the north, another thing in the northeast and so on and so forth.

00:14:48.980 --> 00:14:56.220
[Amit Varma]: And this kind of got me to thinking about how our experiences shape us so profoundly,

00:14:56.220 --> 00:14:59.820
[Amit Varma]: because it struck me while reading the book that some of these subcultures would have

00:14:59.820 --> 00:15:05.220
[Amit Varma]: nothing in common with the other ones like the engineering subculture and say the trucking

00:15:05.220 --> 00:15:10.340
[Amit Varma]: subculture where, you know, there are a few things in common, such as the technology where,

00:15:10.340 --> 00:15:14.680
[Amit Varma]: you know, people use WhatsApp and make Facebook friends from other countries.

00:15:14.680 --> 00:15:19.780
[Amit Varma]: But apart from that, the worlds are so different, they relate to other people so differently

00:15:19.780 --> 00:15:20.860
[Amit Varma]: and all of this.

00:15:20.860 --> 00:15:26.100
[Amit Varma]: So do you find that as sort of a visitor in these different worlds, that you can take

00:15:26.100 --> 00:15:31.300
[Amit Varma]: a step back and look at your friends in each of these worlds, and that their worldview

00:15:31.300 --> 00:15:36.900
[Amit Varma]: in some ways constricted because of the relative narrowness of their experiences?

00:15:36.900 --> 00:15:41.780
[Guest]: That's a great question, Amit, and I 100% agree with you.

00:15:41.780 --> 00:15:48.620
[Guest]: I mean, there's this great quote in the book, English August, actually, that I never allow

00:15:48.620 --> 00:15:52.260
[Guest]: two of my friends from different circles to ever meet.

00:15:52.260 --> 00:16:00.020
[Guest]: That would be two worlds colliding, because we often have these little bubbles, right?

00:16:00.020 --> 00:16:06.220
[Guest]: What I see the world as is composed of these little bubbles who think that the entire world

00:16:06.220 --> 00:16:07.220
[Guest]: revolves around them.

00:16:07.220 --> 00:16:13.220
[Guest]: I mean, many of my friends are in the startup world, and the startup bubble is other world

00:16:13.220 --> 00:16:14.220
[Guest]: altogether.

00:16:14.220 --> 00:16:19.980
[Guest]: I mean, when I go to meet them in Bangalore, sometimes, it's like a step into other portal.

00:16:19.980 --> 00:16:26.340
[Guest]: At the same time, I mean, journalism, of course, is, I mean, one of the reasons why I got into

00:16:26.340 --> 00:16:32.180
[Guest]: journalism was to sort of partake of these different bubbles, at least get a glimpse

00:16:32.180 --> 00:16:36.940
[Guest]: of these different worlds and expand my worldview through that.

00:16:36.940 --> 00:16:40.340
[Guest]: That was one of the reasons I got into journalism.

00:16:40.340 --> 00:16:47.100
[Guest]: And yes, I would definitely say that having this sort of limited worldview, often, I've

00:16:47.100 --> 00:16:55.140
[Guest]: seen it among my engineering batch mates also, the world is very limited for the options

00:16:55.140 --> 00:17:01.420
[Guest]: themselves are so limited after graduation, either you join the corporate world or you

00:17:01.420 --> 00:17:07.540
[Guest]: get into a startup or you start studying for the UPS, these are broadly the or you go for

00:17:07.540 --> 00:17:09.180
[Guest]: a master's abroad.

00:17:09.180 --> 00:17:13.140
[Guest]: And it's essentially limited to these options.

00:17:13.140 --> 00:17:19.020
[Guest]: And I would say yes, the trip of traveling with truckers across India opened my eyes

00:17:19.020 --> 00:17:23.340
[Guest]: in so many ways, which I hope to have shared with the reader through the book.

00:17:23.340 --> 00:17:28.500
[Guest]: And I hope the reader learns something about the many India's that are country in our

00:17:28.500 --> 00:17:29.500
[Amit Varma]: world.

00:17:29.500 --> 00:17:34.260
[Amit Varma]: It was also fascinating for me, like I remember back in my days as a professional poker player,

00:17:34.260 --> 00:17:38.860
[Amit Varma]: I would play with or before so I would have to play with all kinds of I used to play the

00:17:38.860 --> 00:17:41.980
[Amit Varma]: underground cash games in Bombay, I have to play with all kinds of people I would otherwise

00:17:41.980 --> 00:17:43.340
[Amit Varma]: not interact with.

00:17:43.340 --> 00:17:49.380
[Amit Varma]: So whether it's a group of builders in Varshi, I've played with film stars in Warsaw, and

00:17:49.380 --> 00:17:54.980
[Amit Varma]: you know, one group I used to play with, they were people who had grown up going to your

00:17:54.980 --> 00:18:00.720
[Amit Varma]: local RSA shakha every week and were hardcore sort of sanghis in that sense and absolutely

00:18:00.720 --> 00:18:02.140
[Amit Varma]: lovely people, right.

00:18:02.140 --> 00:18:06.740
[Amit Varma]: And what happens in the culture is that, you know, given whichever bubble we are part of,

00:18:06.740 --> 00:18:12.100
[Amit Varma]: we'll sometimes demonize people from different bubbles and not sort of, you know, be completely

00:18:12.100 --> 00:18:15.940
[Amit Varma]: devoid of a deeper understanding of why other people are the way they are.

00:18:15.940 --> 00:18:20.780
[Amit Varma]: And they are also three dimensional and they contain multitudes and all of that, you know,

00:18:20.780 --> 00:18:25.940
[Amit Varma]: given that you were into writing, given that you wanted to travel, and therefore, all of

00:18:25.940 --> 00:18:30.780
[Amit Varma]: these different interests and passions seem to have coalesced towards this particular

00:18:30.780 --> 00:18:32.140
[Amit Varma]: journey that you took.

00:18:32.140 --> 00:18:36.420
[Amit Varma]: But what drew you to the idea of this particular book, like you mentioned, a truck driver helped

00:18:36.420 --> 00:18:41.980
[Amit Varma]: you when you were stranded in Shimla a long time ago, what in particular was sort of the

00:18:41.980 --> 00:18:44.540
[Amit Varma]: expectation that you took into it?

00:18:44.540 --> 00:18:49.420
[Amit Varma]: And did that differ from your experience eventually, because sometimes I imagine what can happen

00:18:49.420 --> 00:18:53.460
[Amit Varma]: is that you can go into something with a romantic notion that, hey, I'm going to travel the

00:18:53.460 --> 00:18:57.300
[Amit Varma]: country in a truck, and I'm going to soak up all the different cultural influences.

00:18:57.300 --> 00:18:59.780
[Amit Varma]: And at the end of it, I'll have this masterpiece.

00:18:59.780 --> 00:19:03.500
[Amit Varma]: And then you actually go and you're just sitting around for 12 hours waiting at a traffic jam

00:19:03.500 --> 00:19:08.260
[Amit Varma]: at a naka with guys who want nothing but to view porn on your phone.

00:19:08.260 --> 00:19:12.380
[Amit Varma]: So you know, were there sort of moments like that when expectations differed from reality

00:19:12.380 --> 00:19:16.420
[Amit Varma]: or did you go into it with the attitude that everything is an unknown unknown, I'll just

00:19:16.420 --> 00:19:19.460
[Amit Varma]: finish the journey and then I'll start forming narratives?

00:19:19.460 --> 00:19:26.260
[Guest]: I mean, my expectations while I was going for the journey, my only expectation was that

00:19:26.260 --> 00:19:28.260
[Guest]: hopefully I'll come out of it alive.

00:19:28.260 --> 00:19:34.580
[Guest]: To be honest, I did not have any preconceived notions, I guess I must have shared some of

00:19:34.580 --> 00:19:40.620
[Guest]: the sort of stereotypes that exist about truckers subconsciously, that you know, they are drunk

00:19:40.620 --> 00:19:47.540
[Guest]: or I know all stereotypes, one may say that are rooted in some form of truth.

00:19:47.540 --> 00:19:54.460
[Guest]: So I may have shared those, but I went in with a totally blank slate and prepared mentally

00:19:54.460 --> 00:20:03.820
[Guest]: for all sorts of physical privations, all sorts of troubles on the way and broadly lived

00:20:03.820 --> 00:20:09.020
[Guest]: up to those expectations in the sense I was right to not expect anything out of it.

00:20:09.020 --> 00:20:14.900
[Guest]: Because just look, I mean, how I set out on the journey itself, I mean, my first, the

00:20:14.900 --> 00:20:21.100
[Guest]: first trucker I hitchhiked with, he was someone who was connected to me by a friend who knew

00:20:21.100 --> 00:20:23.980
[Guest]: someone who was working in a transport office.

00:20:23.980 --> 00:20:26.420
[Guest]: So that was through a connection.

00:20:26.420 --> 00:20:28.100
[Guest]: After that, I was essentially on my own.

00:20:28.100 --> 00:20:32.700
[Guest]: I had no idea how I would find another trucker, where I would go.

00:20:32.700 --> 00:20:35.220
[Guest]: So that was a huge unknown out there.

00:20:35.220 --> 00:20:41.100
[Guest]: And it was a source of considerable anxiety to begin with, because I had no idea how I

00:20:41.100 --> 00:20:46.020
[Guest]: would actually manage it in a practical sense.

00:20:46.020 --> 00:20:52.060
[Guest]: But as the journey progressed, slowly my expectations also started becoming more clear, in the sense

00:20:52.060 --> 00:20:57.900
[Guest]: what can I expect from people, though they were also always belied, I mean, all these

00:20:57.900 --> 00:21:02.660
[Guest]: expectations were never really there, because truckers, there are hundreds of different

00:21:02.660 --> 00:21:06.220
[Guest]: kinds of truckers and personalities of everyone differs.

00:21:06.220 --> 00:21:13.300
[Guest]: And basically, every trip, every truck that you get in, get inside is another world.

00:21:13.300 --> 00:21:16.660
[Guest]: I mean, you, the people are different, their stories are different.

00:21:16.660 --> 00:21:21.860
[Guest]: I mean, that's what I really enjoy about India in some way, you know, I mean, there is this

00:21:21.860 --> 00:21:27.540
[Guest]: particular vantage point of the Indian middle class or the upper middle class, which sort

00:21:27.540 --> 00:21:34.500
[Guest]: of views the rest of India as the great unwashed, you know, I mean, there's this homogenous

00:21:34.500 --> 00:21:42.540
[Guest]: mass of people who essentially are there to serve us, but what I really enjoy seeing is

00:21:42.540 --> 00:21:47.940
[Guest]: in the particular histories that are contained within each person, their own life stories,

00:21:47.940 --> 00:21:54.820
[Guest]: their own background, their family history, I mean, everything says so much about India.

00:21:54.820 --> 00:21:59.180
[Guest]: And it's like a great learning experience and meeting someone outside of your social

00:21:59.180 --> 00:22:03.940
[Guest]: circle and getting to really know their background, it's, it's an education.

00:22:03.940 --> 00:22:07.940
[Guest]: And that's what this trip was, I mean, I was hoping it would be an education and this is

00:22:07.940 --> 00:22:10.260
[Amit Varma]: definitely was.

00:22:10.260 --> 00:22:15.700
[Amit Varma]: And you know, in our normal lives, or rather in our sort of regular lives, I would not

00:22:15.700 --> 00:22:17.460
[Amit Varma]: say this not normal in that sense.

00:22:17.460 --> 00:22:23.700
[Amit Varma]: But in our regular lives, we are all sort of constantly anxious about how other people

00:22:23.700 --> 00:22:24.900
[Amit Varma]: perceive us.

00:22:24.900 --> 00:22:31.260
[Amit Varma]: And in most of our lives, that anxiety is about we want to seem knowledgeable and sophisticated

00:22:31.260 --> 00:22:32.820
[Amit Varma]: and smart and all of that.

00:22:32.820 --> 00:22:38.220
[Amit Varma]: But I imagine here that it's a different kind of anxiety, because you, you know, there is

00:22:38.220 --> 00:22:40.620
[Amit Varma]: a difference of class and privilege here.

00:22:40.620 --> 00:22:45.540
[Amit Varma]: And for you, the tension must have been how do I fit in, I don't want them to feel as

00:22:45.540 --> 00:22:49.660
[Amit Varma]: if I'm coming at them from a place that is above them, you know, not just in terms of

00:22:49.660 --> 00:22:52.900
[Amit Varma]: class or whatever, but even your approach and all that.

00:22:52.900 --> 00:22:56.140
[Amit Varma]: So how did you sort of, you know, deal with that?

00:22:56.140 --> 00:22:59.700
[Amit Varma]: Was there that anxiety that how do I, how do I fit in?

00:22:59.700 --> 00:23:00.700
[Amit Varma]: Should I joke with them?

00:23:00.700 --> 00:23:02.780
[Amit Varma]: What kind of language should I use?

00:23:02.780 --> 00:23:05.660
[Amit Varma]: How did you navigate all of those things?

00:23:05.660 --> 00:23:08.500
[Guest]: That anxiety definitely was there to begin with.

00:23:08.500 --> 00:23:14.540
[Guest]: So what I did was before setting out on the journey itself, I visited a couple of truck

00:23:14.540 --> 00:23:15.540
[Guest]: terminals.

00:23:15.540 --> 00:23:21.940
[Guest]: There's this huge one in Karamburi and another one in Vadala and I interacted with the truckers

00:23:21.940 --> 00:23:28.380
[Guest]: over there just to see, get a sense of what they are like in reality and the kind of warmth

00:23:28.380 --> 00:23:34.260
[Guest]: and generosity that I saw even there really played a big part in reassuring that if your

00:23:34.260 --> 00:23:40.740
[Guest]: intentions are genuine, if you don't condescend to them and if you don't patronize them, they

00:23:40.740 --> 00:23:45.100
[Guest]: are perfectly good people who will answer all your questions happily because they have

00:23:45.100 --> 00:23:51.620
[Guest]: so many grievances inside them over the years, which no one has ever cared for or asked or

00:23:51.620 --> 00:23:57.940
[Guest]: addressed in any way that if there's someone who's asking them genuine questions about

00:23:57.940 --> 00:24:03.740
[Guest]: what problems they face, what their life has been like, they are more than happy to answer.

00:24:03.740 --> 00:24:11.020
[Guest]: So I went in with the expectation that I should just be a genuine person.

00:24:11.020 --> 00:24:17.500
[Guest]: If my intentions are, I don't have any vested interests and if I actually go there and if

00:24:17.500 --> 00:24:22.340
[Guest]: I do care about their lives in some way, that comes across when you're interacting with

00:24:22.340 --> 00:24:23.340
[Guest]: strangers.

00:24:23.340 --> 00:24:29.660
[Guest]: What I've realized is that your eyes and your smile, they reveal a lot about you and about

00:24:29.660 --> 00:24:36.220
[Guest]: your intentions and other human beings can definitely see that.

00:24:36.220 --> 00:24:40.340
[Amit Varma]: You know, I'm reminded of the title of this great book, which came out a few decades ago

00:24:40.340 --> 00:24:43.780
[Amit Varma]: by Alan Siletto called The Loneliness of the Long Distance Runner.

00:24:43.780 --> 00:24:46.420
[Amit Varma]: And it seemed, you know, you could also have something called The Loneliness of the Long

00:24:46.420 --> 00:24:47.780
[Amit Varma]: Distance Trucker.

00:24:47.780 --> 00:24:53.660
[Amit Varma]: And is that part of the reason, like I'm assuming when you say that they were warmer and, you

00:24:53.660 --> 00:24:58.340
[Amit Varma]: know, nicer towards you than you might have expected or than this, you know, the middle

00:24:58.340 --> 00:25:03.180
[Amit Varma]: class stereotypes about the unwashed might lead you to believing, do you think that's

00:25:03.180 --> 00:25:07.020
[Amit Varma]: part of the reason is that they're always on the road, those personal connections aren't

00:25:07.020 --> 00:25:08.020
[Amit Varma]: really happening?

00:25:08.020 --> 00:25:12.180
[Amit Varma]: Like, the way you've kind of described the mini worlds of each of these truckers, it

00:25:12.180 --> 00:25:16.580
[Amit Varma]: seems like, you know, there'll be two or three people traveling together in a truck and that's

00:25:16.580 --> 00:25:21.460
[Amit Varma]: like, you know, that's their whole world and a lot of other stuff is peripheral and they

00:25:21.460 --> 00:25:25.900
[Amit Varma]: must be sort of craving to talk to other people.

00:25:25.900 --> 00:25:30.460
[Amit Varma]: You know, is that a sort of sense also that you got of the truckers life?

00:25:30.460 --> 00:25:39.140
[Guest]: Yes, I think that you're right, because most of the truckers I felt were very lonely.

00:25:39.140 --> 00:25:44.580
[Guest]: I mean, it's a lonely job, and especially when you are alone, like so many truckers

00:25:44.580 --> 00:25:48.100
[Guest]: in India travel alone, they won't even have a khalasi.

00:25:48.100 --> 00:25:54.300
[Guest]: So when you're alone, it's an immensely lonely job, a monotonous job with few distractions.

00:25:54.300 --> 00:25:59.660
[Guest]: I mean, you stop and have some kutka, that's your break, you have some chai and then you

00:25:59.660 --> 00:26:02.300
[Guest]: want some kutka, that's pretty much your break.

00:26:02.300 --> 00:26:08.900
[Guest]: And when someone like me, for instance, asks them, gets into the vehicle, it's not only

00:26:08.900 --> 00:26:16.940
[Guest]: good company, I mean, it's just you get to unload some of the baggage that you have accumulated

00:26:16.940 --> 00:26:19.540
[Guest]: over the years in the truck.

00:26:19.540 --> 00:26:27.300
[Guest]: So definitely that did play a part in shaping their attitudes towards me as this sort of

00:26:27.300 --> 00:26:29.300
[Guest]: privileged person in their midst.

00:26:29.300 --> 00:26:34.900
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I mean, one of the things that I was kind of struck by curiosity for and your book

00:26:34.900 --> 00:26:41.580
[Amit Varma]: gave so many fascinating glimpses of it, was what is the interior life of a trucker?

00:26:41.580 --> 00:26:44.580
[Amit Varma]: You know, and obviously, there's no sort of one answer to this.

00:26:44.580 --> 00:26:49.780
[Amit Varma]: But I was struck by this, you know, fascinating quote from someone called Shyam, who you said

00:26:49.780 --> 00:26:50.780
[Amit Varma]: was a man of few words.

00:26:50.780 --> 00:26:54.260
[Amit Varma]: And at one point, when you ask him that, why did you come into trucking?

00:26:54.260 --> 00:26:57.580
[Amit Varma]: He says this little bit, which I'm going to read out because I found it so fascinating,

00:26:57.580 --> 00:27:03.140
[Amit Varma]: where he says, quote, in a word music, in Kangra as a style, I had many cousins who

00:27:03.140 --> 00:27:04.140
[Amit Varma]: drove trucks.

00:27:04.140 --> 00:27:07.940
[Amit Varma]: They would allow me to ride with them sometimes and play songs all along the way.

00:27:07.940 --> 00:27:10.100
[Amit Varma]: Those are some of the best memories I have.

00:27:10.100 --> 00:27:14.860
[Amit Varma]: That's when I decided I should get into this line, drive trucks to distant places, listening

00:27:14.860 --> 00:27:16.060
[Amit Varma]: to music all along.

00:27:16.060 --> 00:27:18.060
[Amit Varma]: I was not interested in studies.

00:27:18.060 --> 00:27:20.580
[Amit Varma]: All I wanted was my music, stop quote.

00:27:20.580 --> 00:27:21.580
[Amit Varma]: And I found this so interesting.

00:27:21.580 --> 00:27:27.340
[Amit Varma]: And you talk about how, you know, all his music was so sort of carefully curated on,

00:27:27.340 --> 00:27:30.940
[Amit Varma]: you know, the USB drive, which he would have, and so on.

00:27:30.940 --> 00:27:32.500
[Amit Varma]: And it's such a fascinating story.

00:27:32.500 --> 00:27:37.900
[Amit Varma]: And you think of how this person placed in a different social context could live a totally

00:27:37.900 --> 00:27:38.900
[Amit Varma]: different life.

00:27:38.900 --> 00:27:43.140
[Amit Varma]: Like someone with a passion for music born in a good family in Delhi or in a Bollywood

00:27:43.140 --> 00:27:46.300
[Amit Varma]: family in Bombay would be a whole different thing.

00:27:46.300 --> 00:27:51.340
[Amit Varma]: And this person's way of indulging this passion is sort of to become a truck driver.

00:27:51.340 --> 00:27:54.820
[Amit Varma]: At another point, another trucker, you ask the same question to another trucker somewhere

00:27:54.820 --> 00:27:55.820
[Amit Varma]: else.

00:27:55.820 --> 00:28:00.060
[Amit Varma]: And he replied, quote, what should I tell you, I've done almost everything that a man

00:28:00.060 --> 00:28:01.060
[Amit Varma]: can do.

00:28:01.060 --> 00:28:05.860
[Amit Varma]: I've been a truck driver, a tailor, a grape seller, a mechanic, a salesman, and more don't

00:28:05.860 --> 00:28:09.140
[Amit Varma]: didn't stick to any job for more than two years.

00:28:09.140 --> 00:28:10.900
[Amit Varma]: But I'm old now.

00:28:10.900 --> 00:28:12.740
[Amit Varma]: Don't have energy left anymore.

00:28:12.740 --> 00:28:13.740
[Amit Varma]: Stop quote.

00:28:13.740 --> 00:28:19.280
[Amit Varma]: And to this you commented on this by writing, quote, it's a sort of self description most

00:28:19.280 --> 00:28:23.300
[Amit Varma]: working class men in India would have given if only someone asked them.

00:28:23.300 --> 00:28:27.980
[Amit Varma]: India's informal sector does have a way of making ordinary people multifaceted, stop

00:28:27.980 --> 00:28:28.980
[Amit Varma]: quote.

00:28:28.980 --> 00:28:33.340
[Amit Varma]: And it struck me that here that there are, you know, you talk a lot in your book about

00:28:33.340 --> 00:28:37.340
[Amit Varma]: a particular kind of jugar, which is that you're figuring out a way to make something

00:28:37.340 --> 00:28:42.140
[Amit Varma]: work, whether it is, you know, cooling bottles of water by putting them on the windshield

00:28:42.140 --> 00:28:44.420
[Amit Varma]: where the wind blows against them or another.

00:28:44.420 --> 00:28:50.180
[Amit Varma]: But it seems to me that even beyond the jugar of immediate functionality, there is also

00:28:50.180 --> 00:28:56.860
[Amit Varma]: a jugar of life, where in a certain way, given the poverty in this country, given the scarcities,

00:28:56.860 --> 00:29:01.460
[Amit Varma]: given the lack of opportunities, many people have, you know, which, you know, your whole

00:29:01.460 --> 00:29:06.300
[Amit Varma]: life becomes a way of sort of going against different tides being buffeted this way and

00:29:06.300 --> 00:29:09.980
[Amit Varma]: that way and all the time doing jugar, jugar, jugar, jugar, jugar.

00:29:09.980 --> 00:29:14.820
[Amit Varma]: So all of this, whether you're a tailor or a grape seller or a mechanic or a truck driver,

00:29:14.820 --> 00:29:17.900
[Amit Varma]: it's different kinds of jugars at a time.

00:29:17.900 --> 00:29:19.460
[Amit Varma]: Is this something you got a sense of?

00:29:19.460 --> 00:29:23.700
[Amit Varma]: And was there sort of a poignancy that you felt, which I as a reader reading your wonderful

00:29:23.700 --> 00:29:28.580
[Amit Varma]: book certainly did, of, you know, the helplessness of these sort of lives and the fact that these

00:29:28.580 --> 00:29:33.060
[Amit Varma]: guys are still so cheerful and they're going along and they're in whatever, what was that

00:29:33.060 --> 00:29:34.060
[Amit Varma]: sort of sense like?

00:29:34.060 --> 00:29:42.100
[Guest]: Yeah, I mean, the overwhelming sense that I get from my travels is that of wasted potential.

00:29:42.100 --> 00:29:48.140
[Guest]: I see so many, so many bright people, I mean, it's so obvious that they are bright, given

00:29:48.140 --> 00:29:52.260
[Guest]: the right circumstances, they could have become anything they wanted.

00:29:52.260 --> 00:29:57.340
[Guest]: That I feel is the fundamental tragedy of India, the wasted potential, whether it be

00:29:57.340 --> 00:30:02.300
[Guest]: in terms of sports, whether it be in terms of intellect, there's all kinds of talent

00:30:02.300 --> 00:30:03.300
[Guest]: out there.

00:30:03.300 --> 00:30:09.420
[Guest]: People are so smart, I mean, we, I mean, this kind of reduction of smartness to academic

00:30:09.420 --> 00:30:15.540
[Guest]: performance is, does not do justice to the various kinds of intelligence that Indians

00:30:15.540 --> 00:30:16.540
[Guest]: have.

00:30:16.540 --> 00:30:23.540
[Guest]: And the point that you said about being multifaceted, right, that is something which recurred again

00:30:23.540 --> 00:30:24.540
[Guest]: and again.

00:30:24.540 --> 00:30:29.260
[Guest]: I mean, just to make ends meet, people learn all kinds of skills, they learn different

00:30:29.260 --> 00:30:35.620
[Guest]: languages, they move to Kerala or Bihar, you will start speaking Malayalam within a year.

00:30:35.620 --> 00:30:42.420
[Guest]: So there's this enormous reservoir of talent out there, which is both wasted day in and

00:30:42.420 --> 00:30:44.260
[Guest]: day out in India.

00:30:44.260 --> 00:30:55.380
[Guest]: And I feel that it's definitely sad when I think about it, but it's also a way to be

00:30:55.380 --> 00:30:56.380
[Guest]: free.

00:30:56.380 --> 00:31:01.620
[Guest]: I mean, you know, the book that I talked about, A Free Man by M. N. Sethi, that is essentially

00:31:01.620 --> 00:31:07.340
[Guest]: how often many people who live day to day, they are just pursuing freedom.

00:31:07.340 --> 00:31:12.620
[Guest]: I mean, what we perceive as a job and as this lifestyle that we have to meet, these are

00:31:12.620 --> 00:31:17.300
[Guest]: all constraints that bind us, we're all pawns in some way.

00:31:17.300 --> 00:31:23.420
[Guest]: But it could be argued that a truly free person is someone who does not have these large forces

00:31:23.420 --> 00:31:27.620
[Guest]: which are always keeping him constrained.

00:31:27.620 --> 00:31:35.700
[Guest]: Like there's this good quote by Leonard Cohen, like a bird on the wire, like a child drunk

00:31:35.700 --> 00:31:39.820
[Guest]: in a midnight choir, I have tried in my way to be free.

00:31:39.820 --> 00:31:46.260
[Guest]: And that quote really speaks to me, and it sort of encapsulates the lives of all these

00:31:46.260 --> 00:31:48.380
[Guest]: Indians that I met on the road.

00:31:48.380 --> 00:31:54.220
[Amit Varma]: You know, another thing that kind of made me very sad in the book was a sense of how,

00:31:54.220 --> 00:31:58.420
[Amit Varma]: you know, worldviews can be so constricted and constrained by what you experience.

00:31:58.420 --> 00:32:02.020
[Amit Varma]: I mean, we spoke about it earlier, about these different subcultures.

00:32:02.020 --> 00:32:06.700
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, you described it as, you know, all these bubbles which, you know, exist and

00:32:06.700 --> 00:32:07.900
[Amit Varma]: don't intersect.

00:32:07.900 --> 00:32:13.140
[Amit Varma]: And obviously, you know, we can joke about how IIT engineers bubble stops them from so

00:32:13.140 --> 00:32:17.340
[Amit Varma]: many experiences and seeing whatever, but in the case of the truckers, it seems even

00:32:17.340 --> 00:32:18.860
[Amit Varma]: more poignant to me.

00:32:18.860 --> 00:32:23.580
[Amit Varma]: Because once you get into that trucking life, which, you know, can happen when you're in

00:32:23.580 --> 00:32:27.700
[Amit Varma]: your mid teens, for example, you know, you've spoken of people in the book coming into it

00:32:27.700 --> 00:32:28.700
[Amit Varma]: as a khalasi.

00:32:28.700 --> 00:32:32.820
[Amit Varma]: A khalasi, by the way, for the listeners is an apprentice to a truck driver who will ride

00:32:32.820 --> 00:32:37.980
[Amit Varma]: around with him for two, three years and perform odd jobs and then eventually graduate to become

00:32:37.980 --> 00:32:38.980
[Amit Varma]: a driver.

00:32:38.980 --> 00:32:43.980
[Amit Varma]: So that's your guru-shishya parampara in a sense of trucking and people become khalasis

00:32:43.980 --> 00:32:45.540
[Amit Varma]: when they are in their teens.

00:32:45.540 --> 00:32:49.580
[Amit Varma]: And from then it strikes me that what they know of the world is so limited, you know,

00:32:49.580 --> 00:32:55.660
[Amit Varma]: because many of them will have smartphones, you know, especially in the West and the South.

00:32:55.660 --> 00:33:00.420
[Amit Varma]: As you pointed out, a couple of truckers you were with had better smartphones than you,

00:33:00.420 --> 00:33:03.420
[Amit Varma]: you know, and there might be some influences coming from there, but they're close to so

00:33:03.420 --> 00:33:04.420
[Amit Varma]: much of the world.

00:33:04.420 --> 00:33:08.820
[Amit Varma]: And one example of this, which really stayed with me was you spoke about a Kashmiri truck

00:33:08.820 --> 00:33:13.220
[Amit Varma]: driver who was explaining to you the problem between India and Pakistan, the problem of

00:33:13.220 --> 00:33:14.220
[Amit Varma]: Kashmir.

00:33:14.220 --> 00:33:16.060
[Amit Varma]: And to him, it all came down to apples.

00:33:16.060 --> 00:33:21.700
[Amit Varma]: He said the apples of Kashmir are so good that Indians don't want the apples to go to

00:33:21.700 --> 00:33:24.180
[Amit Varma]: Pakistan and Pakistan is closer.

00:33:24.180 --> 00:33:29.180
[Amit Varma]: And that's why the army has to occupy Kashmir, which is stunning, which is stunning.

00:33:29.180 --> 00:33:35.940
[Amit Varma]: And yet so rational for someone who is, who may not have experienced or read about any

00:33:35.940 --> 00:33:41.300
[Amit Varma]: of the discord between these two countries and all of these big geopolitical currents,

00:33:41.300 --> 00:33:45.100
[Amit Varma]: other than the beauty of these apples, you know, and appreciation for them.

00:33:45.100 --> 00:33:48.300
[Amit Varma]: And obviously there were different trucking subcultures because you went to so many different

00:33:48.300 --> 00:33:49.300
[Amit Varma]: places.

00:33:49.300 --> 00:33:55.100
[Amit Varma]: But is that something that also kind of struck you and, you know, you know, got you thinking

00:33:55.100 --> 00:33:56.100
[Amit Varma]: while you were on your travels?

00:33:56.100 --> 00:34:04.820
[Guest]: There is a certain degree of insularity among truckers because while we think of them as

00:34:04.820 --> 00:34:13.260
[Guest]: these all India movers of goods, the fact is their circle is quite limited.

00:34:13.260 --> 00:34:19.100
[Guest]: They are mostly hangout with people from their own caste or from their own village, maximum

00:34:19.100 --> 00:34:21.020
[Guest]: from their own region.

00:34:21.020 --> 00:34:26.060
[Guest]: So across India, there are these dhabas which specify what kind of dhaba they are, whether

00:34:26.060 --> 00:34:28.900
[Guest]: a Rajasthani dhaba or a Bengal dhaba.

00:34:28.900 --> 00:34:34.740
[Guest]: So then the truckers hailing from these regions will specifically go only to these dhabas

00:34:34.740 --> 00:34:39.140
[Guest]: where they know that people belonging to their region hangout and their goods are safe and

00:34:39.140 --> 00:34:40.540
[Guest]: their truck is safe.

00:34:40.540 --> 00:34:50.340
[Guest]: So their world is quite insular and I would say that interaction with other forces are

00:34:50.340 --> 00:34:51.340
[Guest]: usually negative.

00:34:51.340 --> 00:34:56.100
[Guest]: I mean, any person outside their circle whom they interact with is either out there to

00:34:56.100 --> 00:34:58.820
[Guest]: harass him or extort money from him.

00:34:58.820 --> 00:35:04.380
[Guest]: So their perception of the outside world is not necessarily very good because the kind

00:35:04.380 --> 00:35:10.260
[Guest]: of stigma that they have in society, they are regarded with hostility and suspicion

00:35:10.260 --> 00:35:11.260
[Guest]: at large.

00:35:11.260 --> 00:35:15.340
[Guest]: I mean, you take any random person off the street, you ask them their opinion about truckers,

00:35:15.340 --> 00:35:17.860
[Guest]: it's very likely it's going to be negative.

00:35:17.860 --> 00:35:26.220
[Guest]: So they themselves also have this sort of distrust of the larger society and in many

00:35:26.220 --> 00:35:31.660
[Guest]: ways they have also internalized this paraya status in society.

00:35:31.660 --> 00:35:38.740
[Guest]: Like one trucker whom I met in Udaipur described himself as belonging to the seti swichat,

00:35:38.740 --> 00:35:44.180
[Guest]: which is essentially someone who does not belong in a respectable society, who is an

00:35:44.180 --> 00:35:46.420
[Guest]: outcast in some ways.

00:35:46.420 --> 00:35:52.020
[Guest]: So that sort of self-description really struck me because they have internalized their lowly

00:35:52.020 --> 00:35:53.940
[Guest]: status in society.

00:35:53.940 --> 00:35:54.940
[Guest]: Many of them.

00:35:54.940 --> 00:35:59.740
[Guest]: In the south, I met many proud truck drivers as well, who told me that we don't take

00:35:59.740 --> 00:36:03.540
[Guest]: shit from anyone, whether it be the owner or the people.

00:36:03.540 --> 00:36:10.780
[Guest]: So it's certainly not a homogenous thing, but to a large extent, yes, they have internalized

00:36:10.780 --> 00:36:16.540
[Guest]: their lowly status and are insular in ways which prevents them from seeing the larger

00:36:16.540 --> 00:36:17.540
[Guest]: picture.

00:36:17.540 --> 00:36:18.980
[Guest]: I mean, you just look at the job they're doing, right?

00:36:18.980 --> 00:36:24.380
[Guest]: They are the larger picture, actually, because they are the ones who are transporting goods

00:36:24.380 --> 00:36:25.380
[Guest]: everywhere.

00:36:25.380 --> 00:36:30.100
[Guest]: They are the logistics, but they only get to see a small part of the whole picture,

00:36:30.100 --> 00:36:31.100
[Guest]: right?

00:36:31.100 --> 00:36:36.060
[Guest]: They are essentially the supply chain, which is our entire economy, but they only ever

00:36:36.060 --> 00:36:40.380
[Guest]: get to see a small part of it, which is, okay, I need to load these goods here and deliver

00:36:40.380 --> 00:36:41.380
[Guest]: it there.

00:36:41.380 --> 00:36:46.780
[Guest]: It's like so many structural forces are preventing them from seeing the larger picture in many

00:36:46.780 --> 00:36:47.780
[Amit Varma]: ways.

00:36:47.780 --> 00:36:48.780
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

00:36:48.780 --> 00:36:51.420
[Amit Varma]: In fact, you mentioned the saitisvi jaat thing and I was struck by the full quote, which

00:36:51.420 --> 00:36:57.140
[Amit Varma]: is in your book where this person says to you, saitisvi jaat kehlate hai hum truck driver

00:36:57.140 --> 00:37:03.060
[Amit Varma]: aur chhattisvi jaat hai yeh transporters jo hum jaise jaanvaron ko paalte hai, which seems

00:37:03.060 --> 00:37:08.980
[Amit Varma]: to be a very sort of a perceptive way of seeing yourself at the bottom of the food chain and

00:37:08.980 --> 00:37:12.740
[Amit Varma]: the guy above you, you know that he's, you know, treating you like a paaltu jaanvar,

00:37:12.740 --> 00:37:17.620
[Amit Varma]: but he's just one rung above you and you also kind of know that, which seems interesting.

00:37:17.620 --> 00:37:24.220
[Amit Varma]: And what also sort of struck me is you spoke about how the status of truck drivers has

00:37:24.220 --> 00:37:26.340
[Amit Varma]: actually diminished over the decades.

00:37:26.340 --> 00:37:30.380
[Amit Varma]: Like you know, you have this bit where you're speaking about it, you know, how a truck driver

00:37:30.380 --> 00:37:36.260
[Amit Varma]: friend of yours is telling you about quote, the notoriety truck drivers enjoy in society

00:37:36.260 --> 00:37:39.060
[Amit Varma]: and you write quote, he tells me it wasn't always like this.

00:37:39.060 --> 00:37:43.460
[Amit Varma]: In the 80s, when his father started driving trucks, the status of truckers was very different

00:37:43.460 --> 00:37:44.980
[Amit Varma]: from what it is now.

00:37:44.980 --> 00:37:48.900
[Amit Varma]: Without power steering, driving trucks was considered a relatively skilled, well-paid

00:37:48.900 --> 00:37:51.740
[Amit Varma]: job, much like crane and forklift operators now.

00:37:51.740 --> 00:37:55.820
[Amit Varma]: Villagers, largely cut off from the world, would welcome them as a harbingers of goods

00:37:55.820 --> 00:38:01.140
[Amit Varma]: and news, treat them to tea, even invite them into their homes, doktor ke barabar maante

00:38:01.140 --> 00:38:03.660
[Amit Varma]: the, and here you quoted that guy, stop quote.

00:38:03.660 --> 00:38:08.860
[Amit Varma]: And this also drives on how enormous the changes of the last couple of decades are not just

00:38:08.860 --> 00:38:13.140
[Amit Varma]: in this context, because you talk of how villagers cut off from the world would look at getting

00:38:13.140 --> 00:38:14.740
[Amit Varma]: their news from truckers.

00:38:14.740 --> 00:38:19.460
[Amit Varma]: And now the villagers have smartphones and many ways of getting the news and they don't

00:38:19.460 --> 00:38:20.900
[Amit Varma]: need truckers anymore.

00:38:20.900 --> 00:38:25.140
[Amit Varma]: And at the same time, trucking has lost some of the skill because power steering and all

00:38:25.140 --> 00:38:27.420
[Amit Varma]: these other things have come into it.

00:38:27.420 --> 00:38:33.700
[Amit Varma]: And at the same time, truckers, in a sense, are, you know, much more cut off from the

00:38:33.700 --> 00:38:36.980
[Amit Varma]: world than these sort of villagers.

00:38:36.980 --> 00:38:41.540
[Amit Varma]: Does this become an issue, say, with something that the older truckers deal with?

00:38:41.540 --> 00:38:46.780
[Amit Varma]: Because the older truckers might have gotten into the game at a time where it wasn't such

00:38:46.780 --> 00:38:51.020
[Amit Varma]: a lowly profession, so to say, or a sainthi swijat, and now you're a nobody and you're

00:38:51.020 --> 00:38:52.020
[Amit Varma]: a nothing.

00:38:52.020 --> 00:38:57.420
[Amit Varma]: And you talk about one trucker who, you know, did a b comm and wanted to do management,

00:38:57.420 --> 00:39:00.540
[Amit Varma]: and his father would not let him put him in the truck business.

00:39:00.540 --> 00:39:05.300
[Amit Varma]: And he is cursing his father that what kind of a father would do that to his son?

00:39:05.300 --> 00:39:06.300
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

00:39:06.300 --> 00:39:11.060
[Amit Varma]: Is there a difference in approach and attitude between the older guys, the middle aged guys,

00:39:11.060 --> 00:39:14.340
[Amit Varma]: the middle aged guys of my age, and maybe the young guys of your age?

00:39:14.340 --> 00:39:21.980
[Guest]: Yeah, so, you know, among the older guys, I have asked them, I mean, what I used to

00:39:21.980 --> 00:39:26.300
[Guest]: ask them was, what do you think, you're so experienced, you have like so many years of

00:39:26.300 --> 00:39:32.740
[Guest]: experience on the road, does that mean anything to the people who are hiring you?

00:39:32.740 --> 00:39:36.900
[Guest]: And that is where the main essential problem lies, because this sort of experience does

00:39:36.900 --> 00:39:37.900
[Guest]: not have any value.

00:39:37.900 --> 00:39:42.420
[Guest]: In fact, what they told me was that I'm old, so these guys will discard me, they want someone

00:39:42.420 --> 00:39:48.460
[Guest]: young to work longer hours, sleep less and get managed with lesser sleep.

00:39:48.460 --> 00:39:53.180
[Guest]: So there's this immense sense of frustration that I have worked all my life, it's like

00:39:53.180 --> 00:39:54.180
[Guest]: a dead end job, right?

00:39:54.180 --> 00:39:59.860
[Guest]: There's no avenue to go up, once you start as a truck driver, it's not like you will

00:39:59.860 --> 00:40:04.820
[Guest]: get any increment, or there will be any sort of change in your designation.

00:40:04.820 --> 00:40:10.340
[Guest]: And that sense of frustration was immense, especially in the middle aged drivers, who

00:40:10.340 --> 00:40:15.860
[Guest]: see that after all these years of slogging, their savings are negligible, their children

00:40:15.860 --> 00:40:19.860
[Guest]: are also not as educated as they would have liked them to be, many of them have ended

00:40:19.860 --> 00:40:21.860
[Guest]: up joining them only.

00:40:21.860 --> 00:40:29.660
[Guest]: And that sense was there, the younger ones, they were more of hustlers, I would say, the

00:40:29.660 --> 00:40:34.420
[Guest]: attitude was the same, in the sense that I'm trying this out for now, but might move on

00:40:34.420 --> 00:40:35.420
[Guest]: to something else.

00:40:35.420 --> 00:40:41.420
[Guest]: So one of the truckers whom I met was treating this as sort of, treating the job of driving

00:40:41.420 --> 00:40:46.380
[Guest]: trucks as practice for his driving test to become a bus driver.

00:40:46.380 --> 00:40:53.140
[Guest]: So they have other ambitions, they know there are other avenues out there to earn money.

00:40:53.140 --> 00:40:58.580
[Guest]: And they are also keenly aware that becoming a truck driver is like, you are a nobody in

00:40:58.580 --> 00:41:02.940
[Guest]: society, you are likely to be looked down and judged and harassed and extorted, they

00:41:02.940 --> 00:41:05.260
[Guest]: are very well aware of that.

00:41:05.260 --> 00:41:08.620
[Guest]: And they are constantly looking out for other avenues.

00:41:08.620 --> 00:41:14.220
[Guest]: I mean, there's one survey which was conducted recently by Save Life Foundation, which said

00:41:14.220 --> 00:41:21.500
[Guest]: that around 85% of the truckers would not recommend trucking as a job to their family

00:41:21.500 --> 00:41:24.460
[Guest]: members or their relatives or whoever.

00:41:24.460 --> 00:41:27.220
[Guest]: So that's the kind of status there is.

00:41:27.220 --> 00:41:33.900
[Guest]: But you're right, in the early days in the 80s and 90s, 80s were like a proper boom decade

00:41:33.900 --> 00:41:34.900
[Guest]: for trucking.

00:41:34.900 --> 00:41:40.060
[Guest]: There are some figures which I found out about commercial vehicle production, it really boomed

00:41:40.060 --> 00:41:41.860
[Guest]: from the 80s to the 90s.

00:41:41.860 --> 00:41:48.740
[Guest]: And this can be seen also from the small town of Namakkal, where they build these trucks,

00:41:48.740 --> 00:41:52.420
[Guest]: where the number of people employed jumped from 5000 to 17000.

00:41:52.420 --> 00:41:57.820
[Guest]: In just 10 years, there was over a threefold rise in the people employed in making trucks.

00:41:57.820 --> 00:42:03.420
[Guest]: And while we like to think of the 90s as the real sort of liberalization and boom decade,

00:42:03.420 --> 00:42:09.380
[Guest]: but it's clear that the 80s, there was a lot of build up in terms of economic growth in

00:42:09.380 --> 00:42:10.380
[Guest]: the 80s itself.

00:42:10.380 --> 00:42:14.980
[Guest]: And there's no better correlator of economic growth like commercial vehicles.

00:42:14.980 --> 00:42:20.780
[Guest]: I mean, they are the best way possibly to figure out how the economy at large is doing.

00:42:20.780 --> 00:42:23.100
[Amit Varma]: So yeah, I hope that answers your question.

00:42:23.100 --> 00:42:24.100
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

00:42:24.100 --> 00:42:28.860
[Amit Varma]: And what you said about the older truck drivers is also kind of illustrative of, you know,

00:42:28.860 --> 00:42:32.580
[Amit Varma]: a mistake young people often make and old people warn about where you assume that you

00:42:32.580 --> 00:42:35.780
[Amit Varma]: are making some small decision and it is not a big deal.

00:42:35.780 --> 00:42:39.980
[Amit Varma]: For example, I will, you know, I can't find a job right now, I'll start driving a truck,

00:42:39.980 --> 00:42:40.980
[Amit Varma]: let's see how it goes.

00:42:40.980 --> 00:42:44.540
[Amit Varma]: And before you know it, 25 years have passed, and there's nothing else you can do.

00:42:44.540 --> 00:42:47.740
[Amit Varma]: And your whole life has gone by and you're kind of stuck in like you said, it's not even

00:42:47.740 --> 00:42:52.700
[Amit Varma]: like a career track, that you get increments and you get promoted from intern all the way

00:42:52.700 --> 00:42:53.700
[Amit Varma]: to CEO.

00:42:53.700 --> 00:42:55.500
[Amit Varma]: If you're driving a truck, you're driving a truck.

00:42:55.500 --> 00:43:01.300
[Amit Varma]: You're not a CEO at any point, especially when, you know, so much of the industry like

00:43:01.300 --> 00:43:05.220
[Amit Varma]: you pointed out is, you know, not corporatized at all.

00:43:05.220 --> 00:43:12.380
[Amit Varma]: Like you spoke about how I think 75% or three fourths of the trucking in India is by owners

00:43:12.380 --> 00:43:14.340
[Amit Varma]: who own five trucks or less.

00:43:14.340 --> 00:43:21.500
[Amit Varma]: So it's all just a bunch of really small outfits and there aren't structures within which you

00:43:21.500 --> 00:43:22.500
[Amit Varma]: can rise.

00:43:22.500 --> 00:43:27.940
[Amit Varma]: I want to, you know, go back a little bit to that whole question of sort of caste and

00:43:27.940 --> 00:43:29.740
[Amit Varma]: divisions that we sort of spoke about.

00:43:29.740 --> 00:43:34.700
[Amit Varma]: Like one on the whole, you pointed out about how truckers see themselves as, you know,

00:43:34.700 --> 00:43:37.700
[Amit Varma]: Santhisvijat or the lowest of all castes.

00:43:37.700 --> 00:43:40.700
[Amit Varma]: But you've also spoken about, you know, when you were traveling through the north, the

00:43:40.700 --> 00:43:45.860
[Amit Varma]: divisions between Punjabis versus Haryanvis and Jats, where Punjabis are like, we were

00:43:45.860 --> 00:43:48.500
[Amit Varma]: the original truckers and it was a glamorous life.

00:43:48.500 --> 00:43:53.300
[Amit Varma]: And then these Haryanvis and Jats came and messed it up and look at Haryana and how women

00:43:53.300 --> 00:43:56.040
[Amit Varma]: are treated there, which also we'll come back to later.

00:43:56.040 --> 00:44:00.100
[Amit Varma]: And then later on, you know, when you're in the northeast, you speak about, say, the tribalism

00:44:00.100 --> 00:44:05.700
[Amit Varma]: at Imphal, where you write, quote, a sort of trust deficit is palpable in the air here.

00:44:05.700 --> 00:44:10.060
[Amit Varma]: Men size each other up warily, seeking answers to the one question preying on their minds.

00:44:10.060 --> 00:44:11.060
[Amit Varma]: Who are you?

00:44:11.060 --> 00:44:12.460
[Amit Varma]: Are you Indian or tribal?

00:44:12.460 --> 00:44:13.460
[Amit Varma]: If tribal, which tribal?

00:44:13.460 --> 00:44:15.600
[Amit Varma]: If Naga, which Naga?

00:44:15.600 --> 00:44:16.600
[Amit Varma]: Or Meti?

00:44:16.600 --> 00:44:18.160
[Amit Varma]: Or are you a Mia, a Bengali Muslim?

00:44:18.160 --> 00:44:21.740
[Amit Varma]: The answer to that question is what determines the nature of further engagement.

00:44:21.740 --> 00:44:26.520
[Amit Varma]: This breakdown of interpersonal trust means people tend to stick with their own, ensuring

00:44:26.520 --> 00:44:32.540
[Amit Varma]: this vicious cycle of identity politics and ethnic strife continues indefinitely, stop

00:44:32.540 --> 00:44:33.540
[Amit Varma]: quote.

00:44:33.540 --> 00:44:37.140
[Amit Varma]: And this is, of course, not just a problem of the trucking ecosystem, but our society

00:44:37.140 --> 00:44:39.480
[Amit Varma]: itself per se.

00:44:39.480 --> 00:44:45.860
[Amit Varma]: But is this sort of enhanced or like, I would imagine in trucking, it could go both ways.

00:44:45.860 --> 00:44:51.780
[Amit Varma]: Because you all share that common burden of the loneliness of being the long distance

00:44:51.780 --> 00:44:56.500
[Amit Varma]: trucker, as it were, that can bring you together despite all the other divisions.

00:44:56.500 --> 00:45:01.860
[Amit Varma]: But I can also imagine that why this sort of tribalism can be something that you look

00:45:01.860 --> 00:45:07.020
[Amit Varma]: for to find comfort zones, which you find among people like yourself, and therefore,

00:45:07.020 --> 00:45:08.620
[Amit Varma]: that can get enhanced.

00:45:08.620 --> 00:45:11.660
[Amit Varma]: So what was your sense of this during your travels?

00:45:11.660 --> 00:45:18.860
[Guest]: My sense was that, you know, this whole idea of India, India exists in our mind, for the

00:45:18.860 --> 00:45:25.540
[Guest]: vast bunch of people, you like an Andhra trucker going to Guwahati, he does not trust the people

00:45:25.540 --> 00:45:26.540
[Guest]: he meets over there.

00:45:26.540 --> 00:45:29.540
[Guest]: I mean, we are an extremely low trust society.

00:45:29.540 --> 00:45:34.620
[Guest]: That is one fundamental thing I learned, I mean, because we are constantly searching

00:45:34.620 --> 00:45:42.300
[Guest]: for someone who either they have kinship relationships with, or some sort of loose regional affiliation

00:45:42.300 --> 00:45:43.500
[Unknown]: is also fine.

00:45:43.500 --> 00:45:51.340
[Guest]: But this trust deficit is just immense and until the last part, until say the 19th century

00:45:51.340 --> 00:45:56.580
[Guest]: also, even the early 20th century, people would say that you are going to somewhere

00:45:56.580 --> 00:46:01.260
[Guest]: in the Deccan would say, I'm going to Hindustan or like, I'm going to, I mean, that's, that's

00:46:01.260 --> 00:46:03.260
[Guest]: the sort of world that existed, right.

00:46:03.260 --> 00:46:07.660
[Guest]: And that still does, I mean, truckers are the ones who actually have to travel, otherwise

00:46:07.660 --> 00:46:11.940
[Guest]: the others don't need to travel, I mean, either by train or something, but these guys are

00:46:11.940 --> 00:46:16.140
[Guest]: constantly in places where they are not amongst their own.

00:46:16.140 --> 00:46:21.820
[Guest]: And I would say that that only encourages regionalism, that the whole larger part about

00:46:21.820 --> 00:46:27.620
[Guest]: class solidarity, right, that does not come into the picture, any sense of class solidarity

00:46:27.620 --> 00:46:31.300
[Guest]: that I tried to find was absent, there was none.

00:46:31.300 --> 00:46:38.340
[Guest]: They are highly divided, mostly along the lines of ownership itself, I mean, who will

00:46:38.340 --> 00:46:43.420
[Guest]: you rise up against if you want to say, form a union or you want to negotiate for better

00:46:43.420 --> 00:46:47.700
[Guest]: wages, who will you rise against, you all have different owners, you can't even speak

00:46:47.700 --> 00:46:48.700
[Guest]: the same language.

00:46:48.700 --> 00:46:53.860
[Guest]: Even going from Andhra to Tamil Nadu, I struggled, because many of the truckers I've found were

00:46:53.860 --> 00:46:57.740
[Guest]: Tamil, I mean, they couldn't understand Telugu, how will these guys, how are these guys ever

00:46:57.740 --> 00:47:03.700
[Guest]: expected to come under one banner, then there's of course, caste, religion, all kinds of things,

00:47:03.700 --> 00:47:09.340
[Guest]: and this is the prime reason why we don't have any sort of trucker union in India, like

00:47:09.340 --> 00:47:16.540
[Guest]: I recently saw the Irishman, and in that I was struck by how powerful a truck union leader

00:47:16.540 --> 00:47:22.820
[Guest]: can be, I mean, if that is the sort of potential that exists to build, to bring the country

00:47:22.820 --> 00:47:28.940
[Guest]: to a standstill, if you have that sort of influence over a constituency like truckers,

00:47:28.940 --> 00:47:33.860
[Guest]: you can be immensely powerful in the country, that's what I realized after watching Irishman,

00:47:33.860 --> 00:47:39.300
[Guest]: but that sort of thing is unimaginable in India, the only sort of organization which

00:47:39.300 --> 00:47:45.460
[Guest]: claims to represent the truckers, which is AIMTC, All India Motor Transport Congress,

00:47:45.460 --> 00:47:50.940
[Guest]: that is also an association of owners, who then pass off their own interests as the interests

00:47:50.940 --> 00:47:56.580
[Guest]: of the truckers they employ. So that's how it works in India.

00:47:56.580 --> 00:48:00.140
[Amit Varma]: One of the sort of striking anecdotes in your book was where you stop at a dhaba when you're

00:48:00.140 --> 00:48:04.940
[Amit Varma]: going up north, you're making the journey up north, and you stop at a dhaba, and there's

00:48:04.940 --> 00:48:10.220
[Amit Varma]: a little kid who's running around taking the orders, and you have this trucker taking the

00:48:10.220 --> 00:48:15.420
[Amit Varma]: kid on his lap and just playing with his genitals openly in front of everybody while everybody's

00:48:15.420 --> 00:48:21.020
[Amit Varma]: laughing and even the kid is squealing and laughing. And you pointed out how it is sort

00:48:21.020 --> 00:48:25.820
[Amit Varma]: of a natural thing. It wasn't out of the ordinary there. And you wrote, quote, it's shocking

00:48:25.820 --> 00:48:30.980
[Amit Varma]: how outside as liberal havens, attitudes towards children in many parts of India seem to have

00:48:30.980 --> 00:48:36.540
[Amit Varma]: ossified in the medieval era. Child sexual abuse is terrifyingly normalized. Unlike America

00:48:36.540 --> 00:48:41.480
[Amit Varma]: where childhood is disappearing with the advent of mass TV and internet. It seems the concept

00:48:41.480 --> 00:48:47.620
[Amit Varma]: of childhood never really gained mass currency in the first place. Stop quote. And it struck

00:48:47.620 --> 00:48:52.820
[Amit Varma]: me that you also elaborated on how this sort of sanctity of childhood is this thing that

00:48:52.820 --> 00:48:57.860
[Amit Varma]: is separate from adulthood as something that, you know, carries with it so much innocence

00:48:57.860 --> 00:49:02.380
[Amit Varma]: and then gradually you come of age and all of that. And all of that is a luxury that

00:49:02.380 --> 00:49:08.020
[Amit Varma]: is only really there even conceptually for elites like us. And for much of India, it's

00:49:08.020 --> 00:49:13.060
[Amit Varma]: not the case. For much of India, the way people relate to kids is in a very instrumental way.

00:49:13.060 --> 00:49:18.140
[Amit Varma]: Like, you know, in earlier centuries, it was common to think of children only as a resource.

00:49:18.140 --> 00:49:22.340
[Amit Varma]: If you were in a time of famine, you would, you know, sell your kid. And that's one of

00:49:22.340 --> 00:49:28.620
[Amit Varma]: the things that you commented on happening here. So is that something you noted sort

00:49:28.620 --> 00:49:33.140
[Amit Varma]: of repeatedly while you were going? What do you like? Was it something that struck others

00:49:33.140 --> 00:49:37.820
[Amit Varma]: as unusual or that was a normal for them? And is it something that you got used to after

00:49:37.820 --> 00:49:41.860
[Amit Varma]: a period in time that, yeah, this is, it's natural for them to think like this and behave

00:49:41.860 --> 00:49:42.860
[Amit Varma]: like this?

00:49:42.860 --> 00:49:49.660
[Guest]: So, I mean, across Indian highways, all dhabas, literally all dhabas will employ these child

00:49:49.660 --> 00:49:54.180
[Guest]: waiters. There will be two, three of them and they will keep running around collecting

00:49:54.180 --> 00:50:01.660
[Guest]: orders and delivering stuff. So definitely I did get used to it because there was no

00:50:01.660 --> 00:50:08.260
[Guest]: option in the sense, the sort of attitude is so all permeating. In the sense, if you

00:50:08.260 --> 00:50:15.380
[Guest]: look there are 10 million child laborers in India at this time. And that is just staggering.

00:50:15.380 --> 00:50:22.460
[Guest]: And in spite of say the right to education, which makes it compulsory and also free, there

00:50:22.460 --> 00:50:28.580
[Guest]: is still this immense resistance, right? I mean, because of various socio-economic reasons

00:50:28.580 --> 00:50:36.700
[Guest]: due to poverty, all these reasons, there is resistance to enroll people, children in school.

00:50:36.700 --> 00:50:44.460
[Guest]: And that also derives a feel from a deep cultural way of looking at children itself as these

00:50:44.460 --> 00:50:49.820
[Guest]: pure entities. I mean, of course, in middle class circles, it would be scandalous to suggest

00:50:49.820 --> 00:50:58.740
[Guest]: that they don't think of their children as innocent beings. But largely they do. I mean,

00:50:58.740 --> 00:51:05.460
[Guest]: the government itself is sort of changing the laws to recognize this reality. I mean,

00:51:05.460 --> 00:51:12.380
[Guest]: right now, children under the age of 14 are allowed to work in family outfits or they

00:51:12.380 --> 00:51:17.420
[Guest]: are actually allowed. After school, you can work in your family business, which can be

00:51:17.420 --> 00:51:23.900
[Guest]: anything from PD making or working in the kirana store that your family owns. So right

00:51:23.900 --> 00:51:29.580
[Guest]: from that stage, children as this economic resource, that attitude is there. And if we

00:51:29.580 --> 00:51:37.500
[Guest]: were forced to even amend the RT to recognize that fact, it says a lot. But yeah, I would

00:51:37.500 --> 00:51:45.820
[Guest]: say it's a very difficult thing to really get rid of this attitude. Because as long

00:51:45.820 --> 00:51:51.540
[Guest]: as there are economic compulsions, like you always say, it's all incentives. And as long

00:51:51.540 --> 00:51:57.980
[Guest]: as there are economic compulsions, it's very unlikely that this attitude will also be removed.

00:51:57.980 --> 00:52:02.380
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, and I'm reminded of these, you know, the child armies of West Africa, where you

00:52:02.380 --> 00:52:06.260
[Amit Varma]: have militias made up of these 10 year olds and 11 year olds responding to a completely

00:52:06.260 --> 00:52:12.180
[Amit Varma]: different kind of incentive, which also sort of tells you how our modern notion of children

00:52:12.180 --> 00:52:18.420
[Amit Varma]: is so relatively recent. I can also see why, you know, many of sort of what the middle

00:52:18.420 --> 00:52:23.460
[Amit Varma]: class would think of as a great unboshed to use your phrase from earlier in this podcast

00:52:23.460 --> 00:52:28.860
[Amit Varma]: would be so distrustful of government. Because for example, we speak of the Right to Education

00:52:28.860 --> 00:52:32.700
[Amit Varma]: Act, but that is of course, a joke, which does nothing for children, and if anything

00:52:32.700 --> 00:52:40.260
[Amit Varma]: made things harder for them. And similarly, I think one of the things that I'm sure these

00:52:40.260 --> 00:52:46.220
[Amit Varma]: guys intuitively get is that laws don't do anything, that your lived reality is something

00:52:46.220 --> 00:52:50.540
[Amit Varma]: completely different. And, you know, I'd written about this many years ago, all of us are sort

00:52:50.540 --> 00:52:56.940
[Amit Varma]: of distressed by child labor, but there was an old Oxfam study on the situation in Bangladesh,

00:52:56.940 --> 00:53:01.140
[Amit Varma]: where, you know, there were factories which had child workers, and there was international

00:53:01.140 --> 00:53:07.740
[Amit Varma]: outrage about that. And about 30,000 child workers were laid off. And, you know, many

00:53:07.740 --> 00:53:11.820
[Amit Varma]: of the kids who were laid off actually didn't starve to death, you know, many of the girls

00:53:11.820 --> 00:53:18.620
[Amit Varma]: became prostitutes. Similarly, there was a 1995 study by UNICEF, which showed that, you

00:53:18.620 --> 00:53:23.100
[Amit Varma]: know, a bunch of well meaning peoples began a boycott of carpets made in Nepal using child

00:53:23.100 --> 00:53:28.620
[Amit Varma]: labor. And because of that, about 5000 to 7000 Nepali girls turned to prostitution,

00:53:28.620 --> 00:53:32.780
[Amit Varma]: because what was otherwise a better option working in a carpet factory was denied to

00:53:32.780 --> 00:53:36.620
[Amit Varma]: them. So, you know, we elites often think that hey, an easy option is that you get the

00:53:36.620 --> 00:53:41.140
[Amit Varma]: state to legislate and to make a law. And that said, these people will stop treating

00:53:41.140 --> 00:53:47.740
[Amit Varma]: their kids badly. But the reality is behind why all these things happen is something sort

00:53:47.740 --> 00:53:54.700
[Amit Varma]: of completely different and far more disturbing. Moving on from there, it also, you also commented

00:53:54.700 --> 00:54:00.020
[Amit Varma]: at one point on the absence of women in the landscapes that you described, like at one

00:54:00.020 --> 00:54:04.260
[Amit Varma]: point you wrote, quote, the first thing that strikes one about the highways of India, and

00:54:04.260 --> 00:54:09.620
[Amit Varma]: Rajasthan in particular, is a creepy wholesale absence of women, not a single sighting of

00:54:09.620 --> 00:54:13.900
[Amit Varma]: the female form for miles and miles, to the extent that when you finally see one idling

00:54:13.900 --> 00:54:19.300
[Amit Varma]: by the road, you tend to assume she's a sex worker, stop quote. And later on, of course,

00:54:19.300 --> 00:54:23.620
[Amit Varma]: you point out the exception to this, which is when you go to Nagaland and, you know,

00:54:23.620 --> 00:54:28.700
[Amit Varma]: that's a little bit different. But otherwise, in the roads of India, you don't, you know,

00:54:28.700 --> 00:54:35.300
[Amit Varma]: see women on the highways at all. How does this sort of affect the way that truckers

00:54:35.300 --> 00:54:41.380
[Amit Varma]: look at intergender relationships? Are women merely sort of instrumental for them that

00:54:41.380 --> 00:54:45.500
[Amit Varma]: when they can get hold of one they want, you know, sex, which they don't otherwise get

00:54:45.500 --> 00:54:51.980
[Amit Varma]: so much? How does all of that sort of feature in their mental landscapes?

00:54:51.980 --> 00:54:58.740
[Guest]: I would say, you know, this is not just limited to truckers. I mean, so much, so many of the

00:54:58.740 --> 00:55:04.500
[Guest]: men I know, right since childhood, they have interacted with women with only instrumental

00:55:04.500 --> 00:55:11.860
[Guest]: ends in mind. I mean, it could be as little as taking a notebook during school. But that's

00:55:11.860 --> 00:55:17.420
[Guest]: the extent of their interaction with women. And that is the vast majority of men in India.

00:55:17.420 --> 00:55:25.740
[Guest]: I mean, they are stunted as far as interacting with the opposite sex. So many social forces

00:55:25.740 --> 00:55:32.940
[Guest]: have sort of come together to inculcate this attitude in men. I would say, yes, among truckers,

00:55:32.940 --> 00:55:39.300
[Guest]: there is this, in some ways, I would say they do look at women as these exotic objects.

00:55:39.300 --> 00:55:46.740
[Guest]: I mean, I wouldn't say it's purely as an object of sex, but someone who is so far removed

00:55:46.740 --> 00:55:53.420
[Guest]: from their world, and who will essentially never, never, ever enter their world, except

00:55:53.420 --> 00:55:59.700
[Guest]: as a wife, as a long suffering wife, or as a prostitute with whom you have a quick high

00:55:59.700 --> 00:56:08.420
[Guest]: rate alliance. But that is the extent of their view about women. And I would say, even so

00:56:08.420 --> 00:56:18.740
[Guest]: many of the men I met in IIT, were stunted in similar ways. That is one common thread.

00:56:18.740 --> 00:56:23.420
[Guest]: In fact, this whole idea of a masculine world, I mean, I have inhabited many of these masculine

00:56:23.420 --> 00:56:29.860
[Guest]: spaces earlier at a military school, later in IIT. And this, even trucking, it's never

00:56:29.860 --> 00:56:35.660
[Guest]: totally a masculine world. But that whole, my experience in those worlds was something

00:56:35.660 --> 00:56:41.660
[Guest]: that kind of attracted me to this world. I wanted to see what that was like. And that

00:56:41.660 --> 00:56:44.980
[Guest]: is one of the reasons I could fit in also, I would say.

00:56:44.980 --> 00:56:51.900
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, and that's kind of fascinating. And all IIT students listening to this, possibly

00:56:51.900 --> 00:56:57.020
[Amit Varma]: would be nodding their head in agreement that it's exactly like that. And that sort of leads

00:56:57.020 --> 00:57:02.700
[Amit Varma]: me to wondering that how quick are we to judge other people? Like it would be fair to say,

00:57:02.700 --> 00:57:09.020
[Amit Varma]: I think, therefore, that most Indian men are misogynistic and sexist and, you know, in

00:57:09.020 --> 00:57:14.860
[Amit Varma]: their kind of approach to the world. And at different levels, they have hatred and lack

00:57:14.860 --> 00:57:19.380
[Amit Varma]: of empathy for the other, whoever the other might be in their definition. And you then

00:57:19.380 --> 00:57:25.580
[Amit Varma]: have to wonder that how much of this do you actually ascribe to someone being a bad person,

00:57:25.580 --> 00:57:30.700
[Amit Varma]: per se, because if this is a world that you've grown up in, and this is all that you know,

00:57:30.700 --> 00:57:35.140
[Amit Varma]: and you don't know any other way of looking at someone differently, you may have never

00:57:35.140 --> 00:57:41.100
[Amit Varma]: experienced the joy of, you know, that kind of a conversation or that kind of companionship

00:57:41.100 --> 00:57:44.460
[Amit Varma]: that could say come with falling in love with someone and then building a life together

00:57:44.460 --> 00:57:49.560
[Amit Varma]: or whatever. And it just seems to me that it is so easy for many of us who are much

00:57:49.560 --> 00:57:54.660
[Amit Varma]: more fortunate and have more exposure to kind of sit in judgment over them, whether they

00:57:54.660 --> 00:57:59.700
[Amit Varma]: are truckers or from IIT. What is though I think people in IIT have less of an excuse

00:57:59.700 --> 00:58:03.900
[Amit Varma]: to be a sexist, quite honestly. So what's your feeling on this?

00:58:03.900 --> 00:58:10.740
[Guest]: I would say yes, that is, you're on something there. Because even today, 95% of marriages

00:58:10.740 --> 00:58:17.260
[Guest]: are arranged marriages. Like you know, since you're a kid, since you develop some hormones,

00:58:17.260 --> 00:58:23.740
[Guest]: you know that you are going to be, your parents are going to choose your wife for you. And

00:58:23.740 --> 00:58:29.460
[Guest]: that is, it's not even a question over there. For the vast majority, it's not that you have

00:58:29.460 --> 00:58:38.020
[Guest]: an option or there's no debate on that question. So that is the first factor which, it invests

00:58:38.020 --> 00:58:43.900
[Guest]: every relationship we have with the other sex. It's basically pointless, right? Having

00:58:43.900 --> 00:58:50.260
[Guest]: any relationship then because you can't really marry a woman because your parents are going

00:58:50.260 --> 00:58:57.740
[Guest]: to choose one for you. And so what basis is there on which to connect? And then it's also

00:58:57.740 --> 00:59:03.980
[Guest]: a matter of suspicion in the sense of if you are talking to straying women and the constraints

00:59:03.980 --> 00:59:08.340
[Guest]: that are there on the women, I do not even want to get into because I can't imagine the

00:59:08.340 --> 00:59:17.420
[Guest]: level of seclusion that they often find themselves in across conservative households in India.

00:59:17.420 --> 00:59:25.340
[Guest]: So I would say yes, I feel bad also for men. I mean, it's like you said, a combination

00:59:25.340 --> 00:59:33.380
[Guest]: of various forces have conspired to develop this attitude in them. But like you said,

00:59:33.380 --> 00:59:39.380
[Guest]: I mean, it's not and it's their responsibility also to overcome those attitudes. I mean,

00:59:39.380 --> 00:59:45.980
[Guest]: which many of them do try or are at least forced to try due to this prevailing sensitivity

00:59:45.980 --> 00:59:54.220
[Guest]: towards women. It's everywhere, right? Right from the government policies. That sort of

00:59:54.220 --> 00:59:59.340
[Guest]: bombardment, I think, can be effective to some level, hopefully.

00:59:59.340 --> 01:00:05.740
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, though, I feel that even today, a lot of that bombardment is, you know, about empowering

01:00:05.740 --> 01:00:11.900
[Amit Varma]: women almost takes a paternalistic and condescending attitude towards it. And you almost, you know,

01:00:11.900 --> 01:00:16.500
[Amit Varma]: that you should worship women because they are your mother, they are your wife, always,

01:00:16.500 --> 01:00:20.700
[Amit Varma]: you know, setting them in relation to men. And, you know, which, you know, doesn't go

01:00:20.700 --> 01:00:25.420
[Amit Varma]: that much further towards sort of respecting their autonomy. And this reminds me of something

01:00:25.420 --> 01:00:29.660
[Amit Varma]: interesting that Sringda Poonam said to me when she was on my show, I think over two

01:00:29.660 --> 01:00:35.100
[Amit Varma]: years ago. And Sringda has, of course, written this great book called Dreamers about young

01:00:35.100 --> 01:00:39.300
[Amit Varma]: Indians. And she pointed out that how in many of the small towns of India, young men are

01:00:39.300 --> 01:00:45.180
[Amit Varma]: increasingly bewildered because young women are more assertive about what they want, and

01:00:45.180 --> 01:00:49.540
[Amit Varma]: so on and so forth. And the men don't have any clue of how to deal with it, because there

01:00:49.540 --> 01:00:53.980
[Amit Varma]: is nothing in the culture that teaches you what to do in such situations. I mean, we

01:00:53.980 --> 01:00:58.820
[Amit Varma]: think of education as in a narrow sense is coming from your school or college. But really,

01:00:58.820 --> 01:01:02.220
[Amit Varma]: education comes at you from your culture, including something like Bollywood, where

01:01:02.220 --> 01:01:07.780
[Amit Varma]: wooing a woman is basically always stalking a woman, right? So you have absolutely no

01:01:07.780 --> 01:01:14.060
[Amit Varma]: way of sort of figuring out what is a normal relationship. And, you know, that struck me

01:01:14.060 --> 01:01:18.980
[Amit Varma]: as interesting. The other aspect of and you know, I spent a bunch of my experience of

01:01:18.980 --> 01:01:23.740
[Amit Varma]: reading the book, kind of slowing down and trying to think about what is the interior

01:01:23.740 --> 01:01:27.980
[Amit Varma]: life of a trucker? You know, what is he like, like, okay, we can talk about all of these

01:01:27.980 --> 01:01:32.820
[Amit Varma]: attitudes, maybe towards children and towards women, we can talk about the loneliness, you

01:01:32.820 --> 01:01:37.180
[Amit Varma]: have described in great detail at different points of things that they do within their

01:01:37.180 --> 01:01:42.060
[Amit Varma]: trucking, within the ecosystem of their own little truck where somebody might play a lot

01:01:42.060 --> 01:01:47.460
[Amit Varma]: of music, and, you know, there'll be different things going on. And what I also started realizing

01:01:47.460 --> 01:01:53.380
[Amit Varma]: through the book is that they also build up their own sort of mythologies, as we do all

01:01:53.380 --> 01:01:57.100
[Amit Varma]: you know, they have all their ghost stories. It was a fascinating story about the truck

01:01:57.100 --> 01:02:01.900
[Amit Varma]: driver who got married to a Bhutani as you put it, that, and I'm just going to relate

01:02:01.900 --> 01:02:05.980
[Amit Varma]: that for my listeners, because it's such a great story. And it tells you what, and India

01:02:05.980 --> 01:02:10.900
[Amit Varma]: actually has a hoard of great folk tales around these subjects, which most of us aren't even

01:02:10.900 --> 01:02:15.620
[Amit Varma]: aware of. But the story basically was a truck drivers going on the road and there is this

01:02:15.620 --> 01:02:21.940
[Amit Varma]: ghost basically, a young woman who hitchhikes for a ride and he gives her a lift and then

01:02:21.940 --> 01:02:25.540
[Amit Varma]: he falls in love with her and he marries her. And they're living a happy life together.

01:02:25.540 --> 01:02:29.580
[Amit Varma]: And then one day his neighbors tell him that listen, we never see her outside the house.

01:02:29.580 --> 01:02:33.380
[Amit Varma]: She never like leaves the rubbish outside or whatever. We just don't see her at all.

01:02:33.380 --> 01:02:37.340
[Amit Varma]: So he's like, what is a mystery? How does no one else ever spot this woman? So one day

01:02:37.340 --> 01:02:43.100
[Amit Varma]: he goes inside his house when he's supposed to be at work. And he sees that he sees a

01:02:43.100 --> 01:02:48.500
[Amit Varma]: bunch of disconnected bones in the kitchen cooking something. And she immediately realizes

01:02:48.500 --> 01:02:53.060
[Amit Varma]: what has happened and she goes into his arms and she says, I only deceived you because

01:02:53.060 --> 01:02:57.300
[Amit Varma]: you love me so much, but now goodbye and she disappears or something. I'm sorry if that's

01:02:57.300 --> 01:03:02.860
[Amit Varma]: a digression, but I just found that such a lovely and almost moving story, a truck driver

01:03:02.860 --> 01:03:07.100
[Amit Varma]: in love with a ghost. And similarly, there are these other sort of urban legends which

01:03:07.100 --> 01:03:12.140
[Amit Varma]: they believe in, like you spoke about how truck drivers are talking about highway robberies

01:03:12.140 --> 01:03:16.500
[Amit Varma]: and they point out that in one particular place, these people not only, you know, overtake

01:03:16.500 --> 01:03:22.780
[Amit Varma]: you, make you stop and they rob you, but then they also operate on you and take your kidneys.

01:03:22.780 --> 01:03:27.220
[Amit Varma]: And that's basically it, which sounds incredibly implausible, but kind of fascinating. Tell

01:03:27.220 --> 01:03:32.780
[Amit Varma]: me a little bit about these interior mythologies, because we all need stories to keep us alive.

01:03:32.780 --> 01:03:38.060
[Amit Varma]: And relatively fortunate elite people like you and me will have our own set of stories

01:03:38.060 --> 01:03:42.380
[Amit Varma]: that keep us alive, that this is what the politics of today is, X versus Y, that is

01:03:42.380 --> 01:03:50.020
[Amit Varma]: a geopolitics. This is what is happening there. But there are sort of internal worlds which,

01:03:50.020 --> 01:03:53.460
[Amit Varma]: you know, are formed by entirely different narratives and stories. Tell me what kind

01:03:53.460 --> 01:03:56.060
[Amit Varma]: of sense you got of that while on your travels.

01:03:56.060 --> 01:04:03.500
[Guest]: Ghost stories definitely. Highways lend themselves very well to ghost stories because all kinds,

01:04:03.500 --> 01:04:09.180
[Guest]: I mean, 1.5 lakh people die every year in accidents. Most of them are probably looking

01:04:09.180 --> 01:04:17.020
[Guest]: forward to a long life. So they're essentially unfulfilled souls who can then stop the highways

01:04:17.020 --> 01:04:22.580
[Guest]: looking for some victim or in vengeance or whatever was done to them. So truck drivers

01:04:22.580 --> 01:04:27.260
[Guest]: are often involved in these accidents. So all these things come together. And yeah,

01:04:27.260 --> 01:04:31.940
[Guest]: there are a host of stories. I mean, every other place in India will have some particular

01:04:31.940 --> 01:04:37.180
[Guest]: spot which is haunted or which is known to be haunted, where you should not drive after

01:04:37.180 --> 01:04:43.780
[Guest]: a particular time. So that was widespread right from Andhra to Rajasthan. At the same

01:04:43.780 --> 01:04:50.820
[Guest]: time, as far as highway robbery is concerned, I mean, many of them have faced these sorts

01:04:50.820 --> 01:04:56.180
[Guest]: of situations. You can't like drive a truck all your life and not be wrong, essentially.

01:04:56.180 --> 01:05:03.420
[Guest]: It's a huge part of the highway economy. There are some, essentially, I mean, this is right

01:05:03.420 --> 01:05:10.420
[Guest]: since the British era, actually. So many of these nomadic tribes who earlier used to essentially

01:05:10.420 --> 01:05:18.340
[Guest]: be, say, wandering entertainers or all kinds of nomadic castes in India, they were forced

01:05:18.340 --> 01:05:24.260
[Guest]: to settle. They were branded as criminal tribes and so on. Many of them took on to highway

01:05:24.260 --> 01:05:29.900
[Guest]: robbery as a way of survival. So this has been going on since a long time in India.

01:05:29.900 --> 01:05:37.180
[Guest]: And truckers also have their various, they know what modus operandi highway robbers use.

01:05:37.180 --> 01:05:42.740
[Guest]: Some will slip in a field or some will keep nails. They are quite well versed in that.

01:05:42.740 --> 01:05:49.060
[Guest]: Of course, there's nothing they can do about it if that happens. Another interesting sort

01:05:49.060 --> 01:05:56.620
[Guest]: of observation I had about their internal world is also linked to religion. There are

01:05:56.620 --> 01:06:02.980
[Guest]: various temples, like one in Rajasthan, which I visited. Because of the immense uncertainty

01:06:02.980 --> 01:06:10.500
[Guest]: that their job has, you have to rely at some level on the supernatural to lend some level

01:06:10.500 --> 01:06:18.620
[Guest]: of certainty. So, various deities across India are known as the patron of truck drivers.

01:06:18.620 --> 01:06:24.540
[Guest]: You will find so many trucks parked outside their temple. And at the same time, they are

01:06:24.540 --> 01:06:35.180
[Guest]: their own gods. I mean, every truck will have a huge set of photos of Hindu gods. And many

01:06:35.180 --> 01:06:42.620
[Guest]: truck drivers will also conduct rituals. As soon as it's dark, they will light an Adarbati.

01:06:42.620 --> 01:06:48.900
[Guest]: All of this is meant to ensure their safety, essentially. Because it is an immensely insecure

01:06:48.900 --> 01:06:55.620
[Guest]: job. Not just losing your life, there are thieves prowling all around. In India, the

01:06:55.620 --> 01:07:00.820
[Guest]: moment you park your truck, you can assume if you leave it for a day or so, many things

01:07:00.820 --> 01:07:08.420
[Guest]: will be missing from you. There are petty criminalities rampant in all places in India.

01:07:08.420 --> 01:07:14.740
[Guest]: So, essentially, this whole concept of Jugaad, it's like the same extension, except you're

01:07:14.740 --> 01:07:20.980
[Guest]: like robbing someone using ingenious means. And so, they have to constantly be on the

01:07:20.980 --> 01:07:27.820
[Guest]: watch out for these thieves. So, that is the sort of things that preoccupy them in many

01:07:27.820 --> 01:07:34.180
[Guest]: ways, the danger of losing your life. And these stories they come up with reflect many

01:07:34.180 --> 01:07:36.900
[Guest]: of these insecurities.

01:07:36.900 --> 01:07:41.380
[Amit Varma]: One of the fascinating stories I got from your book was regarding these Sahajdari Sikh

01:07:41.380 --> 01:07:45.660
[Amit Varma]: truck drivers that you've taken a ride with and they have a picture of a Baba in the truck

01:07:45.660 --> 01:07:49.660
[Amit Varma]: whose face is rather scarred. And when they catch you looking at the photograph, they

01:07:49.660 --> 01:07:53.780
[Amit Varma]: tell you the origin story, which struck me as a fantastic origin story, which is that

01:07:53.780 --> 01:07:57.940
[Amit Varma]: the Baba looked normal. But then one day, this woman with a scarred face went to him

01:07:57.940 --> 01:08:02.180
[Amit Varma]: and said, Baba, please help me. No one will marry me because of my scarred face. So, he

01:08:02.180 --> 01:08:09.220
[Amit Varma]: transferred his scars onto himself, which is just such a remarkable story. You know,

01:08:09.220 --> 01:08:13.820
[Amit Varma]: you mentioned how big a role religion plays in their lives for sort of obvious reasons

01:08:13.820 --> 01:08:18.300
[Amit Varma]: as a source of hope and all that. And religion, of course, was famously, you know, once called

01:08:18.300 --> 01:08:22.420
[Amit Varma]: the opium of the masses. And actual opium also plays a part in their lives. Like, tell

01:08:22.420 --> 01:08:28.420
[Amit Varma]: me a bit about the role of alcohol and drugs in the trucking life. Because, you know, one

01:08:28.420 --> 01:08:33.140
[Amit Varma]: would imagine that when you live a life of such solitude and loneliness on the road all

01:08:33.140 --> 01:08:37.420
[Amit Varma]: the time, not getting enough sleep and so on, you know, what do you do for relief? There's

01:08:37.420 --> 01:08:40.620
[Amit Varma]: alcohol, there's drugs. You've described in your book about the connection between alcohol

01:08:40.620 --> 01:08:45.220
[Amit Varma]: and sex, of course, that sometimes when they, you know, prostitution rackets will often

01:08:45.220 --> 01:08:49.740
[Amit Varma]: run along the bushes where, you know, pimps will shine a light at night and they'll know

01:08:49.740 --> 01:08:53.860
[Amit Varma]: they have to stop there. And sometimes they'll get robbed, but sometimes they'll actually

01:08:53.860 --> 01:08:59.380
[Amit Varma]: see a sex worker there and the pimp will also have some daru with him in case because they

01:08:59.380 --> 01:09:05.140
[Amit Varma]: often need alcohol to sort of get all their parts working as it were. What's the role

01:09:05.140 --> 01:09:09.540
[Amit Varma]: of that alcohol and drugs sort of play in the lives of these people?

01:09:09.540 --> 01:09:15.900
[Guest]: So I'll take it one by one. So to start with alcohol, for instance, I will, I would say

01:09:15.900 --> 01:09:23.940
[Guest]: that its usage is exaggerated in the minds of the ordinary population with regard to

01:09:23.940 --> 01:09:31.260
[Guest]: our truck drivers. The majority of the truck drivers I met told me that they knew it puts

01:09:31.260 --> 01:09:37.500
[Guest]: their life at risk and that drinking and driving is dangerous. So there was that awareness

01:09:37.500 --> 01:09:42.740
[Guest]: throughout with one exception. So I must have interacted with hundreds of truckers and hitchhiked

01:09:42.740 --> 01:09:51.220
[Guest]: with around 30 to 50 of them. And nowhere did I see any consumption while on the road.

01:09:51.220 --> 01:09:57.660
[Guest]: So that is an unfair stereotype, which I would like to clarify for your listeners. And with

01:09:57.660 --> 01:10:07.500
[Guest]: regard to opium, it is used in certain parts of the country, like Punjab and Rajasthan,

01:10:07.500 --> 01:10:13.900
[Guest]: parts of Haryana. And it's interesting that India actually is one of the few countries

01:10:13.900 --> 01:10:19.420
[Guest]: which is legally allowed to cultivate opium for medicinal purposes. All these extracts

01:10:19.420 --> 01:10:24.180
[Guest]: like codeine, which goes into cough syrups, they are all derived from opium, which is

01:10:24.180 --> 01:10:30.940
[Guest]: legally cultivated in parts of Rajasthan, Madhya Pradesh, and UP. So it is from these

01:10:30.940 --> 01:10:38.980
[Guest]: areas that the Bukki, that is poppy husk is sold, which is actually legal in many parts

01:10:38.980 --> 01:10:43.820
[Guest]: of the country. In Rajasthan, for example, you have government thekas which sell this

01:10:43.820 --> 01:10:48.980
[Guest]: and many truck drivers patronize these thekas. So in these parts, there is quite a dependence

01:10:48.980 --> 01:10:54.900
[Guest]: on opium, especially in Punjab. I mean, I asked anecdotally various truck drivers, what

01:10:54.900 --> 01:11:01.700
[Guest]: percentage of truck drivers we think take opium and it was unanimously over around 75%.

01:11:01.700 --> 01:11:08.500
[Guest]: So in Punjab, the sort of opium addiction we see is quite high compared to the rest

01:11:08.500 --> 01:11:15.700
[Guest]: of the country. One of the truckers I also traveled with, was a quite a heavy user of

01:11:15.700 --> 01:11:23.020
[Guest]: the Bukki. And he would rationalize it saying that this Bukki makes me scratch myself. And

01:11:23.020 --> 01:11:27.260
[Guest]: that is a giveaway trait of an opium addict, which I found out when I was going around

01:11:27.260 --> 01:11:32.980
[Guest]: with them. And that helps me stay awake and, you know, keep all these inhuman hours. So

01:11:32.980 --> 01:11:37.860
[Guest]: that was how he rationalized it. They found kind of interesting. But at the same time,

01:11:37.860 --> 01:11:44.820
[Guest]: it is extremely addictive. The withdrawal symptoms are deadly. The driver I met, he

01:11:44.820 --> 01:11:51.020
[Guest]: himself had admitted himself twice to a Nasha Mukti Kendra and he couldn't beat the habit

01:11:51.020 --> 01:11:59.740
[Guest]: in spite of his attempts. So it's really a dangerous sort of drug which might seem its

01:11:59.740 --> 01:12:08.940
[Guest]: effects are quite mild. But the long term effects on your body is very striking. I mean,

01:12:08.940 --> 01:12:15.060
[Guest]: the face becomes gaunt and your body sort of shrivels away. And it's quite easy to make

01:12:15.060 --> 01:12:19.380
[Guest]: out someone who is dependent on opium, you know, once you get an eye for that sort of

01:12:19.380 --> 01:12:23.940
[Amit Varma]: thing. Yeah, and it's interesting how sort of, I mean, drugs, of course, are in the news

01:12:23.940 --> 01:12:28.980
[Amit Varma]: these days and sitting in Mumbai, we shouldn't possibly not comment too much upon them. But

01:12:28.980 --> 01:12:32.380
[Amit Varma]: it's interesting how a lot of things which could be considered contraband, or, you know,

01:12:32.380 --> 01:12:36.780
[Amit Varma]: sort of in the narcotic family are actually normalized parts of our cultures. And that's

01:12:36.780 --> 01:12:43.260
[Amit Varma]: fine like hung, for example, or, you know, in I'm half Bengali. So a vegetable I grew

01:12:43.260 --> 01:12:49.460
[Amit Varma]: up eating was posto, alu posto and posto is made with poppy seeds and, you know, so on.

01:12:49.460 --> 01:12:54.900
[Amit Varma]: And you know, there are different levels of damage that they can do to the person. I mean,

01:12:54.900 --> 01:13:00.140
[Amit Varma]: I don't think any Bengali will say that posto ever did him any harm. And if we speak of

01:13:00.140 --> 01:13:06.420
[Amit Varma]: being addicted to Bengali food, it's an entirely harmless sort of sense. In your book, of course,

01:13:06.420 --> 01:13:10.420
[Amit Varma]: you pointed out the gradations of this where some of it is just recreational and you use

01:13:10.420 --> 01:13:14.420
[Amit Varma]: and it's cool. And it's not a big deal. But some of the sort of the harder forms of the

01:13:14.420 --> 01:13:18.980
[Amit Varma]: drug can, you know, really damage people. And how is it looked upon in the culture?

01:13:18.980 --> 01:13:23.700
[Amit Varma]: Like, is there a realization among truckers that there is that line? And, you know, those

01:13:23.700 --> 01:13:27.380
[Amit Varma]: who cross it just can't help it. I mean, it's like addiction. I mean, what do you do? You

01:13:27.380 --> 01:13:32.100
[Amit Varma]: go a little too far down that road, and then you're sort of stuck or, you know, are a lot

01:13:32.100 --> 01:13:36.740
[Amit Varma]: of the milder forms like bookie, for example, not treated as a drug at all. I mean, it's

01:13:36.740 --> 01:13:42.260
[Guest]: just something that you have like one per hour or whatever. Yes, you're right. I mean,

01:13:42.260 --> 01:13:48.300
[Guest]: there is an acknowledgement of that line among many truck drivers. For example, one of the

01:13:48.300 --> 01:13:53.860
[Guest]: truckers I traveled with his younger brother had died due to addiction to the harder form,

01:13:53.860 --> 01:13:58.820
[Guest]: which is called chitta in Punjab. So they very well know that these particular forms

01:13:58.820 --> 01:14:05.100
[Guest]: which are often synthetic in nature and recent introductions to the landscape in bookies

01:14:05.100 --> 01:14:12.660
[Guest]: has been taken since centuries in Punjab. And if farmhands used to use it, I have used

01:14:12.660 --> 01:14:18.580
[Guest]: it throughout historically, as a way to keep up their spirits by toiling in the fields.

01:14:18.580 --> 01:14:24.180
[Guest]: So there is definitely that acceptance. But yeah, I mean, often what happens is that the

01:14:24.180 --> 01:14:30.940
[Guest]: kalasis pick up these habits from their ustads, you know, if and then once you're, you're

01:14:30.940 --> 01:14:36.900
[Guest]: biologically addicted to it, then it is in spite of your best efforts, it is very difficult

01:14:36.900 --> 01:14:43.220
[Guest]: to come up with to come out of that habit. And since your lifestyle also kind of encourages

01:14:43.220 --> 01:14:47.820
[Guest]: this the consumption, I mean, it's a monotonous job, like I said, we need to break the monotony.

01:14:47.820 --> 01:14:55.860
[Guest]: And this is a sort of crutch you come to rely upon to somehow survive these gruelling conditions.

01:14:55.860 --> 01:14:59.500
[Guest]: And that's what happens with many truckers. But yes, there is that line in their mind

01:14:59.500 --> 01:15:03.900
[Amit Varma]: for sure. You know, an interesting observation you made in your book, which I keep making

01:15:03.900 --> 01:15:08.060
[Amit Varma]: all the time. So when I saw it in your book, I'm like, it was another come to my arms Rajat

01:15:08.060 --> 01:15:12.380
[Amit Varma]: kind of moment, which is when you speak about India inhabiting different centuries simultaneously,

01:15:12.380 --> 01:15:18.140
[Amit Varma]: which, you know, I had always meant in a sense of social attitudes that we are in the 1920s

01:15:18.140 --> 01:15:21.900
[Amit Varma]: and 21st century, especially if you see the way women are treated. So there, I would say

01:15:21.900 --> 01:15:28.660
[Amit Varma]: we haven't even hit the 21st, mostly 19th and 20th, except in some select Twitter pockets.

01:15:28.660 --> 01:15:33.060
[Amit Varma]: But you know, it struck me that that line also that distinction also holds and I'm just

01:15:33.060 --> 01:15:36.780
[Amit Varma]: thinking aloud as we're speaking about the subject, that it also holds in terms of what

01:15:36.780 --> 01:15:41.020
[Amit Varma]: kind of substances you use in the culture and what the science says. For example, there

01:15:41.020 --> 01:15:46.300
[Amit Varma]: are many substances we use today, for example, coffee, in a manner of speaking, you know,

01:15:46.300 --> 01:15:51.100
[Amit Varma]: it could be said that I'm addicted to coffee. And coffee is actually more addictive than

01:15:51.100 --> 01:15:55.940
[Amit Varma]: many of the softer drugs that are actually banned. And some some would argue it's more

01:15:55.940 --> 01:16:00.940
[Amit Varma]: harmful as well. And also what I sometimes do, though I haven't taken it today, but what

01:16:00.940 --> 01:16:07.860
[Amit Varma]: I often take before recordings where I really need to focus is a cognitive drug called Modafinil.

01:16:07.860 --> 01:16:11.300
[Amit Varma]: India is one of the few places where it's actually legal over the counter. So it's called

01:16:11.300 --> 01:16:17.780
[Amit Varma]: Modeler 100, not named after a Prime Minister. And I find it sort of remarkable. I know a

01:16:17.780 --> 01:16:22.260
[Amit Varma]: lot of people who also take it though I would advise listeners not to try it just because

01:16:22.260 --> 01:16:28.060
[Amit Varma]: I do. But I just find that it is, you know, while coffee is a blunt tool, it's a sharp

01:16:28.060 --> 01:16:33.180
[Amit Varma]: tool, it just keeps me really focused and mentally fresh. Even when I'm physically very

01:16:33.180 --> 01:16:35.980
[Amit Varma]: tired, the one should take it early in the morning, if you take it in the evening, you're

01:16:35.980 --> 01:16:39.820
[Amit Varma]: not going to sleep for the whole night, definitely. So it's kind of interesting that on the one

01:16:39.820 --> 01:16:45.900
[Amit Varma]: hand, you have science going in one way, where we are getting revelations about the efficacy

01:16:45.900 --> 01:16:50.420
[Amit Varma]: and the danger and the addictiveness of different drugs. And on the other hand, you have laws

01:16:50.420 --> 01:16:54.500
[Amit Varma]: which are kind of behind the science, where, you know, maybe there are a few decades behind

01:16:54.500 --> 01:16:59.060
[Amit Varma]: the science and not really caught up with the science entirely. And then there is culture

01:16:59.060 --> 01:17:06.220
[Amit Varma]: which is on its own long, slow continuum where, you know, people have what they have. And

01:17:06.220 --> 01:17:11.500
[Amit Varma]: that's also completely sort of distant from all of these. And as I'm thinking aloud, I'll

01:17:11.500 --> 01:17:15.980
[Amit Varma]: ask you to join me in thinking aloud that even apart from this context, can you sort

01:17:15.980 --> 01:17:19.140
[Amit Varma]: of, you know, what are the different kinds of things that come to your mind where you

01:17:19.140 --> 01:17:24.300
[Amit Varma]: talk about the different centuries that India inhabits, not just sort of in this context,

01:17:24.300 --> 01:17:29.260
[Amit Varma]: but you know, because one could say that you actually took an effort to step out of your

01:17:29.260 --> 01:17:34.100
[Amit Varma]: sort of elite educated middle class bubble and sort of go around. So you know, any observations

01:17:34.100 --> 01:17:35.100
[Guest]: on this?

01:17:35.100 --> 01:17:39.660
[Guest]: You know, one constituency in India, which really comes to my mind when you talk about

01:17:39.660 --> 01:17:47.420
[Guest]: this are the nomadic tribes of India. They constitute around 5 to 10 crores of our population.

01:17:47.420 --> 01:17:52.300
[Guest]: But so many of them have not even been, they're not on electoral rolls. Many of them don't

01:17:52.300 --> 01:17:58.420
[Guest]: have any identity documents. So they are essentially invisibilized citizens of our country. I mean,

01:17:58.420 --> 01:18:03.860
[Guest]: and because they're not even on the electoral rolls, there is no sort of concerted effort

01:18:03.860 --> 01:18:10.460
[Guest]: to raise their standards of living or some targeted schemes to further welfare. I mean,

01:18:10.460 --> 01:18:17.220
[Guest]: there are but they're not as focused because they do not form a core political constituency.

01:18:17.220 --> 01:18:22.980
[Guest]: So many of these nomadic tribes, they live a lifestyle that is essentially unchanged

01:18:22.980 --> 01:18:29.620
[Guest]: from centuries, essentially. So, for example, I met the Gujjars and Bakarwals while I was

01:18:29.620 --> 01:18:34.660
[Guest]: traveling in Kashmir. And their lifestyle, I mean, they constitute what around 15 to

01:18:34.660 --> 01:18:43.540
[Guest]: 20% of Kashmir's population altogether. And they practice the right of transhumans, which

01:18:43.540 --> 01:18:50.220
[Guest]: is essentially taking your flocks up the alpine pastures, and then during the summer and then

01:18:50.220 --> 01:18:57.860
[Guest]: in the winter, you come down again. So their entire livelihood is derived from the wool

01:18:57.860 --> 01:19:02.980
[Guest]: and the dairy products and so on. So this is just one example whom I happened to encounter.

01:19:02.980 --> 01:19:08.580
[Guest]: But across India, in Maharashtra, for example, you have the Dhangars. India has such a huge

01:19:08.580 --> 01:19:14.020
[Guest]: livestock population, right? And who are the ones who are raising them? Many of them belong

01:19:14.020 --> 01:19:18.740
[Guest]: to these nomadic tribes who are wandering across the landscape, especially in Deccan,

01:19:18.740 --> 01:19:24.540
[Guest]: you will find many of these tribes. So what century are they really living in? If you

01:19:24.540 --> 01:19:30.180
[Guest]: really come to think of it? I mean, they will have the mobile phone, of course. I mean,

01:19:30.180 --> 01:19:35.140
[Guest]: mobile phone has become a proxy for modernity, right? In our minds that if someone has a

01:19:35.140 --> 01:19:41.740
[Guest]: mobile phone, then yeah, he's in the modern world. But I wonder if that is really a fair

01:19:41.740 --> 01:19:47.460
[Guest]: statement to make, because all other aspects of your life, all the other comforts which

01:19:47.460 --> 01:19:52.140
[Guest]: we take for granted, and even the way you're living your life, you're pitching tents in

01:19:52.140 --> 01:19:58.380
[Guest]: the middle of nowhere, you are constantly moving. This is essentially unchanged for

01:19:58.380 --> 01:20:04.580
[Guest]: so many years. So I mean, this is one example that comes to my mind, when we say that India

01:20:04.580 --> 01:20:05.580
[Guest]: inhabits multiple centuries.

01:20:05.580 --> 01:20:11.300
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, and it's interesting, you talk about how, you know, when that the seasonal migration

01:20:11.300 --> 01:20:14.540
[Amit Varma]: of the Gujarat is happening, and you're on your way to Kashmir at that time on that leg

01:20:14.540 --> 01:20:18.820
[Amit Varma]: of the trip. And they're all hitchhiking by the side of the road trying to grab a lift.

01:20:18.820 --> 01:20:22.380
[Amit Varma]: And at that point, it struck me that, you know, for these guys, a truck is almost like

01:20:22.380 --> 01:20:27.220
[Amit Varma]: a time machine of sorts, that otherwise, they're sort of walking with their livestock, but

01:20:27.220 --> 01:20:32.140
[Amit Varma]: just for a moment, they use the 20th century to get a little quicker. And like you said,

01:20:32.140 --> 01:20:35.340
[Amit Varma]: you know, some of them, if they have mobile phones, they also have a slice of the 21st

01:20:35.340 --> 01:20:40.820
[Amit Varma]: century in their palms. But it's just a gadget. I mean, you know, what do you do with it?

01:20:40.820 --> 01:20:47.540
[Amit Varma]: I mean, where does sort of the rest of the 21st century, so to say, come from? That's

01:20:47.540 --> 01:20:52.900
[Amit Varma]: that's, yeah, that's a lot of food for thought there. And therefore, we shall take a commercial

01:20:52.900 --> 01:20:58.340
[Amit Varma]: break and think about it.

01:20:58.340 --> 01:21:03.220
[Amit Varma]: Are you one of those people who not only loves to read, but also wants to write better? If

01:21:03.220 --> 01:21:07.220
[Amit Varma]: so, I have something for you. Since April this year, I've been teaching an online course

01:21:07.220 --> 01:21:12.580
[Amit Varma]: called the art of clear writing. Four webinars spread out over four Saturdays, in which I

01:21:12.580 --> 01:21:17.260
[Amit Varma]: share whatever I've learned about the craft and practice of writing over 25 years as a

01:21:17.260 --> 01:21:22.620
[Amit Varma]: professional writer. The course also contains many writing exercises, discussions on email

01:21:22.620 --> 01:21:28.820
[Amit Varma]: and WhatsApp and much interactivity. It costs rupees 10,000 or $150. You can check out the

