[Amit Varma]: want to bridge the gap between the thoughts in your head and the words on the page, then

01:21:38.420 --> 01:21:44.180
[Amit Varma]: the art of clear writing might be just what you need. October batches begin on Saturday,

01:21:44.180 --> 01:21:56.140
[Amit Varma]: October 3rd. So hurry and register before then. IndiaUncut.com slash clear writing.

01:21:56.140 --> 01:21:59.740
[Amit Varma]: Welcome back to the scene in the unseen. I'm chatting with Rajat Obekar, author of the

01:21:59.740 --> 01:22:06.100
[Amit Varma]: delightful book, Truck Day India. And, you know, I have to say that, for those who are

01:22:06.100 --> 01:22:10.020
[Amit Varma]: listening, I had mentioned at the start of the show that we started an hour late because

01:22:10.020 --> 01:22:14.340
[Amit Varma]: of technical glitches, where further technical glitches actually made us stop the recording

01:22:14.340 --> 01:22:20.360
[Amit Varma]: and resume two days later. So right after the question about alcohol and drugs, we had,

01:22:20.360 --> 01:22:24.540
[Amit Varma]: you know, a problem which made us sort of go offline. And now you know, three days later,

01:22:24.540 --> 01:22:28.980
[Amit Varma]: in fact, the first half was recorded on Monday. Now we are back on Thursday and we finished

01:22:28.980 --> 01:22:33.220
[Amit Varma]: at answer taken a break and we are here again. And this is sort of the first time it's happening

01:22:33.220 --> 01:22:37.340
[Amit Varma]: to me, but I thought it's apt because this is kind of both the life of truckers would

01:22:37.340 --> 01:22:43.860
[Amit Varma]: be like, which is the subject of Rajat's book, interminable delays and so on. And also Rajat

01:22:43.860 --> 01:22:50.620
[Amit Varma]: is joining the civil services. So maybe this is apt for that reason as well. So you know,

01:22:50.620 --> 01:22:54.900
[Amit Varma]: one part of the book which sort of interest, he stayed silent, but he's laughing by the

01:22:54.900 --> 01:23:00.580
[Amit Varma]: way I can see on zoom. So one part of the book which really sort of interested me, Rajat

01:23:00.580 --> 01:23:05.820
[Amit Varma]: was also about where you talk about how over time like we've already spoken about how they

01:23:05.820 --> 01:23:09.060
[Amit Varma]: sort of have a distinctive culture of their own, how they develop mythologies of their

01:23:09.060 --> 01:23:13.060
[Amit Varma]: own. And part of the book, which I really enjoyed was about how they own develop their

01:23:13.060 --> 01:23:18.180
[Amit Varma]: own vocabulary with their own aphorisms and sayings and all that. For example, one example

01:23:18.180 --> 01:23:22.660
[Amit Varma]: of that which you give, of course, is Majboori ka naam Mahatma Gandhi hai. And then within

01:23:22.660 --> 01:23:26.300
[Amit Varma]: the book, there were these sort of delightful little throwaway lines, like I'll read out

01:23:26.300 --> 01:23:32.700
[Amit Varma]: a couple of them, which I really liked. There's one, which cautions the drivers to drive carefully.

01:23:32.700 --> 01:23:37.820
[Amit Varma]: And the line is, quote, dheere dheere chaloge, baar baar miloge, tez chaloge, seede haridwar

01:23:37.820 --> 01:23:44.420
[Amit Varma]: miloge, stop quote. And then there's another one, which seems sort of almost a sad acceptance

01:23:44.420 --> 01:23:49.060
[Amit Varma]: of their lot, where they say, quote, ameeron ki zindagi chalti hai biscuit aur cake se,

01:23:49.060 --> 01:23:54.340
[Amit Varma]: driveron ki zindagi, steering aur brakes se, stop quote. And there's another one where

01:23:54.340 --> 01:23:59.100
[Amit Varma]: they are sort of reflecting on marriage, where they say, keechar mein jaoge, pyaar dhona

01:23:59.100 --> 01:24:05.500
[Amit Varma]: parega, driver se shadi karoge, toh rona parega, stop quote. And these are, you know, both

01:24:05.500 --> 01:24:11.700
[Amit Varma]: they are humorous, they are reflective, they're even self-deprecatory. You must be familiar

01:24:11.700 --> 01:24:16.660
[Amit Varma]: with a lot of, you know, this stuff there. What was your sense of sort of navigating

01:24:16.660 --> 01:24:21.100
[Amit Varma]: the lingo? And what kind of sense did it give you again, to go back to the subject we discussed

01:24:21.100 --> 01:24:25.940
[Amit Varma]: earlier of their interior lives, like do some of these become cliches or tropes that come

01:24:25.940 --> 01:24:30.140
[Amit Varma]: up again and again? And, you know, and is it often in terms of language, and this is

01:24:30.140 --> 01:24:35.140
[Amit Varma]: a broader reflection than just beyond the trucking life, that sometimes can such lingo

01:24:35.140 --> 01:24:41.220
[Amit Varma]: and such vocabulary and can such tropes offer sort of the comfort of familiarity to people

01:24:41.220 --> 01:24:43.420
[Amit Varma]: who, you know, might crave that?

01:24:43.420 --> 01:24:52.100
[Guest]: So I mean, these sort of aphorisms, they came up quite again and again, through my journey.

01:24:52.100 --> 01:24:57.580
[Guest]: And many of these are passed down from Ustad to Khalasi. I mean, it's part of the initiation

01:24:57.580 --> 01:25:03.100
[Guest]: into the world of trucking and into the world of the highway, because the highway, for them

01:25:03.100 --> 01:25:07.980
[Guest]: is this unknown beast, right, which they have to constantly negotiate, it keeps throwing

01:25:07.980 --> 01:25:14.580
[Guest]: up these challenges for them, which they have to overcome time and again. So these aphorisms

01:25:14.580 --> 01:25:21.620
[Guest]: also serve as sort of a tutorial in some ways to about how to navigate the highway. At the

01:25:21.620 --> 01:25:29.380
[Guest]: same time, it is also a way to look at their own lives, which are not the lifestyle is

01:25:29.380 --> 01:25:35.380
[Guest]: extremely gruelling. So they seek consolation in these aphorisms. I mean, of course, in

01:25:35.380 --> 01:25:40.860
[Guest]: the south, there must be different versions of these, which I could not really appreciate.

01:25:40.860 --> 01:25:48.260
[Guest]: But in Rajasthan and Punjab, these aphorisms I have developed over the years, and young

01:25:48.260 --> 01:25:54.300
[Guest]: Khalasis are especially fond of recounting them when you ask them. So that is how I learned

01:25:54.300 --> 01:26:00.780
[Guest]: about them from the Khalasis mainly. The Ustads generally are a bit of know-it-alls. They

01:26:00.780 --> 01:26:06.260
[Guest]: are the ones who are a bit more reserved usually. The Khalasis love to talk and they're young

01:26:06.260 --> 01:26:11.780
[Guest]: chaps, I mean, they are hardly 20-21. And they're quite open about their whatever they've

01:26:11.780 --> 01:26:12.780
[Guest]: learned so far.

01:26:12.780 --> 01:26:17.020
[Amit Varma]: And is there a sort of a difference between the way the Khalasis and the Ustads approach

01:26:17.020 --> 01:26:21.220
[Amit Varma]: you? And also, is there a difference in the way that they approach life? Like we spoke

01:26:21.220 --> 01:26:25.900
[Amit Varma]: before the break about how, you know, the Ustads, there is almost a sense of poignancy

01:26:25.900 --> 01:26:30.260
[Amit Varma]: because the status of the truck driver has become more lowly over the course of their

01:26:30.260 --> 01:26:34.980
[Amit Varma]: careers. And there would also be the sense of hopelessness where they realize that it's

01:26:34.980 --> 01:26:40.660
[Amit Varma]: a dead end street. Are the Khalasis also like that? Or are the Khalasis more sort of ambitious

01:26:40.660 --> 01:26:44.580
[Amit Varma]: and looking beyond trucking and so on? What was your experience of that?

01:26:44.580 --> 01:26:50.860
[Guest]: Yeah, the Ustads tend to be more jaded. They are more jaded about life. The best part of

01:26:50.860 --> 01:26:56.220
[Guest]: their lives is behind them. And there's nothing as such they have to look forward to except

01:26:56.220 --> 01:27:00.380
[Guest]: driving the truck. The Khalasis, they are just taking in the sight, you know, they're

01:27:00.380 --> 01:27:04.740
[Guest]: traveling across India, they're learning new stuff. For a couple of years, they're just

01:27:04.740 --> 01:27:10.740
[Guest]: traveling. So they are on a learning curve, if you could put it that way. So they are

01:27:10.740 --> 01:27:17.540
[Guest]: more hopeful and their worldview is also much wider. For example, one Khalasi I met in Nagaland,

01:27:17.540 --> 01:27:23.780
[Guest]: he used to listen to Rihanna, Justin Bieber, and all these folks. He was quite influenced

01:27:23.780 --> 01:27:29.940
[Guest]: by American culture. So you can see that difference. I mean, this guy was probably a couple of

01:27:29.940 --> 01:27:34.180
[Guest]: years down the line, he'll probably take up something else, because he has access to the

01:27:34.180 --> 01:27:39.780
[Guest]: English language to some degree. His worldview is much, much wider than that of the Ustads.

01:27:39.780 --> 01:27:40.780
[Guest]: So I did see that difference.

01:27:40.780 --> 01:27:44.260
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, and it's interesting, his worldview would be wider than his Ustad who is driving

01:27:44.260 --> 01:27:48.780
[Amit Varma]: a truck. But at the same time, his worldview would be wider than wherever he's coming from,

01:27:48.780 --> 01:27:53.900
[Amit Varma]: because he's traveled all around. So in a sense, he's transcending both of those contexts.

01:27:53.900 --> 01:27:57.820
[Amit Varma]: Another interesting thing that you pointed out in the book, and which didn't actually

01:27:57.820 --> 01:28:02.820
[Amit Varma]: take me by surprise at all, is the enormous warmth and generosity with which you were

01:28:02.820 --> 01:28:06.380
[Amit Varma]: treated. Like you've spoken about how, at different times, they would not allow you

01:28:06.380 --> 01:28:10.580
[Amit Varma]: to pay for anything. In one case, after you started the journey, they actually drove into

01:28:10.580 --> 01:28:14.260
[Amit Varma]: this dhaba, which you immediately knew was much more upscale than they would otherwise

01:28:14.260 --> 01:28:19.180
[Amit Varma]: go to. And they ordered a lavish meal with two paneer dishes and a lot of tandoori roti

01:28:19.180 --> 01:28:23.940
[Amit Varma]: and all that. And they insisted on paying for it, and said, ki aap toh humare mehman

01:28:23.940 --> 01:28:29.860
[Amit Varma]: hai, even though they're spending many times a day's normal allowance for food on that.

01:28:29.860 --> 01:28:34.580
[Amit Varma]: And how did you know, where do you think that comes from? Because, you know, there is this,

01:28:34.580 --> 01:28:40.900
[Amit Varma]: I often feel that we in the middle class and we elites are sort of, you know, much less

01:28:40.900 --> 01:28:46.980
[Amit Varma]: generous and much less open in that sense than the people, you know, the middle class

01:28:46.980 --> 01:28:51.740
[Amit Varma]: will refer to as a great unwashed. As you put it earlier in your episode, I don't mean

01:28:51.740 --> 01:28:56.020
[Amit Varma]: to imply that either you or I listen to refer to them like that. Like I remember when I

01:28:56.020 --> 01:29:01.060
[Amit Varma]: first went to Pakistan to cover the cricket tour in 2006. And I was covering the tour

01:29:01.060 --> 01:29:05.380
[Amit Varma]: for the Guardian and Crick Info. And the first time we were in Lahore, we needed to buy some

01:29:05.380 --> 01:29:11.500
[Amit Varma]: pencil cells for our recorders and all that. And two or three of us went to a store, and

01:29:11.500 --> 01:29:15.500
[Amit Varma]: we bought a whole bunch of supplies. And then we asked for the bill and we were chit chatting.

01:29:15.500 --> 01:29:19.260
[Amit Varma]: And at one point, we mentioned we are from India, we've come to cover the tour, everything

01:29:19.260 --> 01:29:24.060
[Amit Varma]: changes, you know, until then, it's all transactional. And, you know, whatever the moment we say

01:29:24.060 --> 01:29:28.100
[Amit Varma]: they're from India, just a warmth just overflows, and they refuse to take money. And I know

01:29:28.100 --> 01:29:32.460
[Amit Varma]: that's a cliche that they refuse to sort of take money from you. But we experience this

01:29:32.460 --> 01:29:38.580
[Amit Varma]: like with one minor exception of a small incident somewhere, we sort of experienced this everywhere

01:29:38.580 --> 01:29:43.980
[Amit Varma]: we went, you know, the generosity of the common person to what someone he does not need to

01:29:43.980 --> 01:29:48.900
[Amit Varma]: be generous to someone who is probably, you know, much better off than him. And as you

01:29:48.900 --> 01:29:53.740
[Amit Varma]: said, you experience this as Mehman Nawazi of the trucker towards someone who's, you

01:29:53.740 --> 01:29:56.980
[Amit Varma]: know, much better off who's come from another world and is going to go back to that world

01:29:56.980 --> 01:30:01.500
[Amit Varma]: soon. What did you make of that? Was it as ubiquitous as you know, the sense that I got

01:30:01.500 --> 01:30:06.940
[Amit Varma]: from the book? And how did it kind of make you feel? And did you then get conscious about

01:30:06.940 --> 01:30:11.540
[Amit Varma]: not exploiting it about, you know, taking a step back and sort of not, you know, all

01:30:11.540 --> 01:30:12.540
[Guest]: of that?

01:30:12.540 --> 01:30:19.700
[Guest]: Amit, yeah, about the middle class, the attitudes are definitely different in terms of how you

01:30:19.700 --> 01:30:26.340
[Guest]: look at money, how you look at strangers. So, what I saw among many truckers, the attitude

01:30:26.340 --> 01:30:35.900
[Guest]: was that the money keeps coming and going. And they often refer to themselves also as

01:30:35.900 --> 01:30:42.660
[Guest]: Dildar, as someone who is not tight fisted in any way. So, that is the sort of mythology

01:30:42.660 --> 01:30:48.980
[Guest]: that they have, some of them have constructed around their lifestyle. And that sort of generosity,

01:30:48.980 --> 01:30:55.020
[Guest]: I think, is tied up with that particular self conception. Among the middle class, I would

01:30:55.020 --> 01:31:01.740
[Guest]: say there is relatively less openness and generosity, in my experience. And if it is

01:31:01.740 --> 01:31:10.860
[Guest]: generosity, it is often in the mold of charity. So, there's a conscious tendency to look at

01:31:10.860 --> 01:31:17.940
[Guest]: generosity as charity or something that accrues merit. And there is a certain selfish intent

01:31:17.940 --> 01:31:22.620
[Guest]: behind it also, in terms of where you will get something in the next life or you will

01:31:22.620 --> 01:31:30.460
[Guest]: be reborn or whatever, these particular concerns are there. But unselfconscious, pure generosity

01:31:30.460 --> 01:31:36.860
[Guest]: and the kind I found was something I do not expect to find among the middle class. As

01:31:36.860 --> 01:31:42.900
[Guest]: far as how it made me feel, it made me extremely conscious. Many times I refused also, I mean,

01:31:42.900 --> 01:31:48.300
[Guest]: you have to step your foot down and when such things happen, which happened all the time.

01:31:48.300 --> 01:31:54.140
[Guest]: In the south, I felt things were a bit more transactional in terms of the attitudes of

01:31:54.140 --> 01:31:58.140
[Guest]: the truckers also. Because that whole self conception of the lifestyle, I mean, what

01:31:58.140 --> 01:32:05.740
[Guest]: I saw was that in the south, it is more of a livelihood rather than a lifestyle. So,

01:32:05.740 --> 01:32:12.260
[Guest]: in the north, it's, we actually consider it as this is my style. And this is how we do

01:32:12.260 --> 01:32:19.100
[Guest]: it. In the south, the truck is more of an asset which is meant to be monetized. And

01:32:19.100 --> 01:32:23.740
[Guest]: so for example, one trucker I met, he was used to take on hitchhikers like anything

01:32:23.740 --> 01:32:28.260
[Guest]: like there were 10 people sitting in the same truck by the end of the journey in the truck

01:32:28.260 --> 01:32:33.380
[Guest]: cabin, or a couple of them with their backs to the windshield, there were rice sacks and

01:32:33.380 --> 01:32:37.940
[Guest]: the entire truck was full. Also, that is how he earns an extra buck. I mean, I admire his

01:32:37.940 --> 01:32:43.660
[Guest]: entrepreneurs. I mean, though it might be illegal to fill people in like that. But he

01:32:43.660 --> 01:32:49.980
[Guest]: is trying to make some money out of it. And because how much does his job really make

01:32:49.980 --> 01:32:57.980
[Guest]: in terms of salaries. So that spirit I admired. In the north, I didn't find this hitchhiking

01:32:57.980 --> 01:33:04.100
[Guest]: seem to be too much except in UP. UP was insane. I mean, I didn't write about it in the book.

01:33:04.100 --> 01:33:11.380
[Guest]: But I hitchhiked from Delhi to Kanpur. And I was standing by the side of the road with

01:33:11.380 --> 01:33:16.940
[Guest]: my bag and I was just holding my finger out. And I see in five minutes, there are around

01:33:16.940 --> 01:33:22.100
[Guest]: six or seven people around me like this. They've seen that over this guy, apparently he knows

01:33:22.100 --> 01:33:29.140
[Guest]: how to find whatever vehicle they didn't even know I was going in a truck. And finally when

01:33:29.140 --> 01:33:34.220
[Guest]: the truck stopped, I see that there are already two or three people inside. And all these

01:33:34.220 --> 01:33:39.500
[Guest]: six or seven people with me are also getting in. So the sort of overpopulation there is

01:33:39.500 --> 01:33:45.780
[Guest]: in UP means that not just buses and trains, even trucks are overcrowded. I mean, there

01:33:45.780 --> 01:33:51.340
[Guest]: was not a single truck which I got in which was not already filled with people. So that

01:33:51.340 --> 01:33:58.060
[Guest]: was quite insane. Nowhere else did I find that happening. So that was quite interesting.

01:33:58.060 --> 01:34:01.780
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, and it's also also sort of interesting. I mean, I'm just wondering now you spoke about

01:34:01.780 --> 01:34:06.740
[Amit Varma]: how truck drivers see themselves as Dildar. And to some extent, I'm wondering if that

01:34:06.740 --> 01:34:10.820
[Amit Varma]: also comes from the self image that they build around themselves, that someone in the south

01:34:10.820 --> 01:34:15.180
[Amit Varma]: will build a different kind of self image where it's a livelihood and he's doing it

01:34:15.180 --> 01:34:19.460
[Amit Varma]: for that reason. And that's, you know, and whereas someone in the north, like you said,

01:34:19.460 --> 01:34:23.580
[Amit Varma]: will consider it part of their lifestyle or who they are, and especially the way the Punjabi

01:34:23.580 --> 01:34:28.940
[Amit Varma]: sees himself as being Dildar and being so, you know, exquisite mehmannawazi and all of

01:34:28.940 --> 01:34:34.260
[Amit Varma]: that. You know, there's also a section where you speak about Sikhs in trucking, where you

01:34:34.260 --> 01:34:39.020
[Amit Varma]: write, quote, interestingly, in North America, as in India, the Sikhs have become a dominant

01:34:39.020 --> 01:34:43.140
[Amit Varma]: presence in trucking. I wonder if the long tryst with migration has something to do with

01:34:43.140 --> 01:34:47.700
[Amit Varma]: why Punjabis took to driving trucks with such enthusiasm, because what is trucking but a

01:34:47.700 --> 01:34:53.620
[Amit Varma]: form of constant displacement, stop quote. And that gives a sense that for many Punjabis,

01:34:53.620 --> 01:34:58.420
[Amit Varma]: you know, just trucking and getting on there is a much more natural than it is for people

01:34:58.420 --> 01:35:03.100
[Amit Varma]: perhaps elsewhere, because so many of them do it. And then that just creates a cycle,

01:35:03.100 --> 01:35:07.020
[Amit Varma]: whether it's a virtuous cycle or a vicious cycle, one really can't comment, it depends

01:35:07.020 --> 01:35:11.100
[Amit Varma]: on their circumstances, trucking might be the best thing they have available to them.

01:35:11.100 --> 01:35:15.140
[Amit Varma]: So it might even be a virtuous cycle. And apart from that, just the sort of the lifestyle

01:35:15.140 --> 01:35:20.620
[Amit Varma]: connotations, the sort of all of that, the other sort of part of your book, which I found

01:35:20.620 --> 01:35:26.900
[Amit Varma]: quite fascinating was the relationship between the trucker and the truck, like which is very

01:35:26.900 --> 01:35:31.900
[Amit Varma]: different from the relationship between anyone else who drives a vehicle and his vehicle,

01:35:31.900 --> 01:35:36.380
[Amit Varma]: you know, like I would not feel for my car the way all truckers would feel about their

01:35:36.380 --> 01:35:40.020
[Amit Varma]: trucks. And you spent a bunch of time in this place called Sirhind where they actually,

01:35:40.020 --> 01:35:44.620
[Amit Varma]: you know, build trucks. Tell me a little bit about what is that relationship between the

01:35:44.620 --> 01:35:46.020
[Guest]: trucker and the truck.

01:35:46.020 --> 01:35:52.020
[Guest]: So I just speak about the Punjabis a bit before I get to your question. So there, the history

01:35:52.020 --> 01:35:59.660
[Guest]: of Punjab is quite tied up with that of trucking in India. So after partition, many Sikhs and

01:35:59.660 --> 01:36:05.620
[Guest]: Khatris from West Pakistan who were resettled in these refugee colonies, many of them spread

01:36:05.620 --> 01:36:12.060
[Guest]: out from there. And they started driving trucks that and this was also tied up with the World

01:36:12.060 --> 01:36:16.860
[Guest]: War Two, which had just ended and many military issue trucks had ended up in India at that

01:36:16.860 --> 01:36:25.060
[Guest]: time. And these were then refashioned by the new owners and personalized in some ways.

01:36:25.060 --> 01:36:31.620
[Guest]: And that is the close linkage. And often what happens is that whenever Punjabis go driving

01:36:31.620 --> 01:36:36.660
[Guest]: trucks, some entrepreneurial chap will set up a Punjabi dhaba also. This is also the

01:36:36.660 --> 01:36:42.580
[Guest]: reason why Punjabi food has become the sort of pan Indian food. And when we say Indian

01:36:42.580 --> 01:36:49.460
[Guest]: food, it's often Punjabi, Mughlai, that sort of thing. And there is a link with close link

01:36:49.460 --> 01:36:56.220
[Guest]: with trucking over there. Why we see that. And as far as your question goes, this whole

01:36:56.220 --> 01:37:05.500
[Guest]: personalization is linked to the emergence of centers like Sirhind. Because firstly,

01:37:05.500 --> 01:37:12.460
[Guest]: let's speak a little about why Indian trucks and trucks in the subcontinent are so colorful.

01:37:12.460 --> 01:37:19.940
[Guest]: What is the outlet? Why is this so specific to the subcontinent? So it is linked to the

01:37:19.940 --> 01:37:25.940
[Guest]: history of goods transport in India. Across history, there have been certain communities

01:37:25.940 --> 01:37:33.900
[Guest]: like the Banjaras and so on who were tasked with transporting goods. And their tradition

01:37:33.900 --> 01:37:41.020
[Guest]: was to decorate their animals. So the camels, their hair would be braided, the bullock carts

01:37:41.020 --> 01:37:46.460
[Guest]: would be decorated, the bullocks themselves would have like tassels hanging around their

01:37:46.460 --> 01:37:52.300
[Guest]: ears. And these are the same tassels which we see hanging around trucks also. And we

01:37:52.300 --> 01:38:01.180
[Guest]: also even see so one text I read dating back to the 10th or 12th century about how a ship

01:38:01.180 --> 01:38:06.300
[Guest]: was decorated during that time. We don't find too many references to this sort of thing,

01:38:06.300 --> 01:38:13.620
[Guest]: but I found one and all the motifs like from the peacocks to the eagles, I mean, everything

01:38:13.620 --> 01:38:20.420
[Guest]: was repeated. So many of these things you can find in a 10th, 12th century text on how

01:38:20.420 --> 01:38:26.900
[Guest]: to paint a ship. And all these motifs are recurring in truck art today. So I found it

01:38:26.900 --> 01:38:31.740
[Guest]: incredibly fascinating. I mean, this is not just some modern phenomenon, though its history

01:38:31.740 --> 01:38:36.860
[Guest]: has not been adequately documented. And it's not possible to document it as much because

01:38:36.860 --> 01:38:42.900
[Guest]: of its informal nature. But it has a long history. In Pakistan, for example, there has

01:38:42.900 --> 01:38:49.500
[Guest]: been a bit more documentation of truck art, because their truck art is much more intricate.

01:38:49.500 --> 01:38:54.580
[Guest]: And it's much more colorful. It's insane. I mean, you must have seen when you went to

01:38:54.580 --> 01:39:04.500
[Guest]: Pakistan. But so there we see some historical accounts of how when the artisans of princely

01:39:04.500 --> 01:39:11.460
[Guest]: states in Rajasthan and Gujarat, many of them Muslims migrated to Karachi after partition.

01:39:11.460 --> 01:39:17.140
[Guest]: And there they started, they transferred their skills to trucking. And that's how these sort

01:39:17.140 --> 01:39:25.940
[Guest]: of motifs came up in Pakistan. In India, unfortunately, we don't have as much record. But Sirhind,

01:39:25.940 --> 01:39:33.940
[Guest]: it was definitely a fascinating place to be in. And what that showed me was how much care

01:39:33.940 --> 01:39:39.860
[Guest]: a trucker puts into decorating his vehicle. And like you said, like the proprietor of

01:39:39.860 --> 01:39:46.420
[Guest]: that particular establishment told me, it's like choosing a life partner. So a lot of

01:39:46.420 --> 01:39:52.020
[Guest]: thought needs to be put into how you own the cabin. So you are because you're going to

01:39:52.020 --> 01:40:00.420
[Guest]: spend like eight out of 12 months of your life there, probably more. So it is much more

01:40:00.420 --> 01:40:05.580
[Guest]: it's like your home and you there should not be any compromises on that end. So the Punjabi

01:40:05.580 --> 01:40:11.580
[Guest]: and the Kashmiri truckers, especially the Kashmiri truckers would invest a lot. When

01:40:11.580 --> 01:40:16.820
[Guest]: I visited, it was around two lakhs in just decorating their truck, which is a lot. So

01:40:16.820 --> 01:40:23.900
[Guest]: yes, this says a lot about the relationship between a truck and a trucker. So often, they

01:40:23.900 --> 01:40:32.220
[Guest]: refer to the truck itself as a she or as a demure woman or a bride. So it's like, yeh

01:40:32.220 --> 01:40:40.380
[Guest]: meri hai, yeh meri wali hai. So all these references come up where there is the personification

01:40:40.380 --> 01:40:47.780
[Guest]: of the truck. It's given some human qualities. And ultimately, it does pay off. I mean, investing

01:40:47.780 --> 01:40:53.860
[Guest]: a loss, this amount of money and time. So they stay for one month in that establishment

01:40:53.860 --> 01:40:58.980
[Guest]: until the whole truck is made, all the design is done. One month they just wait there, supervise

01:40:58.980 --> 01:41:07.340
[Guest]: the building of the truck. That is the amount of devotion and care they put. And I don't

01:41:07.340 --> 01:41:13.260
[Guest]: think you will find that anywhere else in the world apart from the Indian subcontinent.

01:41:13.260 --> 01:41:17.140
[Amit Varma]: One of the TILs in your book and it changed the way I will look at trucks forever is that

01:41:17.140 --> 01:41:22.100
[Amit Varma]: when a manufacturer sells a truck to a trucker, he's basically selling the chassis, right?

01:41:22.100 --> 01:41:25.900
[Amit Varma]: And the rest of it, the body of the truck is something that is built and customized.

01:41:25.900 --> 01:41:29.460
[Amit Varma]: And like you pointed out, there are some places like South India, I think you pointed out

01:41:29.460 --> 01:41:33.980
[Amit Varma]: where it's very functional and they don't really care so much. But up north, the Kashmiris

01:41:33.980 --> 01:41:38.460
[Amit Varma]: and the Punjabis and different cultures, they'll have the truck done up just the way they want.

01:41:38.460 --> 01:41:44.260
[Amit Varma]: Like you quoted Mewa Singh who runs that establishment in Sirindh saying that this is like sort of

01:41:44.260 --> 01:41:48.660
[Amit Varma]: buying a home and like choosing a life partner, but also like buying a home where you want

01:41:48.660 --> 01:41:54.420
[Amit Varma]: every aspect of it sort of personalized and customized exactly as you want all the way

01:41:54.420 --> 01:41:58.340
[Amit Varma]: down to hidden compartments. So what do they do with hidden compartments?

01:41:58.340 --> 01:42:04.300
[Guest]: So hidden compartments are often used to hide contraband. Like for example, one chap I traveled

01:42:04.300 --> 01:42:10.580
[Guest]: with used to hide his bookie in there, whatever for his personal consumption. I'm sure there's

01:42:10.580 --> 01:42:16.460
[Guest]: a lot of smuggling also that happens in India. It definitely happens. And a lot of this is

01:42:16.460 --> 01:42:21.660
[Guest]: facilitated through these hidden compartments and so on because they are useful, right?

01:42:21.660 --> 01:42:27.700
[Guest]: I mean, when the state is often out there to take money from you on various pretexts,

01:42:27.700 --> 01:42:33.020
[Guest]: if there's anything you need to hide, which is very likely you will have the hidden compartments

01:42:33.020 --> 01:42:38.700
[Guest]: come in handy. But I'll also like talk a bit about the whole process. I didn't get into

01:42:38.700 --> 01:42:45.900
[Guest]: it, the process of building the truck itself. So from the chassis, there are around say

01:42:45.900 --> 01:42:56.300
[Guest]: 10 to 15 different types of artisans who are at work trying to sort of build a skeletal

01:42:56.300 --> 01:43:02.740
[Guest]: framework first around the chassis. And then you will have the radium tape, the electrician,

01:43:02.740 --> 01:43:11.260
[Guest]: the painter, the cabin maker, the welder, the artisan who will cut the chadar and in

01:43:11.260 --> 01:43:18.420
[Guest]: all these geometrical shapes. So it's a very specialized job. And often in Punjab, for

01:43:18.420 --> 01:43:23.620
[Guest]: example, I saw that literally all of these artisans were from Bihar. And in Sirindh,

01:43:23.620 --> 01:43:28.180
[Guest]: the place I visited, all of them were from one district, which is Madhubani district

01:43:28.180 --> 01:43:36.140
[Guest]: in Bihar, which itself has a rich heritage of folk art. The Madhubani paintings are quite

01:43:36.140 --> 01:43:45.100
[Guest]: famous. So it's the traditional skill in that region. And many of them come to Punjab to

01:43:45.100 --> 01:43:51.020
[Guest]: work in these establishments. And I stayed there for a couple of days. And it was a revelation.

01:43:51.020 --> 01:43:56.540
[Guest]: It was a lot of fun just talking to these chaps, talking to truck artists, trying to

01:43:56.540 --> 01:44:02.260
[Guest]: see how he how he has learned these things. And there also we find that whole Ustad Khalas.

01:44:02.260 --> 01:44:07.780
[Guest]: I mean, it's like much of India actually runs on these informal apprenticeship networks.

01:44:07.780 --> 01:44:15.660
[Guest]: I mean, formal training because it's not very well established. Everything that most Indians

01:44:15.660 --> 01:44:22.380
[Guest]: have learned, it has been from some generous person, either a relative or someone you know,

01:44:22.380 --> 01:44:29.300
[Guest]: who will very generously impart his skills so that you can pick it up. And that was quite

01:44:29.300 --> 01:44:30.300
[Amit Varma]: interesting.

01:44:30.300 --> 01:44:34.180
[Amit Varma]: And I was also, you know, struck by a part of your book where you talk about how, you

01:44:34.180 --> 01:44:38.740
[Amit Varma]: know, the roads of India itself are changing, like there is an ecosystem out there. And,

01:44:38.740 --> 01:44:42.980
[Amit Varma]: you know, there are all these different moving subcultures, as it were traveling through

01:44:42.980 --> 01:44:47.500
[Amit Varma]: these roads. But then at one point while traveling through Gujarat, you made the observation

01:44:47.500 --> 01:44:51.780
[Amit Varma]: quote, the highways in Gujarat are so slick, they've attained the soulless efficiency of

01:44:51.780 --> 01:44:56.540
[Amit Varma]: the autobahns and freeways of the West, stop quote. And elsewhere, you know, you have spoken

01:44:56.540 --> 01:45:01.660
[Amit Varma]: about how at different parts of the road, you have different dhabas catering to different

01:45:01.660 --> 01:45:07.640
[Amit Varma]: kinds of clientele like for Punjabis and so on. But at the same time, you talk about how

01:45:07.640 --> 01:45:13.060
[Amit Varma]: some of these flyovers and so on are just sort of passing them by. For example, at one

01:45:13.060 --> 01:45:17.620
[Amit Varma]: point, when you stopped at a dhaba, you say quote, business for many of these dhabas,

01:45:17.620 --> 01:45:22.100
[Amit Varma]: especially in Gujarat has been slow. Earlier, they occupied prime real estate right by the

01:45:22.100 --> 01:45:27.260
[Amit Varma]: highway. But the spree of flyover construction has bypassed many of them. Now, cars and trucks

01:45:27.260 --> 01:45:33.060
[Amit Varma]: just zoom above them, oblivious to their presence, stop quote. So is there sort of, and I know

01:45:33.060 --> 01:45:37.980
[Amit Varma]: that there are always these trade-offs and we can both bemoan the loss of the richness

01:45:37.980 --> 01:45:42.060
[Amit Varma]: of this cultural diversity in the form of the different types of dhabas. And on the

01:45:42.060 --> 01:45:49.060
[Amit Varma]: other hand, there is an increased efficiency, the quicker travel times, which also add sort

01:45:49.060 --> 01:45:54.700
[Amit Varma]: of say unseen elements to the lives of the truckers and the drivers. What sense did you

01:45:54.700 --> 01:45:59.300
[Amit Varma]: get of this from the truckers themselves? Like, is this loss something that they bemoan?

01:45:59.300 --> 01:46:04.420
[Amit Varma]: Did you feel that there is some color being lost here, which is, you know, which we don't

01:46:04.420 --> 01:46:08.380
[Amit Varma]: appreciate enough? And, you know, what were your thoughts?

01:46:08.380 --> 01:46:14.420
[Guest]: I would say the effect has largely been positive. Many truckers are happy and they can, they're

01:46:14.420 --> 01:46:19.500
[Guest]: very conscious, they can see the fact that roads have improved so much over the last

01:46:19.500 --> 01:46:24.540
[Guest]: 10-15 years, especially the national highways. So as one trucker put it to me, he says that

01:46:24.540 --> 01:46:29.420
[Guest]: it's become very easy for us. Most of the cities, we can, there's a bypass which they

01:46:29.420 --> 01:46:35.740
[Guest]: have made from which we can avoid the city itself. And almost all of the villages have

01:46:35.740 --> 01:46:40.780
[Guest]: flyovers. So our job is just to drive and there are not too many hurdles in our way.

01:46:40.780 --> 01:46:46.060
[Guest]: And that enables them to do more business because the turnaround time reduces and improves

01:46:46.060 --> 01:46:50.860
[Guest]: their income overall. And generally, it's a good thing, I would say. Of course, there

01:46:50.860 --> 01:46:56.260
[Guest]: is a lot of resistance to these things. You know, interestingly, when I visited my native

01:46:56.260 --> 01:47:02.540
[Guest]: village while on this trip in the middle, on the Karnataka coast, and what I found there

01:47:02.540 --> 01:47:08.820
[Guest]: was there are protests happening by the locals, because they are building a flyover which

01:47:08.820 --> 01:47:13.820
[Guest]: will bypass their main market by the highway. So by the highway, they have like all these

01:47:13.820 --> 01:47:17.940
[Guest]: shops and stuff, but the government is planning to build a flyover which will bypass and there

01:47:17.940 --> 01:47:23.460
[Guest]: is ferocious resistance to this. And we will not allow this flyover to be built. So you

01:47:23.460 --> 01:47:28.900
[Guest]: see the kind of challenges the government also has to overcome to bring this so called

01:47:28.900 --> 01:47:35.500
[Guest]: development. And this loss of heritage, etc. That's when all this comes up, right? When

01:47:35.500 --> 01:47:40.300
[Guest]: all these traditional establishments have been there for decades, find themselves suddenly

01:47:40.300 --> 01:47:46.780
[Guest]: bypassed. So that aspect is there. But I will say it's largely been positive.

01:47:46.780 --> 01:47:50.900
[Amit Varma]: Let's kind of move on to, I mean, we've spoken a lot about Punjab and Kashmir and all of

01:47:50.900 --> 01:47:56.380
[Amit Varma]: that. I found your section on the Northeast interesting, because interesting for reasons

01:47:56.380 --> 01:48:00.620
[Amit Varma]: that it told me about a lot more than just a trucking life. It also gave me a sense of

01:48:00.620 --> 01:48:06.780
[Amit Varma]: how the Northeast is almost such a unique part of India, if we can call it a part of

01:48:06.780 --> 01:48:10.280
[Amit Varma]: India at all. Like, you know, to sort of go back to my trip of Pakistan, my impression

01:48:10.280 --> 01:48:14.740
[Amit Varma]: through traveling through Lahore, Karachi, Islamabad, all these places, it was just like

01:48:14.740 --> 01:48:19.420
[Amit Varma]: the signs were in Urdu, but culturally, I never felt away from home. And the one place

01:48:19.420 --> 01:48:24.260
[Amit Varma]: where I did feel away from home was when I went to Peshawar and that frontier, you know,

01:48:24.260 --> 01:48:28.900
[Amit Varma]: and travel down the Khyber Pass. And there, you know, everybody looks different. And they're

01:48:28.900 --> 01:48:33.780
[Amit Varma]: speaking sort of a different language Pashto instead of Urdu. And there, you know, the

01:48:33.780 --> 01:48:39.860
[Amit Varma]: sense was kind of different, not unfriendly, not in that sense, not hostile, but just different.

01:48:39.860 --> 01:48:46.060
[Amit Varma]: And I thought that, you know, that similar difference and it's very interesting. So since

01:48:46.060 --> 01:48:52.060
[Amit Varma]: this is a show that welcomes digression, I'll take one of my own that, you know, one of

01:48:52.060 --> 01:48:57.460
[Amit Varma]: the enterprising journalists I was traveling with, he managed to do some jugaad and he

01:48:57.460 --> 01:49:01.060
[Amit Varma]: got these guys who would take us right to the edge of the Khyber Pass where the border

01:49:01.060 --> 01:49:04.820
[Amit Varma]: with Afghanistan is so we could look down on Afghanistan. And that's an area where the

01:49:04.820 --> 01:49:09.860
[Amit Varma]: army doesn't even allow Pakistanis to go, right? It's, it's just a restricted area,

01:49:09.860 --> 01:49:14.660
[Amit Varma]: sort of, so to say. And we had a couple of army guys in plainclothes accompanying us

01:49:14.660 --> 01:49:18.260
[Amit Varma]: and we got in a jeep and there were four or five of our journalists. And it was this nice

01:49:18.260 --> 01:49:21.420
[Amit Varma]: trip. And we went right to the edge where we are, you know, standing there and looking

01:49:21.420 --> 01:49:25.660
[Amit Varma]: down into Afghanistan. It was quite awesome. And we were told that if anywhere you are

01:49:25.660 --> 01:49:29.820
[Amit Varma]: stopped by one of these, whatever, whatever you do, don't say you're from India, which

01:49:29.820 --> 01:49:35.180
[Amit Varma]: is kind of obvious, right? So at one point, these guys stopped us. And this dude, with

01:49:35.180 --> 01:49:39.740
[Amit Varma]: this big gun, and by the way, guns are ubiquitous. We went to the gun market in Peshawar, where

01:49:39.740 --> 01:49:45.580
[Amit Varma]: you can just, you know, just buy a gun like you're buying oranges. And anyway, so this,

01:49:45.580 --> 01:49:49.580
[Amit Varma]: this army dude with a big gun who stopped us, he just looks me in the face from like

01:49:49.580 --> 01:49:54.860
[Amit Varma]: seven inches away and says, kahan se ho? And I said, sir, Karachi se aaye hai. And he said,

01:49:54.860 --> 01:50:00.540
[Amit Varma]: Pakistan se aaye ho. As if Pakistan is another country, right? As if, you know, India is

01:50:00.540 --> 01:50:04.540
[Amit Varma]: not the problem. Pakistan is a foreign country to those guys. And I of course thought of

01:50:04.540 --> 01:50:09.100
[Amit Varma]: that as you know, many Kashmiris must be looking at India that way. But apart from that, I

01:50:09.100 --> 01:50:13.980
[Amit Varma]: got a sense of, I've always, you know, had a sense of the Northeast a little bit like

01:50:13.980 --> 01:50:18.780
[Amit Varma]: that. And I was really struck by this lovely phrase you use where you talk about going

01:50:18.780 --> 01:50:24.620
[Amit Varma]: from India to almost India, you know, and I thought that's such a lovely phrase. Tell

01:50:24.620 --> 01:50:29.740
[Amit Varma]: me a little bit about your experience of Northeast India. Like, what did you expect? And what

01:50:29.740 --> 01:50:35.340
[Amit Varma]: did you find? And what were your impressions? And, you know, is it comparable to, you know,

01:50:35.340 --> 01:50:38.380
[Amit Varma]: what I just sort of spoke about in my indulgent digression?

01:50:38.940 --> 01:50:45.260
[Guest]: Northeast India was possibly the biggest unknown in this entire trip, for me as well. Because

01:50:45.260 --> 01:50:49.500
[Guest]: I didn't know anyone over there, not a single, I mean, except for Meghalaya, where I had

01:50:49.500 --> 01:50:56.060
[Guest]: friends, but in Nagaland and Manipur, I didn't know anyone. So I was quite nervous, actually.

01:50:56.060 --> 01:51:05.180
[Guest]: And the sort of reputation that particular highway enjoys NH 39. So there, one out of

01:51:05.180 --> 01:51:11.820
[Guest]: six days, the highway is one because of these strikes, which are called by various insurgent

01:51:11.820 --> 01:51:20.300
[Guest]: groups. And my journey itself began on a not a very positive note. Because when I visited

01:51:20.300 --> 01:51:24.780
[Guest]: the map, like I started off from the map or in Nagaland, which is in the plains, and pretty

01:51:24.780 --> 01:51:31.180
[Guest]: much indistinguishable from the rest of India. So there, I found out that some insurgent

01:51:31.180 --> 01:51:35.420
[Guest]: group has called a bun and the highway shut down for two days, and you can't go anywhere,

01:51:35.420 --> 01:51:41.020
[Guest]: you're stuck there. So that's the note on which the journey itself began. And going

01:51:41.020 --> 01:51:48.300
[Guest]: forward, I was hoping it would be a bit more safer. And it was because I encountered these

01:51:49.100 --> 01:51:55.180
[Guest]: three chaps who were absolutely amazing. Amar Akbar, Anthony, they call themselves, but

01:51:55.180 --> 01:52:02.940
[Guest]: their real names were Rahul, Michael and Mohammed. And it's almost like my brother, when he read

01:52:02.940 --> 01:52:09.180
[Guest]: these, that particular chapter, he asked me, Are you sure you're not making this up?

01:52:09.180 --> 01:52:18.300
[Guest]: I was like, No, not at all. Because I myself was so taken aback by this thing. I mean,

01:52:18.300 --> 01:52:23.580
[Guest]: you have a Hindu Muslim Christian in one truck. And the interesting thing here, there is not

01:52:23.580 --> 01:52:30.140
[Guest]: just the difference in religion, it's actually the difference in ethnicity. And as I write

01:52:30.140 --> 01:52:36.540
[Guest]: in the book, all these three people spoke languages that belong to different language

01:52:36.540 --> 01:52:41.420
[Guest]: families all together. I mean, in one truck, I mean, where would you find that sort of thing

01:52:41.420 --> 01:52:48.540
[Guest]: in the world, let alone India. One of them was a Munda Adivasi from Jharkhand originally,

01:52:48.540 --> 01:52:55.820
[Guest]: who had come to Assam generations ago as a tea worker. So he essentially spoke Munda at home,

01:52:55.820 --> 01:53:02.940
[Guest]: which is an Austro Asiatic language. Another chap spoke Bodo, which is a Tibeto-Burman language. And

01:53:02.940 --> 01:53:07.660
[Guest]: one of them was a Bengali Muslim. So he spoke an Indo-Aryan language. So

01:53:09.180 --> 01:53:16.540
[Guest]: these fault lines are so many in the Northeast. In India, we just think of caste, but there is

01:53:16.540 --> 01:53:23.820
[Guest]: religion, there is tribe, and even among the Hindus, there's caste. So quite an incredible

01:53:23.820 --> 01:53:31.340
[Guest]: place to be in. But the sense that you got about Pakistan in Peshawar, I would say definitely

01:53:31.340 --> 01:53:39.660
[Guest]: got it. People would repeatedly ask me if I was from India. And that was that question often was,

01:53:40.540 --> 01:53:47.500
[Guest]: often came from a place of curiosity and slight suspicion also, because of the history of

01:53:48.060 --> 01:53:53.340
[Guest]: the relationship between India and those parts in the ASFA, for instance, is still

01:53:53.340 --> 01:54:00.700
[Guest]: implemented over there. So that was there. But it was a totally different place. I mean,

01:54:02.140 --> 01:54:08.940
[Guest]: it reminded me more of the Southeast Asia that I had seen in the Lonely Planet documentaries and

01:54:09.660 --> 01:54:19.020
[Guest]: so on, and not as much of India. And ultimately, I kind of fled from Manipur eventually as I write

01:54:19.020 --> 01:54:26.060
[Guest]: in the book, because I have been on the road for four months. And then there were gunshots

01:54:26.060 --> 01:54:31.900
[Guest]: outside my hotel in the dead of the night, which I still don't know what exactly happened. But

01:54:31.900 --> 01:54:38.380
[Guest]: it sort of unnerved me. And you realize that you are in an environment that is so radically

01:54:38.380 --> 01:54:45.180
[Guest]: different from mainland India in so many ways, that there is no, there is a tremendous sense

01:54:45.180 --> 01:54:52.700
[Guest]: of insecurity, especially in Imphal. Kohima I quite liked. Kohima was great. There's so many

01:54:52.700 --> 01:55:00.140
[Guest]: amazing bookshops. And the place in general is quite vibrant. I mean, apart from the fact that

01:55:00.140 --> 01:55:06.060
[Guest]: everything shuts down at 6.30, and only the restaurants stay open till 8.30. Apart from that,

01:55:06.860 --> 01:55:13.660
[Guest]: the place was quite young and I didn't feel out of the place over there. But Imphal definitely

01:55:13.660 --> 01:55:20.300
[Guest]: gave me the creeps as a place. And ultimately, I decided to go back from there. But the experience

01:55:20.300 --> 01:55:27.340
[Guest]: was an eye opener throughout right from Assam to Manipur. And I would recommend listeners to

01:55:28.220 --> 01:55:38.380
[Guest]: visit sometime just to see what amazing landscapes and just the kind of linguistic ethnic diversity

01:55:38.380 --> 01:55:43.900
[Amit Varma]: India has. It'll blow your mind for sure. You know, I was struck by you know, how you've written about

01:55:43.900 --> 01:55:50.300
[Amit Varma]: the massive Korean influence in Imphal and Manipur. And also, you know, speaking of linguistic

01:55:50.300 --> 01:55:54.540
[Amit Varma]: diversity, I was also fascinated by this new language, which you described to me like, of

01:55:54.540 --> 01:55:59.580
[Amit Varma]: course, like, like you pointed out, there are all these different language families, Austroasiatic

01:55:59.580 --> 01:56:04.780
[Amit Varma]: and Tibetan, Burmese and Indo-Aryan, which are kind of mingling together. And you spoke about

01:56:04.780 --> 01:56:09.180
[Amit Varma]: this new language, which has kind of come out at the interest evolved at the intersection of all

01:56:09.180 --> 01:56:16.220
[Amit Varma]: of these called Nagamese. Tell me a little bit about that. So Nagamese, I found like because of

01:56:16.220 --> 01:56:21.740
[Guest]: this tremendous diversity, you have to arrive at a common language in which you can converse like

01:56:21.740 --> 01:56:29.980
[Guest]: the lingua franca. And in Deemapur and some other parts of Nagaland, Nagamese is that standard

01:56:29.980 --> 01:56:37.420
[Guest]: language. It's a mix of Naga words, Assamese, Bengali, Hindi. It's like, it's not an entirely

01:56:37.420 --> 01:56:43.180
[Guest]: formed language. It's a Creole language. It's not a fully developed language, so to speak. But

01:56:43.180 --> 01:56:49.420
[Guest]: people do get by with that. And its history is dated, dates back to centuries. Apparently,

01:56:49.420 --> 01:56:54.540
[Guest]: the Nagas evolved this because the Assamese revenue collectors, merchants, they would frequently come

01:56:54.540 --> 01:57:01.500
[Guest]: up to the hills to extract tribute or whatever. So this sort of language evolved to enable

01:57:01.500 --> 01:57:07.420
[Guest]: communication between the Nagas and the Assamese. Now, of course, it has, the scope of the language

01:57:07.420 --> 01:57:12.940
[Guest]: itself has expanded. It has also taken in Hindi words. There was a tremendous Bihari migration

01:57:12.940 --> 01:57:20.140
[Guest]: in Deemapur and even in the Northeast everywhere. So lot of Biharis who are, I mean, almost all the

01:57:20.140 --> 01:57:25.820
[Guest]: vegetable vendors I saw in Coimbatore were from Bihar. Or the people who are selling frogs and

01:57:25.820 --> 01:57:34.220
[Guest]: silkworms in Deemapur were from Jharkhand. It's insane the amount of migration that happens in

01:57:34.220 --> 01:57:40.460
[Guest]: India and all the interesting encounters this leads to. And of course, all the linguistic

01:57:40.460 --> 01:57:46.220
[Guest]: developments it ultimately leads to. And Nagamese is the best example of that.

01:57:46.220 --> 01:57:50.620
[Amit Varma]: Yeah. And I was also kind of struck by your description of how they sometimes call themselves

01:57:50.620 --> 01:57:56.780
[Guest]: West Southeast Asia, if I remember correctly. Yeah. So one insurgent group has branded itself

01:57:56.780 --> 01:58:04.380
[Guest]: as the group of not Northeast India, but West Southeast Asia, which is an extremely convoluted

01:58:04.380 --> 01:58:08.780
[Guest]: way. I mean, if you add the North over there, then you will have all the cardinal directions

01:58:08.780 --> 01:58:16.620
[Amit Varma]: in that name. So yeah, I was also kind of struck by sort of the political economy of what's

01:58:16.620 --> 01:58:22.860
[Amit Varma]: happening in terms of the struggles, like you, of course, spoke about, you know, the sort of

01:58:22.860 --> 01:58:27.660
[Amit Varma]: insurgents and the battles that they're in. And I'll kind of take another digression because when

01:58:27.660 --> 01:58:34.620
[Amit Varma]: I was, I had written an essay a long time back about the Maoist insurgencies in, you know, the

01:58:34.620 --> 01:58:41.500
[Amit Varma]: East of India. And I'd also use the same concept while talking about the gangsters of UP. But it's

01:58:41.500 --> 01:58:46.460
[Amit Varma]: essentially a concept which was formulated by this economist called Mankar Olson. And it's a concept

01:58:46.460 --> 01:58:51.180
[Amit Varma]: of roving bandits and stationary bandits. And the way Olson talks about it is that imagine you're a

01:58:51.180 --> 01:58:55.260
[Amit Varma]: village and you're just living and, you know, there's no one ruling over you and you're just

01:58:55.260 --> 01:58:59.020
[Amit Varma]: living life. But every once in a while bandits will come and they'll wipe you out and they'll

01:58:59.020 --> 01:59:04.380
[Amit Varma]: go away. And now there are two kinds of bandits. One kind of bandit is a roving bandit, which is

01:59:04.380 --> 01:59:09.180
[Amit Varma]: a bandit who is passing by. And therefore, the incentives of those roving bandits are just to

01:59:09.180 --> 01:59:14.300
[Amit Varma]: take everything they can and destroy the place and leave it completely barren. And then there

01:59:14.300 --> 01:59:18.620
[Amit Varma]: are the stationary bandits and they are the roving bandits who come there and then they decide that

01:59:18.620 --> 01:59:22.940
[Amit Varma]: let us just stay here and milk this place. There's no need to destroy it. And they basically become

01:59:22.940 --> 01:59:28.140
[Amit Varma]: the state. So the state is a stationary bandit, but their incentives are different. They don't

01:59:28.140 --> 01:59:33.340
[Amit Varma]: want to destroy these people. They just want to keep them at the level where they can continue

01:59:33.340 --> 01:59:38.700
[Amit Varma]: taking sort of tributes from these people and continue taking hafta or taxes or whatever you

01:59:38.700 --> 01:59:43.900
[Amit Varma]: call it. They are the state. And it seems to me that a lot of sort of low level conflict that is

01:59:43.900 --> 01:59:49.340
[Amit Varma]: happening in India is a conflict between a state that hasn't quite managed to establish the rule

01:59:49.340 --> 01:59:53.820
[Amit Varma]: of law and become the stationary bandit, which gives it the monopoly on violence. And these

01:59:53.820 --> 01:59:59.500
[Amit Varma]: other people who are on one hand, they're roving bandits. And sometimes they themselves try to play

01:59:59.500 --> 02:00:05.740
[Amit Varma]: the role of stationary bandits, like in parts of the Red Corridor where, you know, the insurgents

02:00:05.740 --> 02:00:12.380
[Amit Varma]: will also try to provide some of those sort of services. Would that sort of framework fit what

02:00:12.940 --> 02:00:17.340
[Amit Varma]: you saw in the Northeast? Because like at one point there is a striking quote by you where you

02:00:17.340 --> 02:00:21.980
[Amit Varma]: say, quote, there is no real difference between the policemen and the insurgents. It's the kind

02:00:21.980 --> 02:00:26.860
[Amit Varma]: of situation where in the same house, one brother will be a policeman and the other an Andarwala,

02:00:26.860 --> 02:00:30.700
[Amit Varma]: he says only half joking, you're quoting someone here. And they work together in a climate of

02:00:30.700 --> 02:00:37.340
[Amit Varma]: connivence. Chor chod chachere bhai hote hai, he says, but with no humor this time. So what was

02:00:37.340 --> 02:00:43.020
[Amit Varma]: your sense of the dynamics of that kind of situation while you were there, especially as

02:00:43.020 --> 02:00:49.660
[Amit Varma]: you were kind of worried about your own safety in that regard? So your description fits in perfectly

02:00:49.660 --> 02:00:56.300
[Guest]: with what's happening over there, because they essentially run a parallel government. And it is

02:00:56.300 --> 02:01:02.940
[Guest]: well established. It's an open secret that government employees themselves pay part of

02:01:02.940 --> 02:01:10.380
[Guest]: their salaries to the insurgent groups. And all the businessmen have to pay something. If you want

02:01:10.380 --> 02:01:15.660
[Guest]: to run any kind of business, you have to pay something to the NSCNIM, which is the leading

02:01:15.660 --> 02:01:22.060
[Guest]: insurgent group in Nagaland. Recently, there was quite a bit of a controversy after the governor

02:01:22.060 --> 02:01:28.380
[Guest]: of Nagaland, R N Ravi, he called out all these insurgent groups, called them armed, not rebels,

02:01:28.380 --> 02:01:37.340
[Guest]: armed criminals, armed groups, which they did not take well. So there was even controversy after

02:01:38.220 --> 02:01:44.300
[Guest]: he said that all government employees should disclose which of their relatives are in these

02:01:44.300 --> 02:01:51.660
[Guest]: insurgent groups. And that led to a lot of discontent among the government employees

02:01:51.660 --> 02:01:57.420
[Guest]: over there. So that situation still exists. And it has existed over the years, because

02:01:58.460 --> 02:02:04.940
[Guest]: the insurgents over there are not really insurgents, so to say, they have a proper camp,

02:02:05.660 --> 02:02:10.940
[Guest]: what are very few kilometers away from Bimapur, where they have their own military setup. And

02:02:11.740 --> 02:02:19.180
[Guest]: since a couple of decades, they have a ceasefire with the Indian state, which has essentially

02:02:19.180 --> 02:02:24.540
[Guest]: allowed them all these privileges of collecting hafta or taxes from the truckers. Truckers

02:02:24.540 --> 02:02:29.580
[Guest]: especially have to bear the brunt of this. There's also a lot of highway robbery on S39.

02:02:30.620 --> 02:02:35.740
[Guest]: So they are constantly put at risk because of this. And it's bewildering, you know, when you

02:02:35.740 --> 02:02:40.060
[Guest]: go there, you can't figure out which is the state and which are the insurgents, you can

02:02:40.060 --> 02:02:45.420
[Guest]: never really tell. Because the policemen sometimes of course will wear the uniform.

02:02:45.420 --> 02:02:49.340
[Guest]: But otherwise, so many of the people who are collecting all these entry tax, etc, they'll

02:02:49.340 --> 02:02:55.740
[Guest]: have nothing on, they look damn shady. They look like dangerous people, just by the looks on their

02:02:55.740 --> 02:03:00.780
[Guest]: faces. And I can never really tell which insurgent group this guy belongs to. So there's this,

02:03:01.500 --> 02:03:08.780
[Guest]: it's like the fog of war, right? That's the sort of situation you find yourself in. And that can

02:03:08.780 --> 02:03:14.700
[Guest]: be very unsettling. I mean, that was part of the reason why I constantly felt a bit insecure over

02:03:14.700 --> 02:03:18.700
[Amit Varma]: there. Because you don't know who the authority is and who the threat is. And it also strikes,

02:03:18.700 --> 02:03:22.940
[Amit Varma]: I should also possibly clarify on your behalf that when you say the people collecting entry

02:03:22.940 --> 02:03:28.780
[Amit Varma]: taxes had nothing on, what you mean is they had no uniform on. I am sure that they had something on.

02:03:29.660 --> 02:03:33.260
[Amit Varma]: Apart from that, you know, when I was reading the section of your book and the Northeast,

02:03:33.260 --> 02:03:37.900
[Amit Varma]: I was actually selfishly hoping that, you know, you would stay there longer and, you know, take

02:03:37.900 --> 02:03:42.300
[Amit Varma]: one for the team, stay there for a couple of years and write a bit more because that was just such a

02:03:42.300 --> 02:03:46.460
[Amit Varma]: fascinating section. Now, another sort of fascinating aspect of the book, which I really

02:03:46.460 --> 02:03:53.740
[Amit Varma]: enjoyed, and coming back now to India in general, is your sort of detailed breakdown of the trucking

02:03:53.740 --> 02:04:00.380
[Amit Varma]: economy. You know, where you talk about where you sort of talk about, we've already spoken about,

02:04:00.380 --> 02:04:04.620
[Amit Varma]: you know, Sattaisvijat and, you know, Chhattisvijat, but you've broken down the trucking

02:04:04.620 --> 02:04:10.220
[Amit Varma]: sort of economy into, you know, it's different constituent parts, like there is a consigner,

02:04:10.220 --> 02:04:14.620
[Amit Varma]: and then there is the operator. And in between them, there is a booking agent, and there is a

02:04:14.620 --> 02:04:20.060
[Amit Varma]: commission agent. And a lot of the trucking economies of consists of really small players,

02:04:20.060 --> 02:04:27.100
[Amit Varma]: like 75% of it is, you know, people who own less than five trucks. And, you know, so on,

02:04:27.100 --> 02:04:32.300
[Amit Varma]: you've spoken about the information asymmetry, the cartels, corruption, and all of that all,

02:04:32.300 --> 02:04:37.660
[Amit Varma]: you know, again, could be a whole book about the political economy of that. And it's so fascinating.

02:04:37.660 --> 02:04:41.740
[Amit Varma]: Tell me a little bit about that. What was the journey of discovery through these structures

02:04:41.740 --> 02:04:49.100
[Amit Varma]: that sort of exist and within the trucking industry in India? First thing that really

02:04:49.100 --> 02:04:56.620
[Guest]: struck me was the level of cartelization that is there in the industry. It's quite insane. I mean,

02:04:56.620 --> 02:05:03.900
[Guest]: a very small proportion of the booking agents who are essentially the guys who are the middlemen for

02:05:03.900 --> 02:05:09.420
[Guest]: the consignors, the guy wants to send his money. These guys essentially control the prices. And

02:05:09.420 --> 02:05:14.620
[Guest]: there is no transparency in how this price is fixed. Because it's all over the phone,

02:05:14.620 --> 02:05:20.380
[Guest]: it's extremely opaque. And the way these deals are structured is that

02:05:21.660 --> 02:05:28.300
[Guest]: the share of the proceeds which goes to the trucker is negligible compared to the effort

02:05:28.300 --> 02:05:32.780
[Guest]: and the risk that he is putting in this whole enterprise. And he's the one who's putting his

02:05:32.780 --> 02:05:40.140
[Guest]: life at risk, right, essentially by going on the road all year. And, of course, he's the one who's

02:05:40.140 --> 02:05:47.500
[Guest]: doing the grunt work. But around 40 to 50% of the entire amount that the consignor pays goes to the

02:05:47.500 --> 02:05:54.460
[Guest]: middleman. So as one trucker put it to me, India is a country of Dalals. And that really struck me

02:05:54.460 --> 02:06:03.660
[Guest]: because across the landscape, I mean, I don't know if there is any estimate on what proportion of

02:06:03.660 --> 02:06:10.220
[Guest]: India earns its living just by being a middleman. I mean, I'm sure it's going to be huge,

02:06:10.220 --> 02:06:17.340
[Guest]: right from the agricultural markets, where we see the dominance of the Arhatiyas to the

02:06:17.340 --> 02:06:25.420
[Guest]: sort of fixers that exist even outside government offices who can get your files passed. I mean,

02:06:25.420 --> 02:06:32.460
[Guest]: these are all middlemen, right, who are somehow earning a living by doing as little as possible

02:06:32.460 --> 02:06:39.660
[Guest]: and getting as much as possible in return. And this is the trucking industry is also no stranger

02:06:39.660 --> 02:06:45.420
[Guest]: to this. In fact, I would say it's one of the industries which is highly dominated by intermediaries.

02:06:45.420 --> 02:06:51.500
[Guest]: So that was quite a revelation. How I found all this was by going to these transport nagars,

02:06:51.500 --> 02:06:57.260
[Guest]: which are ubiquitous. They are there in almost every small and big city. You will have one

02:06:57.260 --> 02:07:03.340
[Guest]: transport nagar where all the trucks will go. The offices of all the middlemen will be over there,

02:07:03.340 --> 02:07:11.100
[Guest]: who will connect the supplier to the trucker. And these places are quite great. I mean,

02:07:11.100 --> 02:07:17.580
[Guest]: you can just go to any office, sit, the guy will offer you some chai, a couple of more

02:07:17.580 --> 02:07:21.820
[Guest]: cups and you can just sit there and chat. They don't have much on their hands, they'll have their

02:07:21.820 --> 02:07:27.980
[Guest]: phone in between, but they're happy to chat usually. So I spent quite a lot of time in

02:07:27.980 --> 02:07:34.860
[Guest]: these transport nagars across India. Every place I went to, I would spend one day in the transport

02:07:34.860 --> 02:07:41.340
[Guest]: nagar, just try to talk to people and just figure out how things work there. So that was quite

02:07:41.340 --> 02:07:50.140
[Guest]: interesting. And the corruption in the industry, it accounts for around 50,000 crore a year.

02:07:51.020 --> 02:07:59.900
[Guest]: So the latest estimate says that around 50,000 crores rupees is paid in bribes by truckers.

02:07:59.900 --> 02:08:09.260
[Guest]: It is staggering. It's 5 trillion rupees in just one year. And that was quite insane.

02:08:09.980 --> 02:08:16.140
[Guest]: And these arrangements are highly organized. That was another striking thing. The truckers in

02:08:16.140 --> 02:08:21.020
[Guest]: Udaipur pointed out to me, they are actually given these coded receipts,

02:08:21.020 --> 02:08:25.980
[Guest]: like there will be something written on it, QSS, just to clarify to the guy who's

02:08:25.980 --> 02:08:31.740
[Guest]: going to extract money ahead that you have already paid it. And it's stunning how organized it is.

02:08:32.780 --> 02:08:39.980
[Guest]: And the truckers of course bear the brunt of this. Every person who stops them extracts some

02:08:39.980 --> 02:08:47.260
[Guest]: money from them. And the survey said that around 40% of them give no reason at all.

02:08:47.260 --> 02:08:55.580
[Guest]: And the interesting thing is that around 30% of them take money in the name of Mata Ka Jagran.

02:08:55.580 --> 02:09:01.740
[Guest]: That some of these local groups will say that, okay, we have this Mata Ka Jagran here happening.

02:09:01.740 --> 02:09:09.100
[Guest]: So then this is not even the state. These are just random people and who may be linked to

02:09:09.100 --> 02:09:16.060
[Guest]: the political class in some way, but it's not government officials. So this is another thing

02:09:16.060 --> 02:09:22.140
[Guest]: which was quite striking because there is no difference as such between the state and these

02:09:23.020 --> 02:09:29.980
[Guest]: sort of shadowy figures who are linked to the local political economy in many ways.

02:09:29.980 --> 02:09:36.540
[Guest]: In Goa, for instance, one chap told me that all the money that is extracted from them,

02:09:36.540 --> 02:09:43.340
[Guest]: Goa is like a lot of mining happens there. It used to happen. And trucks have a terrible

02:09:43.340 --> 02:09:48.700
[Guest]: time in Goa like drivers. I mean, our experiences, of course, is that of an idyllic vacations.

02:09:48.700 --> 02:09:55.020
[Guest]: But for truckers, Goa is just a terrible place. And he says the majority of the people who

02:09:55.020 --> 02:10:01.340
[Guest]: collect this money are just agents of some local politician. There is a blurring between

02:10:01.980 --> 02:10:10.620
[Guest]: the state and you realize what the level of rule of law is that exists in reality on Indian

02:10:10.620 --> 02:10:17.420
[Guest]: highways. And throughout the recurring pattern was of this only the complete breakdown of rule

02:10:17.420 --> 02:10:25.820
[Guest]: and law in many ways, sometimes by the state itself and sometimes by these extra legal authorities.

02:10:26.460 --> 02:10:31.740
[Amit Varma]: No, and that's, that's so fascinating to me, like the state as the supposed stationary bandit,

02:10:31.740 --> 02:10:37.260
[Amit Varma]: but not managing to be the stationary bandit efficiently enough. So all of these little

02:10:37.260 --> 02:10:42.220
[Amit Varma]: other sort of roving bandits becoming stationary. Therefore, while I'll come back to the corruption

02:10:42.220 --> 02:10:48.140
[Amit Varma]: angle of it, because that's so fascinating. But first, you know, to go back to the way the

02:10:48.140 --> 02:10:52.300
[Amit Varma]: the trucking economy is structured. So tell me if I got that right, there is a consigner who has to

02:10:52.300 --> 02:10:56.540
[Amit Varma]: send goods somewhere. And there is a trucker who is actually taking the goods somewhere.

02:10:56.540 --> 02:11:01.020
[Amit Varma]: And in between, there are two kinds of agents. One is a booking agent who is dealing with the

02:11:01.020 --> 02:11:05.740
[Amit Varma]: consigner and saying, okay, this is the kind of money I'll take from you to get the job done.

02:11:05.740 --> 02:11:11.820
[Amit Varma]: And below that is the commission agent, who is a guy who the booking agent contacts and who is

02:11:11.820 --> 02:11:17.980
[Amit Varma]: then passing the job on to the trucker himself. Now, over here, what is happening is, as you

02:11:17.980 --> 02:11:22.780
[Amit Varma]: pointed out, there is asymmetry of information. Nobody knows what the guy above him in the food

02:11:22.780 --> 02:11:29.180
[Amit Varma]: chain is really charging. And this is a huge problem. So give me a sense of supposing if you

02:11:29.180 --> 02:11:34.460
[Amit Varma]: have any idea of a broad, mota mota idea of these kind of figures, that supposing I am a consigner,

02:11:34.460 --> 02:11:41.420
[Amit Varma]: and I am paying 100 rupees to get my goods taken from X to Y, how much of that 100 is going to the

02:11:41.420 --> 02:11:49.420
[Guest]: trucker? I would say around 60 of that will go to the trucker. Yeah, 50 to 60 will go to that

02:11:49.420 --> 02:11:59.020
[Guest]: trucker. The intermediaries take around 40 to 50% of whatever the money is. The booking agents will

02:11:59.580 --> 02:12:03.100
[Guest]: take more than the commission agent. That's really interesting because I

02:12:03.100 --> 02:12:06.860
[Amit Varma]: cannot imagine that if someone manages to disrupt the market and clean up some of the friction in

02:12:06.860 --> 02:12:12.860
[Amit Varma]: between, then the consigner can pay 90 instead of 100. And the trucker can take 70 instead of

02:12:13.820 --> 02:12:18.540
[Amit Varma]: 60. And you can still have enough leftover for the middleman. But I guess that the middlemen

02:12:18.540 --> 02:12:23.500
[Amit Varma]: themselves are a kind of mafia and they control access. And it would be very difficult to break

02:12:23.500 --> 02:12:29.420
[Guest]: into that kind of market, right? Yeah, in many ways, you know. So you know,

02:12:29.420 --> 02:12:36.940
[Guest]: I have talked to some startup folks also, you know, who are trying to break this stranglehold

02:12:36.940 --> 02:12:43.420
[Guest]: of the intermediaries. And so theoretically, it's so easy, right? You make one nice portal,

02:12:43.420 --> 02:12:49.500
[Guest]: where you connect the consigner to the trucking agent himself, and you just eliminate the

02:12:49.500 --> 02:12:54.700
[Guest]: middleman. Theoretically, it sounds so simple. But like you said, the middlemen are like a proper

02:12:54.700 --> 02:13:00.700
[Guest]: mafia. So the offices of these guys, they were working in Vishakhapatnam at that time,

02:13:00.700 --> 02:13:08.060
[Guest]: their offices were attacked, broken into, pretty much trashed by the goondas of these middlemen,

02:13:08.060 --> 02:13:14.300
[Guest]: who realized that these guys are gaining some traction in the area and cutting our business.

02:13:14.860 --> 02:13:23.180
[Guest]: So they are quite a powerful segment in this industry. And it all works on the phone, right?

02:13:23.180 --> 02:13:29.740
[Guest]: That sort of tech adoption and penetration of technology in this industry is especially low,

02:13:29.740 --> 02:13:35.980
[Guest]: compared to many others. And given India's terrible networks, I mean, when you go to the highway in

02:13:35.980 --> 02:13:41.100
[Guest]: the city itself, often it's bad. When you go to the highways, though, no question. So all that

02:13:41.100 --> 02:13:48.380
[Guest]: makes it very difficult to sort of address this stranglehold of the intermediaries. And most of

02:13:48.380 --> 02:13:53.420
[Guest]: the startups that are in this space, this logistic space and in the business of removing the

02:13:53.420 --> 02:14:00.860
[Guest]: intermediaries, most of them have given up. There are a couple of them, but largely most of them

02:14:00.860 --> 02:14:08.700
[Guest]: have shut shop. That tells a lot about how much control and influence the intermediaries have.

02:14:08.700 --> 02:14:12.940
[Amit Varma]: That's fascinating. I was also, you know, struck by different parts of your book,

02:14:12.940 --> 02:14:18.620
[Amit Varma]: there is the intermingling of sort of history with your narrative. And at one point, you talk about

02:14:18.620 --> 02:14:24.060
[Amit Varma]: how Shersa Suri did so many things to eliminate the highway robbery problem, because even though

02:14:24.060 --> 02:14:28.380
[Amit Varma]: you don't have trucks in that time, you do have goods being transported and you do have the

02:14:28.380 --> 02:14:33.420
[Amit Varma]: problem of highway robbers. And I'll ask you a bit to elaborate upon that and elaborate on,

02:14:33.420 --> 02:14:38.380
[Amit Varma]: you know, then the irony that in modern times, as you say, in your book, I'll read out again

02:14:38.380 --> 02:14:43.100
[Amit Varma]: from what you've written, where you write, quote, if we were to compare medieval and modern India,

02:14:43.100 --> 02:14:47.900
[Amit Varma]: it would seem things have both changed and remained the same. While the highways today

02:14:47.900 --> 02:14:52.860
[Amit Varma]: are relatively safer and punishments less drastic, official extraction from truckers,

02:14:52.860 --> 02:14:58.380
[Amit Varma]: highway robbery by another name, continues unabated, perpetrated with the aid of extractive

02:14:58.380 --> 02:15:03.580
[Amit Varma]: innovations such as mechanical, stop quote, and mechanical is within single quotes, it's obviously

02:15:03.580 --> 02:15:07.900
[Amit Varma]: a particular kind of fine that you described, which was very opaque, and then you got to the

02:15:07.900 --> 02:15:13.340
[Amit Varma]: bottom of it. And you found that it was for flouting rules, which are itself written so vaguely

02:15:13.340 --> 02:15:17.500
[Amit Varma]: that they're open to interpretation. And therefore, it is sort of highway robbery. And as you pointed

02:15:17.500 --> 02:15:22.540
[Amit Varma]: out, there is highway robbery by the state and by others. So it seems that there is a culture

02:15:22.540 --> 02:15:27.500
[Amit Varma]: of highway robbery, which has come all the way from Shersa Suri and all that. And that's also a

02:15:27.500 --> 02:15:33.020
[Amit Varma]: kind of a fascinating period. So tell me about sort of the historical development of the culture

02:15:33.020 --> 02:15:39.660
[Guest]: of our roads, so to say. The two main highways of India, historically Uttarapath and Dakshinapath.

02:15:39.660 --> 02:15:50.140
[Guest]: So these two were the historical main highways. One Uttarapath linked Peshawar to Bengal. And

02:15:50.860 --> 02:15:57.660
[Guest]: the Dakshinapath linked Bihar, the Pataliputra through Madhya Pradesh, etc. to the west coast

02:15:57.660 --> 02:16:03.740
[Guest]: and to Maharashtra. So and from there, there were other routes which went across South India. These

02:16:03.740 --> 02:16:10.620
[Guest]: were the two main routes. And what we see from history is that highway robbers have existed as

02:16:10.620 --> 02:16:17.420
[Guest]: long as there were roads. So for example, Angulimal, who features like in the Buddhist Jataka

02:16:17.420 --> 02:16:24.860
[Guest]: stories, he was a notorious highway robber. And this tradition continues. The state did try

02:16:24.860 --> 02:16:32.140
[Guest]: historically to curb this menace and make things safer. For example, in the Mahajanapada period,

02:16:32.140 --> 02:16:39.900
[Guest]: around 600 BC, there were officials who were appointed called Rajukas, whose job was to

02:16:39.900 --> 02:16:45.660
[Guest]: protect the travelers and the merchants. That was their essential job. Of course, there were also

02:16:45.660 --> 02:16:50.940
[Guest]: customs agents called the Kamikaz, who would take money from them, legitimate taxes and so on. But

02:16:50.940 --> 02:16:59.420
[Guest]: in practice, highway robbery has been a part and parcel of the transportation culture in India,

02:16:59.420 --> 02:17:08.140
[Guest]: because we think of highway robbery as this violent, the coyotes and bandits who will come

02:17:08.140 --> 02:17:17.020
[Guest]: and attack you. But highway robbery also takes place when someone without any legitimacy and

02:17:17.020 --> 02:17:22.700
[Guest]: without any authority is taking money from you, maybe not using the threat of violence itself,

02:17:22.700 --> 02:17:28.060
[Guest]: but who's taking money from you in a matter of fact way and you are giving it to them. And that

02:17:28.060 --> 02:17:34.540
[Guest]: has continued across history. So we have like petty Rajas. So any sort of political authority

02:17:34.540 --> 02:17:39.820
[Guest]: who establishes himself in certain area, he will say that, okay, whatever roads are passing through

02:17:39.820 --> 02:17:44.860
[Guest]: this, these are under my control. And anyone who are passing through the entry tax that we call it

02:17:44.860 --> 02:17:51.420
[Guest]: right now, that sort of entry tax has been collected across history. And Sher Shah Suri played

02:17:51.420 --> 02:17:59.180
[Guest]: an interesting role in curbing this, because what he realized was all these highway robbers operate

02:18:00.540 --> 02:18:06.620
[Guest]: with the knowledge and the active cooperation of the village headmen, which are around these

02:18:06.620 --> 02:18:12.620
[Guest]: highways. So the village headmen were a very influential constituency at that time. And

02:18:12.620 --> 02:18:17.980
[Guest]: so what he did was that he said, if any the coyote or robbery takes place in your area,

02:18:17.980 --> 02:18:24.860
[Guest]: it is the job of the village headman called the Mukaddam to either find the culprit and compensate

02:18:24.860 --> 02:18:29.980
[Guest]: the traveler for the loss of his property. And if someone is killed, then it is the job of the

02:18:29.980 --> 02:18:36.300
[Guest]: Mukaddam to find the guy or you, the Mukaddam himself will lose his life. So that's a bit

02:18:36.300 --> 02:18:45.340
[Guest]: drastic, but it worked during his period, at least. And we have the writings of a Mughal

02:18:45.340 --> 02:18:51.500
[Guest]: historian actually, called Abbas Sherwani, who writes about the kind of changes he brought.

02:18:51.500 --> 02:18:57.180
[Guest]: Now Sher Shah Suri as a figure is just fascinating. He is one of my favorite figures from Indian

02:18:57.180 --> 02:19:04.060
[Guest]: history, partly because he has so much to do with the development of the highway system in India.

02:19:04.060 --> 02:19:11.580
[Guest]: And he was the one who renovated the Uttarapatha, which what we know as the Grand Trunk Road now.

02:19:12.300 --> 02:19:20.860
[Guest]: So he renovated it from across the entire terrain. He also built new roads from Agra to

02:19:21.740 --> 02:19:28.060
[Guest]: Gujarat, Agra to Marwar and so on. So he expanded the road network a lot firstly,

02:19:28.060 --> 02:19:34.460
[Guest]: and he also built a network of thousands of Sarais, Sarais being these resting

02:19:35.100 --> 02:19:41.740
[Guest]: places for travelers. And many of these Sarais later then grew to become Kasbahs. I mean,

02:19:41.740 --> 02:19:48.780
[Guest]: they were the nucleus of urbanization. So there would be a marketplace which would form around

02:19:48.780 --> 02:19:54.140
[Guest]: this Sarai. Slowly that marketplace would turn into a small town. And so that is how a lot of

02:19:54.140 --> 02:19:58.940
[Guest]: urbanization happened in India also. Like even today, the Mughal Sarai, Begu Sarai, all these

02:19:58.940 --> 02:20:04.780
[Guest]: are prominent junctions, right? And the name reveals that they originated from a simple,

02:20:04.780 --> 02:20:10.540
[Guest]: small Sarai, a resting house for travelers. So that was another one of his contributions.

02:20:10.540 --> 02:20:16.380
[Guest]: Overall, I feel as a figure, he is massively underrated in Indian history, partly because

02:20:16.380 --> 02:20:24.780
[Guest]: he is this sort of an upstart figure who rises from nowhere, rags to riches, often uses

02:20:24.780 --> 02:20:33.500
[Guest]: unscrupulous means to gain power. And he is not like the perfect role model, say to say, for a

02:20:34.220 --> 02:20:42.780
[Guest]: newly independent India, which was looking for these very straight-jacketed figures like Akbar

02:20:42.780 --> 02:20:48.700
[Guest]: and Ashoka, whose values fit in with that of a budding nation, like they are secular. At the

02:20:48.700 --> 02:20:55.580
[Guest]: same time, they are tolerant, they are non-violent. And all these factors led us to privilege these

02:20:55.580 --> 02:21:00.780
[Guest]: figures other than Sher Shah Suri, who was a brilliant administrator. And he was also secular

02:21:00.780 --> 02:21:05.340
[Guest]: in his own way. I mean, he did not really discriminate as such in his army and so on,

02:21:05.340 --> 02:21:11.260
[Guest]: in terms of recruitment. And his administrative innovations themselves were quite remarkable.

02:21:11.260 --> 02:21:16.460
[Guest]: He introduced the rupaiya, which we know as the rupee today. He introduced the use of Hindi,

02:21:16.460 --> 02:21:21.180
[Guest]: Hindavi as it was known then, in the local administration. Earlier, only Persian was used.

02:21:21.180 --> 02:21:27.420
[Guest]: So this led to good things for the local population. So I'm basically a big fan of

02:21:27.420 --> 02:21:33.420
[Guest]: Sher Shah Suri. And I think he should be more celebrated, maybe a biopic someday.

02:21:34.540 --> 02:21:38.060
[Amit Varma]: Maybe a biopic someday. If Akshay Kumar is listening to this, we are in trouble,

02:21:38.060 --> 02:21:42.220
[Amit Varma]: Rajat, and it is your fault. And it's interesting that you talk about sort of building up Akbar and

02:21:42.220 --> 02:21:47.260
[Amit Varma]: Ashoka as modern heroes, because even there, I mean, people contain multitudes. And even they

02:21:47.260 --> 02:21:52.780
[Amit Varma]: had different aspects to them. And it's almost as if, you know, they were at one point, you know,

02:21:52.780 --> 02:21:58.700
[Amit Varma]: sort of presented as these people with these very salutary sides of themselves, Ashoka,

02:21:58.700 --> 02:22:04.380
[Amit Varma]: the man of peace and all of that, and Akbar being secular and whatever, when you know,

02:22:04.380 --> 02:22:09.820
[Amit Varma]: there were other aspects to their character as well. And perhaps we'll really mature as a society

02:22:09.820 --> 02:22:13.820
[Amit Varma]: when we can get closer to this embracing of complexity. I kind of smiled when you were

02:22:13.820 --> 02:22:17.980
[Amit Varma]: talking about the mukaddams because I thought all my listeners will immediately say, here is where

02:22:17.980 --> 02:22:23.100
[Amit Varma]: Amit talks about incentives. And that's actually a place to talk about incentives in two ways.

02:22:23.100 --> 02:22:26.700
[Amit Varma]: Like one, of course, if you're telling the mukaddam that if you don't catch the thief,

02:22:26.700 --> 02:22:31.180
[Amit Varma]: I will behead you. That is an incentive for the mukaddam to do the job of policing well.

02:22:31.180 --> 02:22:36.460
[Amit Varma]: But it is also an incentive for him to catch any random guy he doesn't like and say that is a thief,

02:22:36.460 --> 02:22:43.020
[Amit Varma]: I have caught him, behead him and end of story. So one, you know, those go in different ways.

02:22:43.020 --> 02:22:50.060
[Amit Varma]: And that would also be unseen in a modern context, because what would we know of the many people

02:22:50.060 --> 02:22:55.260
[Amit Varma]: wrongfully implicated by medieval mukaddams. But, you know, coming back to sort of your journeys,

02:22:55.260 --> 02:22:59.340
[Amit Varma]: it seems to me that when you travel, especially when you travel in the way that you are doing,

02:22:59.340 --> 02:23:05.420
[Amit Varma]: where you're going deeper into context, and, you know, where traditions arise from, and so on,

02:23:05.420 --> 02:23:09.900
[Amit Varma]: you're not just traveling through space, you're also traveling through time, right?

02:23:09.900 --> 02:23:14.540
[Amit Varma]: You're not just exploring India as it is today, you're also exploring the history of India.

02:23:15.180 --> 02:23:21.340
[Amit Varma]: You also get drawn to do sort of history writing, and is travel writing to some extent,

02:23:21.340 --> 02:23:26.380
[Amit Varma]: history writing? Is there a continuum? And do you like, you know, you were earlier talking about

02:23:26.380 --> 02:23:31.980
[Amit Varma]: the fascinating history of truck art, where, you know, 12th century ships could look like

02:23:31.980 --> 02:23:38.220
[Amit Varma]: 21st century trucks, and how that's been documented so much in Pakistan, and so much of that is

02:23:38.220 --> 02:23:43.420
[Amit Varma]: fascinating, and then Shersha Suri and all that. So do you also then feel like writing a travel

02:23:43.420 --> 02:23:47.260
[Amit Varma]: book sometime, which is a travel through time and not a travel through space as such, which is

02:23:47.260 --> 02:23:53.980
[Guest]: just sort of historical? You know, I am a huge history buff. And the more I read history over

02:23:53.980 --> 02:24:00.940
[Guest]: the years, I realized that travel accounts play such a huge role in our reconstruction,

02:24:00.940 --> 02:24:05.820
[Guest]: the reconstruction of our history as we know it. And like right from Yuan Tsang to

02:24:06.780 --> 02:24:12.540
[Guest]: Ibn Battuta, these guys have left such pivotal account, which give us so much specific

02:24:12.540 --> 02:24:18.940
[Guest]: information about India at that point. And it is so valuable. But even in these accounts, you know,

02:24:18.940 --> 02:24:27.340
[Guest]: I find that there is very little mention of the common people about the texture of ordinary life

02:24:27.340 --> 02:24:33.660
[Guest]: as it were. Because these guys often hung around in noble circles, their audience itself was

02:24:34.620 --> 02:24:39.420
[Guest]: often of a courtly background. So probably they didn't mention they didn't find it important

02:24:39.420 --> 02:24:47.260
[Guest]: enough to mention it. And, but there is so much poverty of these accounts of the ordinary people,

02:24:47.260 --> 02:24:53.020
[Guest]: I mean, historians struggle so much to reconstruct how the life of an ordinary peasant or an ordinary

02:24:53.020 --> 02:24:59.740
[Guest]: merchant would have been. And that I feel really bad about it, because it's so dominated by these,

02:24:59.740 --> 02:25:05.580
[Guest]: the doings of these kings and so on. But I mean, how much of that really mattered to the ordinary

02:25:05.580 --> 02:25:12.780
[Guest]: peasant at that point, I highly doubt much of it did. So my motivation for travel writing is,

02:25:12.780 --> 02:25:21.020
[Guest]: is for me, travel writing is nothing but making the mundane interesting, and just capturing the

02:25:21.020 --> 02:25:25.900
[Guest]: texture of everyday life. I mean, there are other genres, I mean, a lot of nonfiction academic

02:25:25.900 --> 02:25:31.340
[Guest]: research, which gets deep into topics and presents a thoughtful analysis of them. But for me, travel

02:25:31.340 --> 02:25:37.660
[Guest]: writing has a separate job, which is to just document the ordinary and make it interesting

02:25:37.660 --> 02:25:43.660
[Guest]: for the reader. And who knows, hopefully someday, these accounts will serve as a way to recreate

02:25:44.220 --> 02:25:49.420
[Guest]: history of the early 21st century. I mean, and that is my ultimate goal in the long term,

02:25:49.420 --> 02:25:54.780
[Guest]: that is what really motivates me. And that's why I'm only interested in writing about the

02:25:54.780 --> 02:26:00.140
[Guest]: ordinary people of India, and what their life about their hopes or what they think,

02:26:00.140 --> 02:26:05.500
[Guest]: these things often go undocumented in other places. I mean, travel writing is the place

02:26:05.500 --> 02:26:10.620
[Guest]: to cover them. And I feel very strongly about that. And yeah, like I said, I mean,

02:26:10.620 --> 02:26:15.980
[Guest]: it's deeply connected with history, right? I mean, our attitudes, or the particular positions,

02:26:15.980 --> 02:26:21.180
[Guest]: the circumstances we find ourselves in, various people have their own little histories, they're

02:26:21.180 --> 02:26:26.380
[Guest]: linked to their family and their caste. And all of this is what is India for me, I mean, for me,

02:26:26.380 --> 02:26:33.660
[Guest]: you know, just like we say that, in every person resides God, for me, in every person resides India.

02:26:33.660 --> 02:26:39.260
[Guest]: And every person is a representative of India in so many ways. And that is what I'm

02:26:40.060 --> 02:26:47.420
[Guest]: very moved to explore and write about. Hopefully, in the future, I'll get to write more.

02:26:48.780 --> 02:26:53.500
[Amit Varma]: No, that that multiplicity of visions at an individual level is kind of fascinating to me,

02:26:53.500 --> 02:26:58.540
[Amit Varma]: you know, earlier in this episode, you spoke about how we experience Goa as tourists,

02:26:58.540 --> 02:27:05.180
[Amit Varma]: but truck drivers experience it as, you know, a much more dangerous, difficult place to navigate.

02:27:05.180 --> 02:27:09.260
[Amit Varma]: I remember in my years playing poker professionally, I encountered it in a whole different

02:27:09.260 --> 02:27:13.740
[Amit Varma]: way, which is kind of, you know, quite apart from that. And this is a beautiful passage from your

02:27:13.740 --> 02:27:19.420
[Amit Varma]: book, which kind of speaks to that, which comes from where, when sort of you are in the northeast,

02:27:19.420 --> 02:27:23.420
[Amit Varma]: and you go to sleep somewhere on the highway in a truck, and you wake up in the morning, and you

02:27:23.420 --> 02:27:27.660
[Amit Varma]: take a little walk, and the Andarwalas referred to here are of course, the extremists that you're

02:27:27.660 --> 02:27:32.060
[Amit Varma]: worried about. And at this point, you write this passage, I'll quote, quote,

02:27:32.060 --> 02:27:36.780
[Amit Varma]: My fear of Andarwalas interrupting our journey has been unfounded. Instead, I have witnessed one

02:27:36.780 --> 02:27:41.740
[Amit Varma]: of the most splendid sunrises of my life. I guess such is the nature of travel, when the true nature

02:27:41.740 --> 02:27:46.620
[Amit Varma]: of a place reveals itself, or perhaps when you realize there is no true nature of a place.

02:27:46.620 --> 02:27:51.020
[Amit Varma]: It is merely the images we associate with the place that shape our perception of it.

02:27:51.020 --> 02:27:55.500
[Amit Varma]: The human brain is incapable of associating more than a handful of things with this.

02:27:55.500 --> 02:28:00.300
[Amit Varma]: Its job is to underplay complexity and categorize reality into simplicity.

02:28:00.300 --> 02:28:04.220
[Amit Varma]: That's why one must never internalize anything the world tells you about a place.

02:28:04.220 --> 02:28:08.780
[Amit Varma]: The only way to travel is to forget everything you think you know about a place, discover it

02:28:08.780 --> 02:28:14.380
[Amit Varma]: anew, forge new associations, associations that are all your own. I for one knew that after this

02:28:14.380 --> 02:28:20.860
[Amit Varma]: trip, I will always remember this sunrise when I think of Nagaland and not insurgents or headhunting

02:28:20.860 --> 02:28:26.620
[Amit Varma]: tribals. Stop coding. This was such a beautiful passage in one of the highlights of the book.

02:28:26.620 --> 02:28:31.340
[Amit Varma]: And this also, you know, leads to sort of a conflict within the travel writer, which in a

02:28:31.340 --> 02:28:36.380
[Amit Varma]: very minor way, I think I felt when, you know, in earlier small travels I have made, like when I was

02:28:36.380 --> 02:28:41.340
[Amit Varma]: traveling to Pakistan in 2006, I live blogged the event, I would put up multiple posts in a day,

02:28:41.340 --> 02:28:47.180
[Amit Varma]: and I was blogging a lot. And at one point, I realized that there is a danger here. And the

02:28:47.180 --> 02:28:54.300
[Amit Varma]: danger is that trying, because of that imperative that I have given myself, of trying to find the

02:28:54.300 --> 02:29:00.220
[Amit Varma]: extraordinary in the mundane, where I might write about a chalk and just imbue it with significance,

02:29:00.220 --> 02:29:03.820
[Amit Varma]: while for the person around there, it's just a chalk, it's just a pillar.

02:29:06.380 --> 02:29:11.180
[Amit Varma]: And the other aspect of that, of course, is that as a local person, where I am in my cities,

02:29:11.180 --> 02:29:15.980
[Amit Varma]: whether it's Mumbai or whatever, and Mumbai is also, you know, has so many layers of,

02:29:15.980 --> 02:29:20.460
[Amit Varma]: you know, all the different centuries and the influences that are here. And both of us,

02:29:20.460 --> 02:29:25.260
[Amit Varma]: of course, are in Mumbai right now, although remote, because of this dreaded pandemic.

02:29:25.820 --> 02:29:30.300
[Amit Varma]: So question there is that then there is a trade off that on the one hand, you want to take a step

02:29:30.300 --> 02:29:34.780
[Amit Varma]: out where you're suddenly more mindful of everything, and therefore in a position to

02:29:34.780 --> 02:29:41.660
[Amit Varma]: recognize the special, where it might otherwise be normalized. But on the other hand, there might

02:29:41.660 --> 02:29:47.100
[Amit Varma]: also be the tendency for the travel writer, the imperative, so to say, the incentive almost,

02:29:47.100 --> 02:29:52.540
[Amit Varma]: to find something special in everything that is ordinary. Is that something that you've thought

02:29:52.540 --> 02:29:57.900
[Amit Varma]: about? Like, how does one navigate? On the one hand, the travel writer's gaze is going to be

02:29:58.540 --> 02:30:02.860
[Amit Varma]: a little deeper, but is there a danger that it goes sort of too deep?

02:30:03.660 --> 02:30:06.940
[Guest]: That's an interesting question. I mean, I have thought about it in the

02:30:06.940 --> 02:30:15.100
[Guest]: sense that, yeah, it, it is possible to go overboard in contextualizing a place.

02:30:16.380 --> 02:30:22.700
[Guest]: I mean, often what happens is that you go a bit too deep. I mean, for the I'm, when I'm writing,

02:30:22.700 --> 02:30:27.260
[Guest]: I always think about the reader. And for me, the reader is someone who like has a smartphone

02:30:27.260 --> 02:30:33.020
[Guest]: within range, and who's going to pick that up the moment you lose his attention. So I

02:30:33.020 --> 02:30:42.380
[Guest]: that my attempts always are to set the context, but not to the extent where I am losing sight of

02:30:43.420 --> 02:30:48.780
[Guest]: the place I am in. You know, often what happens is that you get into the history of a place and so

02:30:48.780 --> 02:30:56.780
[Guest]: on. And you lose sight of what is in front of you, which often is mundane, like you said,

02:30:56.780 --> 02:31:04.460
[Guest]: so there is that risk. But overall, I think the job of the travel writer is to open someone's

02:31:04.460 --> 02:31:10.860
[Guest]: eyes to the fascinating realities of multiplicities of the world around you. And of the ordinary

02:31:10.860 --> 02:31:16.300
[Guest]: person who probably thinks yaar yeh kya pakao cheez hai yeh bahar jo hai. But the travel writer's

02:31:16.300 --> 02:31:22.300
[Guest]: job is to make him see the beauty in it. And for me, that is what it is. I mean, I am someone who

02:31:22.300 --> 02:31:31.100
[Guest]: likes to see the beauty in everything. It can get a bit annoying, but I genuinely find a lot of

02:31:31.100 --> 02:31:35.980
[Guest]: things beautiful. I mean, part of that comes from I think science. I mean, Richard Feynman was a

02:31:35.980 --> 02:31:43.740
[Guest]: huge influence on me when I was growing up. And the way he sees beauty in the smallest of

02:31:43.740 --> 02:31:49.180
[Guest]: phenomenon, I mean, the world is an incredibly fascinating and beautiful place. And it is that

02:31:49.180 --> 02:31:56.380
[Guest]: sort of enthusiasm for the world which I wish to transmit through my writing. And that is what I

02:31:56.380 --> 02:32:00.620
[Amit Varma]: believe the purpose of travel writing is. Great. So I've taken a lot of your time today. So I'll

02:32:00.620 --> 02:32:05.820
[Amit Varma]: kind of end with a final question. And at one point early in the book, you talk about this

02:32:05.820 --> 02:32:10.620
[Amit Varma]: truck driver Shyam, and you're sort of traveling with him. And he says he likes Kishore Kumar.

02:32:10.620 --> 02:32:15.660
[Amit Varma]: And you ask him his favorite song. And he, you know, names a song and then you ask him to sing,

02:32:15.660 --> 02:32:19.660
[Amit Varma]: he sings a bit of that, and then he feels embarrassed feeling that he's revealed a bit of

02:32:19.660 --> 02:32:23.660
[Amit Varma]: himself to you. And the lyrics of that lovely song, of course, are, quote,

02:32:23.660 --> 02:32:30.300
[Amit Varma]: Jeevan ke safar mera hi milte hai bichhar jaane ko, aur de jaate hai yaade, tanhai mein tarpaane ko.

02:32:30.300 --> 02:32:35.180
[Amit Varma]: And this sort of seems to me to summarize so well, that, you know, the loneliness of the

02:32:35.180 --> 02:32:40.140
[Amit Varma]: long distance trucker as we spoke about. But is this something that you felt at the end of the

02:32:40.140 --> 02:32:45.020
[Amit Varma]: book that, you know, was there the sense of loss that, you know, these are all people who at

02:32:45.020 --> 02:32:49.740
[Amit Varma]: different levels, you must have been close to, like, are you in touch with them? Have you sent

02:32:49.740 --> 02:32:53.980
[Amit Varma]: your book to any of them? You've mentioned that, you know, after all the writing was done, you were

02:32:53.980 --> 02:32:58.380
[Amit Varma]: still what's happening with them and all of that. What is that relationship like? And also, it must

02:32:58.380 --> 02:33:03.820
[Amit Varma]: be a complicated one, because at one level, they were instrumental to you in the sense that you

02:33:03.820 --> 02:33:09.100
[Amit Varma]: were using them to go on a journey and write a book. But at the other level, you have been upfront

02:33:09.100 --> 02:33:13.740
[Amit Varma]: about what you want, and they know that. And then on the basis of that, your relationship is

02:33:13.740 --> 02:33:19.100
[Amit Varma]: a kind of building and there is a lot of warmth there. And, you know, one gets a sense of those

02:33:19.100 --> 02:33:24.780
[Amit Varma]: little little intimacies that are scattered through the book. So what is it like now when you

02:33:24.780 --> 02:33:30.380
[Amit Varma]: think of them and also having so many different friends who are not from the earlier bubbles,

02:33:30.380 --> 02:33:35.580
[Amit Varma]: you were part of like engineering or journalism or whatever, does it change the way you look at

02:33:35.580 --> 02:33:40.460
[Amit Varma]: people in general, like people who are unseen to us in a way, you know, maybe the beggar at the

02:33:40.460 --> 02:33:45.420
[Amit Varma]: traffic signal or the person serving chai at the dhaba we go to, do you feel you kind of look at

02:33:45.420 --> 02:33:51.740
[Amit Varma]: them differently and that your gaze has been impacted by these experiences? So as far as

02:33:51.740 --> 02:33:57.820
[Guest]: them being instrumental, I wouldn't go as far to say that because you know, when I set out on the

02:33:57.820 --> 02:34:05.180
[Guest]: trip, I had no idea I mean, this book was ever going to come out, or I'm even going to write one,

02:34:05.180 --> 02:34:12.780
[Guest]: I did it mainly to have some fun and make some friends along the way. So I mean, I did take notes

02:34:12.780 --> 02:34:17.900
[Guest]: and all in case it comes handy someday, but that possibility seemed remote to me because

02:34:19.020 --> 02:34:23.180
[Guest]: what I was thinking at that point was, who's going to read about it? I mean,

02:34:23.180 --> 02:34:28.460
[Guest]: while I was interested in it, but often there's this niggling doubt, right? Is this something

02:34:28.460 --> 02:34:33.500
[Guest]: that's interesting for the wider world? And that self doubt is something that eats you away in many

02:34:33.500 --> 02:34:41.740
[Guest]: ways. So that was how so we used to hang out like just like someone who I met and who are going to

02:34:41.740 --> 02:34:48.700
[Guest]: be separated in some time. So you speak all that you can in that in that particular time. Over the

02:34:48.700 --> 02:34:53.180
[Guest]: years, I have fallen out of touch also with them. Because what happens with truckers, especially,

02:34:53.180 --> 02:34:58.300
[Guest]: you know, they change so many phone numbers, they keep changing their phone numbers. I don't know

02:34:58.300 --> 02:35:04.300
[Guest]: why. And if they change their boss, they start working for a different owner, then their number

02:35:04.300 --> 02:35:10.220
[Guest]: will change. And they're constantly on the move, right? It's incredibly difficult to talk to them

02:35:10.220 --> 02:35:14.780
[Guest]: on the phone, because they are always busy. They're either driving on the road and it's

02:35:14.780 --> 02:35:19.580
[Guest]: incomprehensible on the phone, you know, when you try to talk. So all these factors made it

02:35:19.580 --> 02:35:25.180
[Guest]: very difficult to keep in touch. Jora and Jagdev were two people who I did keep in touch with.

02:35:25.180 --> 02:35:31.580
[Guest]: I've also sent them a copy of my book. So hopefully they like it. Because I don't think

02:35:31.580 --> 02:35:36.380
[Guest]: they can read English. My next plan is to somehow get this translated to Hindi or Punjabi.

02:35:37.420 --> 02:35:44.060
[Guest]: Because there is so much readership for these two, these kind of stories from the

02:35:44.060 --> 02:35:49.660
[Guest]: internet. And even you don't even need to change the title of the book. The title of the book

02:35:49.660 --> 02:35:57.420
[Guest]: remains the same. I hope to get it translated soon. And yeah, I mean, how I see the wider world,

02:35:57.420 --> 02:36:04.540
[Guest]: I think has remained the same. I mean, I've always been curious about the underclass,

02:36:04.540 --> 02:36:11.740
[Guest]: about someone who we don't ordinarily meet in our circles and so on. So that part has remained the

02:36:11.740 --> 02:36:18.060
[Guest]: same. Though my understanding of the world of truckers definitely has improved. But the way

02:36:18.060 --> 02:36:22.380
[Guest]: I view the larger world, I think has probably remained the same, which is something that

02:36:22.380 --> 02:36:27.580
[Amit Varma]: motivated me to go on this trip in the first place. And finally, are you writing something

02:36:27.580 --> 02:36:33.340
[Amit Varma]: now? Is there something your devoted readers such as myself can expect from you? Are you taking one

02:36:33.340 --> 02:36:38.860
[Amit Varma]: for the team in one way or another so that we can read a great book? Yeah, I am working on my

02:36:38.860 --> 02:36:46.540
[Guest]: second travel book. So I have signed something with HarperCollins. And it should come out in

02:36:46.540 --> 02:36:52.700
[Guest]: the next couple of years. Quite excited. It's another. I'm going to explore another class of

02:36:52.700 --> 02:36:58.540
[Guest]: itinerants who we don't get to read much about. But it's all going to be about the ordinary people

02:36:58.540 --> 02:37:05.100
[Guest]: of India, and their relationship with the world with God and all these things. So it's quite

02:37:05.100 --> 02:37:09.900
[Guest]: excited about it. And yeah, hopefully the readers will like you will enjoy it.

02:37:10.700 --> 02:37:15.020
[Amit Varma]: Sounds fascinating. And I can't wait. I'll, I won't take any more of your time because I want

02:37:15.020 --> 02:37:19.420
[Amit Varma]: you to get back to writing that book, which I'm so eager to read. Rajat, thank you so much for

02:37:19.420 --> 02:37:24.380
[Amit Varma]: your time and your insights. And you know, having the patience to sit through all these technical

02:37:24.380 --> 02:37:28.780
[Amit Varma]: difficulties as we record this episode. I appreciate that. Thank you so much, Amit.

02:37:28.780 --> 02:37:30.460
[Guest]: Entirely my pleasure. Thank you.

